## PREFACE (pp. 1-6)

- Book is about huge differences in incomes/living standards between rich and poor countries
- Written during Arab Spring — Mohamed Bouazizi self-immolation Dec 17, 2010 sparked revolution
- Ben Ali (Tunisia, ruled since 1987) ousted Jan 14, 2011; Mubarak (Egypt, ~30 years) ousted Feb 11, 2011
- Average Egyptian income: ~12% of average American; life expectancy 10 years shorter; 20% in dire poverty
- Egyptian protestors (Noha Hamed, Mosaab El Shami, Wael Khalil) all focused on POLITICAL change first — corruption, oppression, lack of political rights
- Mohamed ElBaradei tweet: "Tunisia: repression + absence of social justice + denial of channels for peaceful change = a ticking bomb"
- Three conventional explanations for poverty rejected:
  1. Geography (desert, climate) — but Nogales disproves this
  2. Culture (work ethic, Islamic beliefs) — but shared culture across border
  3. Ignorance (leaders don't know right policies) — but elites CHOOSE bad policies for self-enrichment
- Authors' thesis: Egypt is poor because ruled by narrow elite organizing society for own benefit at expense of masses. Political power narrowly concentrated, used to create wealth for those who hold it (Mubarak's $70B fortune)
- This applies universally: North Korea, Sierra Leone, Zimbabwe all poor for same reason as Egypt
- Rich countries (Britain, US) became rich because citizens overthrew elites controlling power, created society with broadly distributed political rights, accountable government, economic opportunity for masses
- Key insight: Britain richer than Egypt because of 1688 revolution that transformed politics → economics → Industrial Revolution
- Industrial Revolution didn't spread to Egypt because Ottoman Empire (then British colonialism) treated Egypt same as Mubarak later did
- Egypt's 1952 revolution overthrew monarchy but brought another extractive elite to power — basic structure unchanged
- Past revolutions in Egypt failed because revolutionaries simply replaced old elites, re-created similar system
- For change: need broad political transformation, as in England 1688, France 1789, Japan, Botswana, Brazil

## CHAPTER 1: SO CLOSE AND YET SO DIFFERENT (pp. 7-18)

### The Economics of the Rio Grande
- Nogales divided by a fence — Arizona side vs Sonora side
- Nogales, AZ (Santa Cruz County): $30K household income, most teens in school, majority adults are HS graduates, relatively healthy population with high life expectancy, Medicare access, electricity/phones/sewage/roads, law and order, democracy is "second nature"
- Nogales, Sonora: income ~1/3 of Arizona side, most adults lack HS degree, many teens not in school, high infant mortality, shorter life expectancy, poor public health, bad roads, high crime, business is risky (robbery, bribes), corruption and ineptitude daily reality
- Until 2000 reforms, Sonora under corrupt PRI (Partido Revolucionario Institucional) control
- Same geography, climate, disease environment, ethnic background, culture, food, music
- Area was unified until Gadsden Purchase of 1853 — Lt. N. Michler noted "pretty little valley of Los Nogales"
- The BORDER defines the difference — different institutions of the United States vs Mexico
- US institutions: choose occupations freely, acquire schooling/skills, employers invest in technology, political participation, accountable government, basic services
- Mexico institutions: disparate incentives, less investment, less opportunity
- WHY different institutions? Traces to early colonial period — institutional divergence then with lasting implications

### The Founding of Buenos Aires (pp. 21-23)
- 1516: Spanish navigator Juan Díaz de Solís sailed into wide estuary on Eastern Seaboard of South America, named it Río de la Plata ("River of Silver")
- Indigenous peoples (Charrúas in Uruguay, Querandí on Argentine Pampas) were hostile hunter-gatherers without centralized political authorities
- Charrúas clubbed de Solís to death as he explored
- 1534: Pedro de Mendoza led first mission of settlers, founded Buenos Aires — temperate climate, "good airs"
- BUT: Charrúas and Querandí refused to provide food or labor, attacked settlement. No silver or gold locally (silver came from Inca Andes far west). Spaniards went hungry.
- 1537: Juan de Ayolas expedition went up Paraná River, found the Guaraní — sedentary agricultural people (maize/cassava). Completely different from Charrúas/Querandí
- Spanish overcame Guaraní resistance, founded Nuestra Señora de Santa María de la Asunción (today's Asunción, Paraguay)
- Conquistadors married Guaraní princesses, set themselves up as new aristocracy, adapted existing forced labor and tribute systems
- Within four years Buenos Aires abandoned — all Spaniards moved to Asunción
- Buenos Aires not resettled until 1580 — ironic given it became "Paris of South America"
- KEY LESSON: Colonists not interested in tilling soil themselves; wanted others to do it, plus gold/silver to plunder

### From Cajamarca... (pp. 23-28)
- Columbus sighted Bahamas Oct 12, 1492; Spanish colonization began in earnest with Cortés invading Mexico 1519, Pizarro to Peru a decade later, Mendoza to Río de la Plata
- Over next century Spain conquered most of central, western, and southern South America; Portugal claimed Brazil

#### The Spanish Colonization Strategy (perfected by Cortés):
1. Capture the indigenous leader
2. Claim accumulated wealth of the leader
3. Coerce indigenous peoples to give tribute and food
4. Set themselves up as new elite, taking control of existing taxation/tribute/forced labor

#### Cortés and the Aztecs:
- Nov 8, 1519: Cortés arrived at Tenochtitlan, welcomed by Moctezuma
- Account from Franciscan priest Bernardino de Sahagún's Florentine Codices (compiled after 1545):
  - Spanish seized Moctezuma, guns fired, "Fear prevailed. It was as if everyone had swallowed his heart"
  - Spanish demanded white tortillas, turkey hens, eggs, fresh water, wood, firewood, charcoal
  - Inquired about city's treasure, sought gold with "great zeal"
  - At storehouse Teocalco: took quetzal feather head fans, golden discs, golden nose crescents, leg/arm bands
  - "They took it all"
  - Detached gold, set fire to precious things, melted gold into bars
- Military conquest of Aztecs completed by 1521

#### The Encomienda System:
- Cortés as governor of New Spain divided indigenous population through *encomienda*
- Origin: 15th-century Spain, reconquest from Moors/Arabs
- New World version far more pernicious: grant of indigenous peoples to a Spaniard (*encomendero*)
- Indigenous had to give tribute and labor services; encomendero supposedly converting them to Christianity
- Bartolomé de las Casas: Dominican priest, arrived Hispaniola 1502, became critic of Spanish colonialism
  - Participated in conquest of Cuba 1513, granted encomienda, then renounced it
  - Wrote *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies* (1542)
  - His account of encomienda in Nicaragua: settlers took residence in allotted towns, stole foodstuffs, took over native lands, treated entire population as household members, forced labor "night and day... without any rest whatsoever"
  - In New Granada (Colombia): Spanish seized King Bogotá, held him prisoner 6-7 months demanding gold/emeralds, tortured him with strappado, burning tallow, iron hoops — king eventually died from torture

#### Pizarro and the Incas:
- De las Casas: "In 1531 another great villain journeyed with a number of men to the kingdom of Peru"
- Pizarro started at coast near Tumbes, marched south
- Nov 15, 1532: reached Cajamarca where Inca emperor Atahualpa was encamped (had just defeated brother Huáscar in succession contest after father Huayna Capac's death)
- Spanish laid trap: killed guards/retainers (~2,000 people), captured Atahualpa
- Ransom: fill one room with gold, two more with silver. He did it. Spanish strangled him July 1533
- That November: captured Inca capital Cusco. Incan aristocracy imprisoned until they produced gold/silver; burned alive if they didn't satisfy demands
- Artistic treasures of Cusco, Temple of the Sun stripped and melted

#### The Mita System (pp. 27-28):
- After encomienda, Spain divided Inca people into encomiendas under each conquistador
- 1545: Diego Gualpa discovered massive silver at Cerro Rico ("The Rich Hill") in modern Bolivia
- City of Potosí grew around it — population 160,000 by 1650 (larger than Lisbon or Venice)
- Viceroy Francisco de Toledo arrived Peru 1569, spent five years investigating
- Commissioned massive survey of entire adult population
- Moved indigenous population into new towns called *reducciones* ("reductions") to facilitate labor exploitation
- Revived Inca institution *mita* (Quechua for "a turn"): under Incas, forced labor for temples, aristocracy, army — in return Inca elite provided famine relief/security
- De Toledo's Potosí mita: most onerous scheme of labor exploitation in colonial period
- Catchment area: middle of Peru through most of Bolivia, ~200,000 square miles
- One-seventh of male inhabitants required to work in Potosí mines
- Mita endured throughout colonial period, abolished only in 1825
- De Toledo also consolidated encomienda into head tax (fixed sum per adult male in silver) — designed to force people into labor market
- *Repartimiento de mercancias*: forced sale of goods to locals at Spanish-determined prices
- *Trajin* ("the burden"): used indigenous people as pack animals to carry wine, coca, textiles

#### Legacy of Mita Visible Today (pp. 29-30):
- Provinces of Calca vs Acomayo near Cusco: both mountainous, Quechua-speaking descendants of Incas
- Acomayo much poorer — inhabitants consume ~one-third less than Calca
- People in Acomayo know and say: "Don't you know the people here are poorer than people in Calca?"
- Road to Calca is surfaced; road to Acomayo in terrible disrepair (need horse or mule)
- Calca: sell crops on market for money. Acomayo: grow food for subsistence
- KEY DIFFERENCE: Acomayo was in Potosí mita catchment area; Calca was not
- Institutional roots trace directly to de Toledo's exploitation plan

### ...to Jamestown (pp. 30-36)
- As Spanish conquered Americas in 1490s, England was minor power recovering from Wars of the Roses
- 1588: defeat of Spanish Armada — sign of growing English assertiveness at sea
- English colonized North America as latecomers — not because it was attractive but because "desirable" parts (dense populations, gold/silver) already taken by Spain
- Arthur Young (18th-century writer) noted colonies' staple production value decreased with distance from equator: West Indies hottest = 8l. 12s. 1d. per head; northern settlements = 2s. 6d.

#### Jamestown Founded:
- First attempt: Roanoke, North Carolina (1585, 1587) — complete failure
- 1607: three vessels (*Susan Constant*, *Godspeed*, *Discovery*) under Captain Christopher Newport, for Virginia Company
- May 14, 1607: founded Jamestown up the James River (named after King James I)
- Colonists' model: influenced by Cortés, Pizarro, de Toledo — capture local chief, coerce population
- Landed within Powhatan Confederacy (~30 polities under King Wahunsunacock), capital at Werowocomoco, 20 miles from Jamestown
- Unlike Aztecs/Incas, Wahunsunacock lacked overwhelming centralized political control

#### Captain John Smith:
- Born in rural Lincolnshire, England; soldier of fortune — fought in Netherlands, Hungary, captured in Romania, sold as slave, escaped
- Imprisoned on voyage for mutiny; Virginia Company's sealed orders named him to ruling council
- Winter 1607: colony leader Edward Marie Wingfield dithered; Smith saved colony through trading missions
- Captured by Opechancanough (Wahunsunacock's younger brother), brought before king at Werowocomoco
- According to some accounts, life saved by Pocahontas (Wahunsunacock's young daughter)
- Freed Jan 2, 1608; Newport returned same day with supplies
- Smith first to realize Cortés/Pizarro model wouldn't work in Virginia — no gold, people couldn't be forced
- Quote from Smith's diary: "Victuals you must know is all their wealth"
- Anas Todkill (early settler diary): "There was no talke, no hope, no worke, but dig gold, refine gold, load gold"
- April 1608: Newport sailed with cargo of pyrite (fool's gold)
- Sept 1608: Newport returned with orders to crown Wahunsunacock (make him subservient to James I)
- Wahunsunacock's reply: "If your King have sent me presents, I also am a King, and this is my land... Your father is to come to me, not I to him, nor yet to your fort, neither will I bite at such a bait."
- Coronation attempt was "complete fiasco" — Wahunsunacock imposed trade embargo
- Dec 1608: Newport sailed again with Smith's letter pleading Virginia Company to change approach
- Smith's plea: "send some thirty carpenters, husbandmen, gardeners, fishermen, blacksmiths, masons" — not more "useless goldsmiths"
- Smith imposed rule: "he that will not worke shall not eat" — Jamestown survived second winter

#### Virginia Company's Institutional Evolution (pp. 34-36):
- After two disastrous years with no profit, Virginia Company replaced ruling council with single governor: Sir Thomas Gates
- Winter 1609/1610: "starving time" — Smith left autumn 1609, Wahunsunacock throttled food. Of 500 entering winter, only 60 alive by March. Resorted to cannibalism
- Gates and deputy Sir Thomas Dale imposed "Lawes Divine, Morall and Martiall":
  - No running away to Indians, upon pain of death
  - Robbing a garden = death
  - No selling any commodity to captains/mariners for private use = death
- New model: Virginia Company owned all land, men in barracks, company rations, work gangs with overseers, execution as first resort
- BUT colonists could run away — to Indians or to frontier. Low population density = couldn't coerce English settlers either
- Population density comparison (Map 2): US at most 3/4 person per sq mile; central Mexico/Andean Peru = 400+ per sq mile — 500x higher
- Starting 1618: dramatically new strategy adopted
  - "Headright system": 50 acres per male settler + 50 more for each family member/servant brought
  - Settlers given their own houses, freed from contracts
  - 1619: General Assembly introduced — all adult men got say in laws/institutions governing colony
  - "It was the start of democracy in the United States"
- Virginia Company took 12 years to learn: what worked for Spanish in Mexico/Peru wouldn't work in the north
- Rest of 17th century: struggles over second lesson — only viable option was giving colonists incentives

#### Attempts to Create Extractive Institutions in North America (pp. 36-38):
- English elites repeatedly tried to restrict economic/political rights — each attempt failed
- 1632: Lord Baltimore (Cecilius Calvert) granted 10 million acres on upper Chesapeake Bay by Charles I
  - Charter gave "free, full, and absolute Power" to create government
  - Drew up plan for manorial society: plots of thousands of acres run by lords, tenants working land and paying rents
- 1663: founding of Carolina by eight proprietors including Sir Anthony Ashley-Cooper
  - Secretary: John Locke (the philosopher!)
  - Formulated "Fundamental Constitutions of Carolina"
  - Blueprint for elitist, hierarchical society: "we may avoid erecting a numerous democracy"
  - Bottom: "leet-men" (hereditary serfs, clause 23: "All children of leet-men shall be leet-men, and so to all generations")
  - Above: landgraves (48,000 acres each) and caziques (24,000 acres each) forming aristocracy
  - Parliament: only landgraves and caziques represented; could only debate measures pre-approved by proprietors
- All these plans FAILED: impossible to force settlers into rigid hierarchy when they had too many options (frontier, other colonies)
- Settlers demanded economic freedom, further political rights
- Maryland: settlers insisted on own land, forced Lord Baltimore to create assembly. 1691: assembly induced king to declare Maryland a Crown colony
- Carolinas: similar struggle, proprietors lost. South Carolina became royal colony 1729
- By 1720s: all thirteen colonies had similar structures — governor + assembly based on male property holder franchise
- Not full democracies (women, slaves, propertyless excluded) but political rights very broad compared to contemporary societies
- These assemblies + leaders formed First Continental Congress in 1774 — prelude to independence

### A Tale of Two Constitutions (pp. 41-45)
- US Constitution (Philadelphia, May 1787) was outcome of long process beginning with 1619 General Assembly in Jamestown
- Contrast with Mexico's independence process is stark

#### Mexico's Path to Independence:
- Feb 1808: Napoleon invaded Spain. By May, took Madrid. By September, King Ferdinand captured and abdicated
- Junta Central formed, retreated to Cádiz. In 1812 Cortes produced Cádiz Constitution — constitutional monarchy, popular sovereignty, end of special privileges, equality before law
- These demands were anathema to South American elites who ruled through encomienda, forced labor, absolute power
- Napoleonic collapse created constitutional crisis throughout colonial Latin America — local juntas formed
- First independence declaration: La Paz, Bolivia, 1809 — quickly crushed by Spanish troops from Peru
- 1810 Hidalgo Revolt in Mexico: Father Miguel Hidalgo's army sacked Guanajuato, killed intendant and white people indiscriminately — more like class/ethnic warfare than independence movement
- This united ALL elites against popular participation — Mexican elites viewed Cádiz Constitution with extreme skepticism
- 1815: Napoleon fell, Ferdinand VII returned, abrogated Cádiz Constitution
- 1820: Spanish army assembling in Cádiz to reclaim colonies mutinied against Ferdinand, forced restoration of Cádiz Constitution
- New Cortes even more radical — proposed abolishing all forced labor, attacking military's right to own courts
- Mexican elites decided: better to go it alone than accept this radical constitution
- Feb 24, 1821: Augustín de Iturbide published Plan de Iguala — constitutional monarchy with Mexican emperor, removing threatening Cádiz provisions
- Iturbide declared himself emperor; Simón Bolívar described position as "by the grace of God and of bayonets"
- By Oct 1822: Iturbide dismissed congress, replaced with his own junta — pattern repeated throughout 19th-century Mexico

#### Antonio López de Santa Ana:
- Son of colonial official in Veracruz, rose as soldier in independence wars
- 1821: switched sides to Iturbide, never looked back
- First became president May 1833 but exercised power less than a month
- Let Valentín Gómez Farías act as president — lasted 15 days before Santa Ana retook power
- Between 1824-1867: FIFTY-TWO presidents in Mexico, few constitutionally sanctioned
- Santa Ana president eleven times (1833, 1839, 1841, 1844, 1847, 1853-1855)
- Lost Texas, Alamo, presided over disastrous Mexican-American War (lost New Mexico, Arizona)
- Consequence: insecure property rights, weak Mexican state, little ability to raise taxes or provide services
- Independence motivation was to PROTECT colonial extractive institutions from reform
- Alexander von Humboldt called Mexico "the country of inequality"
- As US experienced Industrial Revolution, Mexico got poorer

### Having an Idea, Starting a Firm, and Getting a Loan (pp. 45-48)
- Industrial Revolution started in England — cotton cloth production mechanized (water wheels, then steam)
- Innovation spearheaded by new entrepreneurs, spread across North Atlantic to US
- Patent system systematized in Statute of Monopolies (English Parliament, 1623) — to stop king granting arbitrary "letters patent"
- KEY FINDING: Between 1820-1845, only 19% of US patentees had parents who were professionals or from recognized landowning families
- 40% of patentees had only primary schooling or less (like Edison)
- Thomas Edison: last of 7 children, father did many occupations, homeschooled by mother
  - Founded General Electric; world-record 1,093 US patents, 1,500 worldwide
  - Early on sold Quadruplex telegraph patent to Western Union for $10,000
- US was more democratic politically AND economically than any other nation — critical to becoming most innovative nation

#### Banking: US vs Mexico:
- US: 1818 had 338 banks/$160M assets; by 1914 had 27,864 banks/$27.3B assets — intense competition, low rates
- Mexico (1910): only 42 banks, TWO controlled 60% of total banking assets — no competition, high rates, lending to privileged only
- After Santa Ana: French installed Emperor Maximilian (1864-1867), then expelled; Benito Juárez formed government
- After Juárez's death: Porfirio Díaz (victorious general vs French) won Battle of Tecoac (Nov 1876), elected president, ruled ~34 years
- Key contrast: US generals (Washington, Grant, Eisenhower) abided by Constitution; Mexican strongmen only removed by force
- Díaz violated property rights, expropriated land, granted monopolies to supporters including banking
- US also initially developed banking monopolies — state politicians gave friends monopoly charters
- BUT US politicians subject to election/reelection — citizens could check and remove them
- Banking monopolies crumbled in US; broad political rights guaranteed equal access to finance

### Path-Dependent Change (pp. 49-52)
- 1870s-80s: globalization via steamship/railway expanded international trade
- Díaz's changes were "path-dependent" — next stage of same extractive institutions, not transformation
- In US: Land Ordinance of 1785 through Homestead Act of 1862 gave broad access to frontier
- In Latin America: frontier lands allocated to politically powerful, making them more powerful
- Yaqui people of Sonora: 1900-1910 possibly 30,000 deported, enslaved on henequen plantations of Yucatán
- Díaz overthrown 1910; revolutions followed in Bolivia (1952), Cuba (1959), Nicaragua (1979)
- Mass repression: Chile (2,279 killed under Pinochet 1973-90; 50,000 tortured); Guatemala (up to 200,000 murdered 1962-96); Argentina (9,000-30,000 "disappeared" 1976-83)

### Making a Billion or Two (pp. 52-56)
- Bill Gates vs Carlos Slim: both world's richest, but made wealth in completely different ways
- Gates/Microsoft: innovation-based but faced DOJ antitrust (May 1998), FTC inquiry (1991), deal Nov 2001
- Carlos Slim: stock market deals, buying/revamping unprofitable firms
  - Major coup: Telmex (telecom monopoly privatized by President Carlos Salinas 1990)
  - Govt sold 51% voting stock (20.4% total); Slim's Grupo Corso consortium won despite not highest bid
  - Delayed payment using Telmex's own dividends — public monopoly became private monopoly
- *Recurso de amparo* ("appeal for protection"): petition arguing law doesn't apply to you
  - Dates to Mexican constitution of 1857; originally for individual rights
  - In Telmex's hands: tool for cementing monopoly power
- Slim in US: 1999 bought CompUSA, violated contract with COC Services, sued in Dallas — lost, fined $454M
  - Lawyer Mark Werner: "firms have to respect the rules of the United States if they want to come here"

### Toward a Theory of World Inequality (pp. 56-60)
- Nogales, Sonora prosperity (~$5K avg income) comes from maquiladora plants — all US-based (Memorex, Samsonite, etc.)
- US citizen 7x as prosperous as Mexican, 10x+ vs Peru/Central America, 20x vs sub-Saharan Africa, 40x vs Mali/Ethiopia
- Rankings remarkably stable going back 50, 100, 150 years
- Core framework: economic institutions shape incentives; political institutions determine economic institutions
- Political institutions = not just constitutions but power/capacity of state + distribution of political power
- Those who control politics may prefer extractive institutions — no consensus needed for change
- Book thesis: "the economics of poverty and prosperity" AND "the politics of poverty and prosperity"

## CHAPTER 2: THEORIES THAT DON'T WORK (pp. 60-)

### The Lay of the Land (pp. 60-62)
- First sustained growth: England/Britain after 1707; Industrial Revolution in second half of 18th century
- Spread to Western Europe, US, settler colonies (Canada, Australia, New Zealand), then Japan, Singapore, South Korea, Taiwan, China
- Bottom 30: almost all sub-Saharan Africa plus Afghanistan, Haiti, Nepal
- Map 3 (2008): darkest = GDP/capita <$2K; white = $20K+
- Americas ranking persistent for 150+ years: US/Canada → Chile/Argentina/Brazil/Mexico → Colombia/DR/Ecuador/Peru → Bolivia/Guatemala/Paraguay
- Middle East: oil-rich (Saudi/Kuwait) near top 30 but would fall without oil; non-oil (Egypt/Jordan/Syria) cluster with Guatemala/Peru
- Patterns not immutable: most of current inequality emerged since late 18th century; Americas ranking 500 years ago was completely different
- Some nations grew rapidly then reversed: Argentina (grew until 1920), Soviet Union (1930-1970)

### The Geography Hypothesis (pp. 63-70)
- Poor countries between tropics of Cancer and Capricorn; rich nations in temperate latitudes
- Montesquieu (late 18th c): tropical people lazy, lack inquisitiveness, tend to be ruled by despots
- Modern version (Jeffrey Sachs): tropical diseases (malaria) harm labor productivity; tropical soils unproductive
- REFUTED by Nogales (same climate both sides), North/South Korea, East/West Germany
- Historical reversal: at time of Columbus, tropical Americas (Aztec, Inca) were RICHER than temperate zones (US/Canada = Stone Age). Aztecs had money/writing; Incas used knotted-rope quipus
- Reversal not confined to Americas: South/SE Asia more prosperous than Australia/New Zealand before colonization; now reversed. Within Africa, pre-contact southern Africa was least developed — now most prosperous
- Great premodern tropical civilizations: Angkor (Cambodia), Vijayanagara (India), Aksum (Ethiopia), Indus Valley (Mohenjo Daro, Harappa)
- Tropical diseases: consequence of poverty (govts unable/unwilling to invest in public health), not cause. England was unhealthy in 19th c. but invested in clean water/sewage/health services
- Low agricultural productivity in poor countries: due to ownership structure and incentive problems, NOT soil quality. Modern inequality caused by uneven dissemination of industrial technologies, not agricultural divergence

#### Critique of Jared Diamond's Thesis:
- Diamond (*Guns, Germs, and Steel*): intercontinental inequality from different endowments of domesticable plant/animal species → Fertile Crescent farmed earlier → density/specialization/innovation
- Powerful for explaining WHY Spanish conquered Incas — but can't explain modern inequality
- After exposure to all species/technologies, Incas should have caught up — they didn't. Gap GREW (Spaniard now 6x richer than Peruvian)
- Nogales: in 1532 Peru/Mexico richer than US/Canada. North America became richer by adopting Industrial Revolution; South America didn't. Geographic endowments favored South America
- Diamond's east-west Eurasian orientation (following William McNeill): enabled crop/animal/innovation spread. But Sahara didn't permanently block sub-Saharan Africa — Portuguese arrived 15th c., income gaps were small then, have GROWN since
- Can't explain variation WITHIN continents (England vs Moldova; Argentina vs Bolivia)
- Maps 4-5: Sus scrofa (pig ancestor) and aurochs (cow ancestor) widely distributed across Eurasia/North Africa; wild rice, wheat, barley ancestors spread from Levant to Central Asian "stans" — wide distribution means species availability can't explain Eurasian inequality
- Middle East: led Neolithic Revolution, first towns (Iraq), iron smelted in Turkey, dynamic through Middle Ages — Ottoman Empire expansion (not geography) made it poor

### The Culture Hypothesis (pp. 72-78)
- Max Weber: Protestant ethic key to rise of modern industrial society
- Modern versions: Africans lack work ethic/believe in witchcraft; Latin America suffers "Iberian" or "mañana" culture; Chinese/Confucian values once thought inimical to growth, now credited for it
- Social norms matter and can support institutional differences — "yes and no"
- BUT religion, national ethics, African/Latin values NOT important for understanding inequality
- Trust/cooperation: important but mostly OUTCOME of institutions, not independent cause
- Nogales: same culture both sides. Mexicans trust less in surveys — natural when govt can't eliminate drug cartels or provide unbiased legal system
- North/South Korea: common history, unprecedented cultural homogeneity before division at 38th parallel. Different "culture" today is consequence, not cause
- Kingdom of Kongo example (pp. 75-76):
  - Portuguese visited 1483; Kongo highly centralized; capital Mbanza = 60,000 people (same as Lisbon, larger than London ~50,000 in 1500)
  - King Nzinga a Nkuwu converted to Catholicism (took name João I); Mbanza renamed São Salvador
  - Portuguese agricultural missions 1491/1512 encouraged wheel/plow adoption — ALL failed
  - BUT Kongolese quickly adopted GUNS to capture/export slaves (market incentives)
  - Also adopted literacy, dress styles, house designs
  - Real reason no wheel/plow: no incentives. High expropriation risk from king; could be enslaved. King preferred slave exports over agricultural productivity
- In 19th c. many African societies DID respond to Industrial Revolution opportunities (palm oil, groundnuts in West Africa; exports to Rand mines in South Africa) — obliterated by European colonialism then postindependence govts
- Low African trust: outcome of institutions undermining human/property rights historically
- Weber's Protestant ethic: Catholic France quickly mimicked Netherlands/England; Italy equally prosperous; East Asian successes have nothing to do with Christianity
- Islamic poverty argument: spurious. Syria/Egypt poor because Ottoman Empire provinces → English/French colonies → hierarchical authoritarian regimes post-independence. Egypt under Muhammad Ali (1805-1848) temporarily broke free and DID grow — modernized state/bureaucracy/army/tax, agricultural/industrial growth — ended when Egypt fell under European influence after Ali's death
- "English" culture: US/Canada/Australia were English colonies but so were Sierra Leone/Nigeria. Variation within former English colonies as great as entire world
- "European" culture: Argentina/Uruguay more European descent than US/Canada but economic performance "leaves much to be desired." Japan/Singapore prospered without Europeans
- China: poverty until Mao's death due to disastrous policies (Great Leap Forward 1950s → famine; Cultural Revolution 1960s → persecution), not Chinese culture. Growth from Deng Xiaoping's reforms
- "Hispanic" culture can't explain why Argentina/Chile more prosperous than Peru/Bolivia
- Indigenous culture argument: Colombia/Ecuador/Peru have similar incomes but Colombia has very few indigenous people

### The Ignorance Hypothesis (pp. 79-80)
- Most popular among economists: inequality exists because rulers don't know how to make countries rich
- Based on Lionel Robbins (1935) definition of economics as study of scarce means with alternative uses
- First Welfare Theorem: identifies when market allocation is socially desirable; when conditions not met = "market failure"
- Ignorance hypothesis: poor countries have many market failures + economists/policymakers don't know how to fix them
- Ghana example: Kwame Nkrumah's post-independence decline — NOT caused by ignorance
  - British economist Tony Killick advised Nkrumah, recorded absurd projects:
  - Footwear factory in North, hides transported 500+ miles to Southern tannery (abandoned), leather 200 miles to Kumasi factory, shoes 200 miles to Accra market
  - Mango canning plant in area where mangos don't grow, output exceeding entire world demand
  - Killick: enterprise "whose viability was undermined by poor siting"
  - Nkrumah had good advisers — he CHOSE bad policies for political reasons
- Nkrumah advised by Nobel laureate Sir Arthur Lewis — knew policies were bad but needed them for political support
- If ignorance were the problem, leaders would quickly learn and gravitate toward good policies
- US vs Mexico: NOT differences in knowledge — Díaz CHOSE institutions enriching elites because of institutional constraints
- Ghana PM Kofi Busia (1969-71): opponent of Nkrumah, led democratic govt but faced same constraints
  - Price controls were good politics (cheap food for urban constituencies) even though bad economics
  - Dec 27, 1971: signed IMF agreement with massive devaluation — knew the political gamble
  - Result: rioting in Accra, military coup by Lt. Col. Acheampong who reversed devaluation
- China's reform: NOT because CCP finally understood collective ownership was bad — Deng Xiaoping defeated opponents within party, masterminded political revolution. "It was politics, not better advice"
- "They get it wrong not by mistake or ignorance but on purpose"
- Abba Lerner (1970s): "Economics has gained the title Queen of the Social Sciences by choosing solved political problems as its domain"

## CHAPTER 3: THE MAKING OF PROSPERITY AND POVERTY (pp. 85-)

### The Economics of the 38th Parallel (pp. 85-88)
- Summer 1945: Japan's colony in Korea collapsed. Korea divided at 38th parallel (South = US, North = Russia)
- June 1950: North invaded South, Korean War began
- Hwang Pyŏng-Wŏn and brother: separated 1950, reunited 2000 through family reunification program
  - Hwang stayed South = pharmacist. Brother dragged North = doctor/air force
  - At reunion: brother had no car, no phone ("My daughter at Foreign Ministry has a phone, but if you don't know the code you can't call")
  - Brother refused money: "government will say 'Give that money to us'"
  - Brother's coat threadbare, borrowed from government. Always nervous, "as though someone were listening"
  - Hwang lived well; brother "looked awful and was thin as a rake"
- South Korea: living standards similar to Portugal/Spain. North: ~one-tenth of South's, akin to sub-Saharan Africa
- Average North Korean life expectancy TEN YEARS less than South Korean
- Map 7: satellite night image — North almost completely dark; South blazing with light
- Differences created entirely by different institutions after 1945

#### South Korea: Syngman Rhee (Harvard/Princeton-educated, anticommunist) elected 1948. Not democracy — Rhee and successor Park Chung-Hee authoritarian. BUT market economy with private property. After 1961 Park channeled credit/subsidies to successful firms → "Miracle Economy"

#### North Korea: Kim Il-Sung (anti-Japanese communist) dictator by 1947 with Soviet help. Juche system = rigid central planning. Private property outlawed, markets banned. Recurring famines, industrial/agricultural collapse. No incentives. By late 1990s: tenfold gap.

### Extractive and Inclusive Economic Institutions (pp. 89-93)
- Teenagers in North vs South: North = poverty, propaganda education, 10 years army, can't own property/start business, only black markets. South = good education, market economy, banks, can open any business, hire workers, enjoy fruits of effort

#### INCLUSIVE ECONOMIC INSTITUTIONS: allow/encourage broad participation in economic activities; feature secure private property, unbiased law, public services providing level playing field; permit new business entry, allow career choice

#### EXTRACTIVE ECONOMIC INSTITUTIONS: designed to extract incomes/wealth from one subset to benefit another (North Korea, colonial Latin America's mita/encomienda/repartimiento)

- Secure private property rights CENTRAL — but must exist for MAJORITY, not just elite
- Barbados example (1680 census): ~60,000 population, 39,000 African slaves. 175 largest sugar planters owned most land/slaves. 29 of 40 judges were large planters; 8 senior military officials too
  - Elite HAD secure property rights but two-thirds of population were slaves — NOT inclusive

### The Role of the State (pp. 93-94):
- Property rights, law, contracts all RELY ON STATE with coercive capacity
- State needed for roads, infrastructure, regulation, coordination on large scale
- State "inexorably intertwined" with economic institutions
- Inclusive economic institutions NEED and USE the state
- Extractive contrast: NK education = propaganda, can't prevent famine; colonial Latin America state focused on coercing indigenous peoples

### Extractive and Inclusive Political Institutions (pp. 95-99)
- Economic institutions created by people — WHO decides depends on politics
- Conflict inherent: inclusive institutions good for nation but some groups prefer extractive (Communist Party, sugar planters)

#### ABSOLUTIST political institutions: power narrow and unconstrained. Those wielding power set up extractive economic institutions for self-enrichment

#### PLURALISTIC political institutions: distribute power broadly, subject it to constraints. Power rests with broad coalition/plurality

#### Two conditions for INCLUSIVE political institutions: (1) Pluralistic (2) Sufficiently centralized state

#### Somalia Contrast: power widely distributed (almost pluralistic) BUT no centralization
- Society divided into antagonistic clans; power constrained only by guns of another clan
- Result: CHAOS not inclusion. Problem = no political/state centralization
- Max Weber: state = "monopoly of legitimate violence." Without it → can't enforce law, provide services → chaos

#### Synergy/Feedback Loop:
- Extractive political → extractive economic → wealth to elites → reinforces political dominance
- Extractive economic/political institutions SUPPORT EACH OTHER and tend to persist
- When newcomers overthrow elites under extractive institutions, face same incentives → maintain extraction (Díaz in Mexico)
- Inclusive political → inclusive economic → equitable resource distribution → sustains inclusive political
- 1618: Virginia Company gave land → but economic rights wouldn't be trusted without political rights (General Assembly 1619)
- Combinations of extractive + inclusive are GENERALLY UNSTABLE

### Why Not Always Choose Prosperity? (pp. 99-100)
- Kingdom of Kongo/Congo: independent from Belgium 1960; under Mobutu (1965-97) unbroken decline
  - Elite "Les Grosses Legumes" (Big Vegetables) became fabulously wealthy
  - Mobutu built palace at Gbadolite with Concorde-capable airport; rented Concorde from Air France; bought castles in Europe, large tracts of Brussels
- Wouldn't Mobutu benefit from inclusive institutions? NO — inclusive institutions redistribute income AND power; dictator may become worse off
- FUNDAMENTAL: disputes and conflict over institutions inevitable — different consequences for prosperity, distribution, power
- Economic growth creates WINNERS AND LOSERS

#### Creative Destruction (Joseph Schumpeter):
- Growth replaces old with new: new sectors take resources from old, new firms displace established ones, new tech makes existing skills/machines obsolete
- Creates losers in political arena AND economic marketplace
- FEAR of creative destruction often at ROOT of opposition to inclusive institutions
- On eve of Industrial Revolution: European governments controlled by aristocracies whose income came from land or trading monopolies/entry barriers from monarchs
- Creative destruction threatened them: factories/towns took resources from land, reduced rents, increased wages

---

## PAGES 301-320: CHAPTER 9 (cont.) — Reversing Development / CHAPTER 10: THE DIFFUSION OF PROSPERITY

### Slavery's Persistence After Abolition of Slave Trade (pp. 301-303)
- Abolition of Atlantic slave trade did NOT end slavery in Africa — it redirected it
- When legitimate commerce (palm oil, groundnuts, rubber) grew, African elites used the SAME coercive apparatus built during slave trade
- Asante Empire (modern Ghana): after 1807 when external slave trade closed, slaves redeployed to large plantations around capital Kumase, producing gold and kola nuts for export
- Dahomey: king had large palm oil plantations near coastal ports of Whydah and Porto Novo, all based on slave labor
- In Nigeria, 1820s-30s the Oyo Kingdom collapsed, replaced by Yoruba city-states (Illorin, Ibadan) directly involved in slave trade. In 1830s Oyo's capital sacked, Yoruba cities fought Dahomey for regional dominance, generating massive slave supply
- Slavery EXPANDED throughout 19th century Africa — in West African kingdoms (Asante, Dahomey, Yoruba city-states) well over half the population were slaves
- French colonial records for western Sudan (Mali, Burkina Faso, Senegal, Niger, Chad): 30% of population enslaved as of 1900
- European colonization also failed to end slavery — in Sierra Leone, slavery only formally abolished in 1928, despite Freetown being founded as a haven for freed slaves
- In Liberia (founded for freed American slaves in 1840s), as late as 1960s an estimated one-quarter of labor force was coerced, living in conditions close to slavery

### Making a Dual Economy (pp. 303-308)
- Sir Arthur Lewis's "dual economy" paradigm (1955): less-developed countries split into modern sector (urban, industry, advanced tech) and traditional sector (rural, agriculture, backward institutions)
- Lewis won Nobel Prize in 1979 for this work
- Traditional sector features: communal land ownership, no private property rights, inefficient labor use
- "Problem of development" per Lewis: moving people from traditional to modern sector
- South Africa as clearest example of dual economy — contrast between KwaZulu-Natal (east of Great Kei River: wealthy beachfront, sugarcane, good roads) and Transkei (west: brown, deforested, makeshift huts)
- KEY ARGUMENT: The dual economy was NOT natural or inevitable — it was CREATED by South African white elites to produce a reservoir of cheap labor and reduce competition from black Africans
- The backwardness of the Transkei was recent and man-made, not a historic remnant

### South Africa's Colonial History (pp. 305-310)
- Dutch East India Company founded Cape Town in 1652 — area was sparsely settled by Khoikhoi hunter-gatherers
- Xhosa people in Ciskei/Transkei were densely populated, agricultural — far from slave markets, avoided worst effects of slave trade
- 19th century: Europeans attracted by temperate climate (no malaria/yellow fever unlike West Africa — the "white man's graveyard")
- British took Cape Town during Napoleonic Wars, precipitating Xhosa wars as settlement frontier expanded
- 1835: Great Trek — Afrikaners (Boers) migrated inland from British-controlled coast, founded Orange Free State and Transvaal
- 1867: vast diamond reserves discovered at Kimberly; 1886: rich gold mines in Johannesburg
- Boer Wars (1880-1881 and 1899-1902) — British fought to control mineral wealth
- 1910: Union of South Africa formed, merging British and Afrikaner territories

### African Economic Dynamism Before Dispossession (pp. 306-309)
- Xhosa in Ciskei/Transkei responded eagerly to economic opportunities from European settlement
- As early as 1832, a Moravian missionary noted demand for European consumer goods
- 1876: Civil commissioner John Hemming visited Fingoland in Ciskei — "struck with the very great advancement" — brick houses, fruit trees, irrigated land, plows on hillsides
- 1879: magistrate in Griqualand East noted Africans had purchased 38,000 acres; three years later 8,000 African farmers working 90,000 acres
- Stephen Sonjica, self-made Ciskei farmer: father said "Buy land? Don't you know that all land is God's, and he gave it to the chiefs only?" Sonjica saved £80, bought oxen, plow, and a small farm. Told in 1911 address
- 1869: Methodist missionary W. J. Davis recorded collecting £46 in cash from prosperous African farmers "for the Lancashire Cotton Relief Fund" — Africans donating money to poor English textile workers
- KEY POINT: Private property in land weakened chiefs' power, creating economic dynamism

### Destruction of African Prosperity (pp. 309-313)
- Between 1890-1913, two forces destroyed African rural prosperity:
  1. Antagonism from European farmers competing with successful Africans
  2. Mining interests wanted cheap labor, achievable only by impoverishing Africans
- George Albu, chairman of Association of Mines, 1897 testimony to Commission of Inquiry: proposed forcing Africans to work, taxing them, preventing them from holding land — "He must do his part of the work of helping his neighbours"
- Natives Land Act of 1913: 87% of land to Europeans (20% of population), 13% to Africans — created the legal foundation of apartheid
  - Stopped black sharecroppers from farming on white-owned land except as labor tenants
  - Created Transkei and Ciskei as African "Homelands" (later Bantustans)
- After 1913: vast numbers of Africans evicted, crowded into tiny Homelands, forced into cheap labor for mines/farms
- Historian Francis Wilson: miners' wages fell 30% between 1911-1921; in 1961 wages still 12% lower than 1911 despite steady economic growth
- South Africa became the most unequal country in the world

### The Color Bar and Bantu Education (pp. 313-316)
- Job reservation for Europeans introduced in mining as early as 1904 — Africans banned from skilled positions (amalgamator, assayer, blacksmith, boiler maker, etc.)
- Color bar extended to entire economy in 1926, lasted until 1980s
- Bantu Education Act: Hendrik Verwoerd's 1954 speech: "The Bantu must be guided to serve his own community... There is no place for him in the European community above the level of certain forms of labour"
- State removed possibility of education benefiting Africans AND refused to invest in black schools
- White South Africans shared living standards of Western Europe; black South Africans scarcely richer than rest of sub-Saharan Africa
- Economic growth without creative destruction — by 1970s growth had stopped
- Extractive political institutions: whites only could vote/run for office; by 1930s blacks explicitly disenfranchised everywhere
- Dual economy ended in 1994 not by Lewis's natural economic development, but by black political mobilization — Soweto uprising 1976, then growing protests that brought down Apartheid

### Development Reversed (pp. 316-320)
- World inequality exists because some nations could take advantage of Industrial Revolution, others couldn't
- Extractive institutions either persisted or were imposed/strengthened by the very process of European growth
- Dutch East India Company stamped out indigenous development in Banda Islands via genocide, made other Southeast Asian city-states pull back from commerce
- India: largest producer/exporter of textiles in 18th century — Indian calicoes and muslins traded worldwide
  - English East India Company (founded 1600) established monopoly, then switched to continental empire under Robert Clive
  - Battles of Plassey (1757) and Buxar (1764): EIC conquered Bengal, looted local wealth, intensified extractive taxation
  - British textile producers got Parliament to ban import of calicoes, destroying India's main export market
  - India went from producing textiles to buying British textiles and growing opium for EIC to sell in China
  - Result: de-urbanization and increased poverty — development reversed
- Atlantic slave trade repeated same pattern in Africa: states turned into war machines capturing/selling slaves, political centralization crumbled, extractive institutions persisted
- South Africa: Europeans imposed institutions to create reservoir of cheap labor, dual economy prevented 80% of population from skilled occupations

## CHAPTER 5: "I'VE SEEN THE FUTURE, AND IT WORKS": GROWTH UNDER EXTRACTIVE INSTITUTIONS (pp. 142-170)

### I've Seen the Future (pp. 142-143)
- Central question: if most societies historically have extractive institutions, does that mean no growth ever occurs? Obviously not — extractive institutions must create SOME wealth in order to extract it
- A ruler monopolizing political power with a centralized state can impose law and order and stimulate economic activity
- BUT growth under extractive institutions DIFFERS from growth under inclusive institutions: it will NOT be sustained growth requiring technological change, but rather growth based on EXISTING technologies
- Soviet Union is the vivid illustration: state-spearheaded rapid growth under extractive institutions that ultimately came to an end and collapsed

### The Soviet Growth Story (pp. 143-146)
- After WWI, victors met at Versailles; Russia absent because Bolsheviks overthrew tsarist regime October 1917
- Civil war between Reds (Bolsheviks) and Whites; English, French, Americans sent expeditionary force against Bolsheviks
- William Bullitt (young diplomat) and Lincoln Steffens (muckraker journalist) sent to Moscow to meet Lenin
- Steffens had been in Russia during the revolution; his presence made the mission look credible
- Steffens was bowled over by what he saw as the great potential of the Soviet regime
- KEY QUOTE: "Soviet Russia was a revolutionary government with an evolutionary plan. Their plan was not to end evils such as poverty and riches, graft, privilege, tyranny, and war by direct action, but to seek out and remove their causes."
- Upon return, Steffens told Bernard Baruch: "I have been over into the future, and it works." Perfected as: "I've seen the future, and it works."
- Into the early 1980s, many Westerners still believed the Soviet future was working
- Lenin died 1924; by 1927 Stalin consolidated power, purged opponents, launched rapid industrialization
- Stalin's method: develop industry by government command, resource it by taxing agriculture at very high rates
- No effective tax system → Stalin "collectivized" agriculture: abolished private property rights to land, herded people into giant collective farms run by Communist Party
- Collectivization made it easier for Stalin to grab agricultural output to feed factory workers
- CONSEQUENCES: collective farms completely lacked incentives → production fell sharply → not enough to eat → probably SIX MILLION people died of famine, hundreds of thousands murdered or banished to Siberia

### Why Extractive Growth Worked Temporarily (pp. 144-146)
- Neither new industry nor collectivized farms were EFFICIENT — they did not make best use of Soviet resources
- Sounds like a recipe for stagnation, but Soviet Union grew rapidly — reason is not hard to understand
- Markets are the best way to allocate resources efficiently, but when productivity gap between sectors is ENORMOUS, even inefficient top-down reallocation can generate growth
- Before 1928, most Russians lived in countryside with primitive technology and few incentives; last vestiges of feudalism eradicated only shortly before WWI
- Huge unrealized economic potential in reallocating labor from agriculture to industry
- Stalin moved resources very poorly used into industry where they could be employed more productively, even if industry itself was very inefficiently organized
- KEY STAT: Between 1928 and 1960, Soviet national income grew at 6% per year — probably the most rapid spurt of economic growth in history up to then
- This growth was NOT created by technological change but by REALLOCATING LABOR and CAPITAL ACCUMULATION (new tools and factories)
- Growth so rapid it fooled not just Steffens but the CIA, Soviet leaders themselves (Khrushchev 1956: "we will bury you"), and Western academics
- Nobel Prize-winner Paul Samuelson's widely-used economics textbook repeatedly predicted Soviet economic dominance — 1961 edition: USSR would overtake US by 1984 or 1997; 1980 edition delayed dates to 2002 and 2012
- Late as 1977, a leading English economist argued Soviet-style economies were SUPERIOR in growth, employment, price stability, and even altruistic motivation — Western capitalism better only at political freedom

### Why Extractive Growth Cannot Be Sustained (pp. 146-148)
- By the 1970s, Soviet economic growth had all but stopped
- TWO REASONS extractive institutions cannot generate sustained technological change:
  1. Lack of economic incentives
  2. Resistance by the elites (creative destruction threatens their power)
- Once inefficiently used resources had been reallocated to industry, few economic gains remained to be had by fiat
- Only area where Soviets sustained innovation: military and aerospace (enormous efforts) → first dog (Leika), first man (Yuri Gagarin) in space, the AK-47

### Gosplan and the Failure of Central Planning (pp. 146-149)
- Gosplan: supposedly all-powerful planning agency for the Soviet economy
- Five-year plans were supposed to provide long time horizon for rational investment and innovation
- REALITY: what got implemented had little to do with five-year plans, which were frequently revised, rewritten, or simply ignored
- Industry development driven by commands from Stalin and the Politburo, who frequently changed their minds
- All plans labeled "draft" or "preliminary" — only ONE copy of a plan ever labeled "final" (light industry, 1939)
- KEY QUOTE (Stalin, 1937): "only bureaucrats can think that planning work ends with the creation of the plan. The creation of the plan is just the beginning. The real direction of the plan develops only after the putting together of the plan."
- Stalin wanted to maximize his discretion to reward the politically loyal and punish enemies
- Gosplan's main role: provide Stalin with INFORMATION to monitor friends and enemies; it tried to AVOID making decisions (if you made a bad decision, you might get shot)

### The 1937 Census Disaster (pp. 148)
- Example of what happened when you took your job seriously and second-guessed the Party
- 1937 census (first since 1926) showed population of ~162 million — far less than the 180 million Stalin anticipated and the 168 million he himself announced in 1934
- The accurate numbers reflected the mass famines and purges of the early 1930s
- Stalin's response: had those who organized the census ARRESTED and sent to Siberia or SHOT
- Next census (1939): organizers "got it right" — found population was 171 million

### The Incentive Problem in Detail (pp. 148-150)
- Stalin understood people had few incentives to work hard in the Soviet economy
- Sometimes introduced positive incentives (directing food to areas where productivity had fallen)
- By 1931, gave up on creating "socialist men and women" who would work without monetary incentives — criticized "equality mongering"
- Different jobs got different wages; a bonus system was introduced
- Bonuses could be quite high — as much as 37% of wage for management/senior engineers
- BUT bonuses created DISINCENTIVES for technological change:
  1. Innovation took resources away from current production → risked missing output targets → no bonuses
  2. Output targets based on PREVIOUS production levels → huge incentive to NEVER expand output (future targets would be "ratcheted up")
  3. Underachievement was the best strategy to meet targets and get bonuses
  4. Bonuses paid monthly → kept everyone focused on present, while innovation is about sacrificing today for tomorrow

### Central Planning vs. the Invisible Hand (pp. 149-150)
- Central planning could not replace Adam Smith's "invisible hand" of the market
- Famous examples of perverse incentives:
  - Plan formulated in TONS of steel sheet → sheet made too heavy
  - Plan formulated in AREA of steel sheet → sheet made too thin
  - Plan for chandeliers in tons → so heavy they could hardly hang from ceilings
- By the 1940s, Soviet leaders were aware of these perverse incentives but treated them as technical problems
- Moved from output-target bonuses to allowing firms to set aside profits for bonuses
- "Profit motive" was no more encouraging of innovation than output targets because prices were set by government, completely unconnected to value of innovations
- Innovation bonuses introduced explicitly in 1946; since 1918 the principle existed that innovators should receive monetary rewards, but rewards were small and unrelated to value
- Only in 1956 was it stipulated bonuses should be proportional to innovation's productivity — but productivity measured using existing (government-set) prices, so still no real incentive
- Innovation bonus fund limited by firm's wage bill → reduced incentive to innovate in labor-saving ways

### Coercion as Substitute for Incentives (pp. 150-151)
- Communist Party used not just carrots but also sticks — big sticks
- Criminal offenses created for workers perceived to be shirking
- June 1940 law: absenteeism (any 20 minutes unauthorized absence or even idling on the job) = criminal offense punishable by 6 months hard labor and 25% pay cut
- KEY STATS: Between 1940 and 1955, 36 MILLION people (~one-third of adult population) found guilty of such offenses
  - 15 million sent to prison
  - 250,000 shot
  - In any given year, 1 million adults in prison for labor violations
  - Plus 2.5 million in Stalin's Siberian gulags
- KEY INSIGHT: "you can move someone to a factory, but you cannot force people to think and have good ideas by threatening to shoot them"
- Coercion worked for sugar production in Barbados/Jamaica but could not compensate for lack of incentives in a modern industrial economy

### The Fundamental Problem (pp. 151-152)
- Failure to introduce effective incentives was NOT due to technical mistakes in bonus scheme design
- It was INTRINSIC to the whole method of extractive growth achieved by government command
- Government command could solve SOME basic economic problems but stimulating sustained growth required individuals to use their talent and ideas — impossible in Soviet-style system
- Soviet rulers would have had to abandon extractive economic institutions, but this would jeopardize their POLITICAL POWER
- When Gorbachev started to move away from extractive economic institutions after 1987, the power of the Communist Party crumbled, and with it, the Soviet Union

### Transition: From Soviet Case to Broader Patterns (pp. 152)
- Soviet Union generated rapid growth under extractive institutions because Bolsheviks built a powerful centralized state and used it to allocate resources toward industry
- But like ALL growth under extractive institutions: did not feature technological change, was not sustained
- Growth first slowed, then totally collapsed
- Throughout history most societies ruled by extractive institutions; those that imposed some order could generate some limited growth
- Some major turning points in history are characterized by institutional innovations that CEMENTED extractive institutions and increased authority of one group
- Rest of chapter: nature of state centralization that enables growth under extractive institutions → Neolithic Revolution → Maya city-states

### On the Banks of the Kasai: Bushong vs. Lele (pp. 153-156)
- Kasai River: great tributary of the River Congo, rising in Angola, heading north to merge with Congo near Kinshasa
- Significant differences in prosperity between groups within Congo despite overall poverty
- Kasai is the boundary between TWO groups: Lele (western bank) and Bushong (eastern bank) — see Map 6
- On the face of it, few differences should exist: separated only by a river (crossable by boat), common origin, related languages, similar houses/clothes/crafts
- Anthropologist Mary Douglas and historian Jan Vansina studied them in the 1950s → discovered startling differences
- Douglas: "The Lele are poor, while the Bushong are rich... Everything that the Lele have or can do, the Bushong have more and can do better"
- KEY DIFFERENCES:
  - Lele produced for SUBSISTENCE; Bushong produced for EXCHANGE in the market
  - Lele used inferior technology — did not use NETS for hunting (greatly improved productivity)
  - Douglas: "absence of nets is consistent with a general Lele tendency not to invest time and labor in long-term equipment"
  - Bushong practiced sophisticated MIXED FARMING: five crops planted in succession in a two-year rotation — yams, sweet potatoes, manioc (cassava), beans; gathered two and sometimes THREE maize harvests per year
  - Lele had no such system; managed only ONE annual harvest of maize
- LAW AND ORDER differences:
  - Lele dispersed into fortified villages in constant conflict; anyone venturing between villages or into forest could be attacked or kidnapped
  - In Bushong country, this rarely if ever happened
- NOT geography, NOT ignorance (Lele knew about Bushong tools), NOT culture (Lele were eager to buy guns — "their eager purchase of firearms shows their culture does not restrict them to inferior techniques when these do not require long-term collaboration and effort")

### The Kuba Kingdom and King Shyaam (pp. 155-156)
- Differences explained by DIFFERENT POLITICAL INSTITUTIONS
- Lele lived in fortified villages not part of a unified political structure
- Around 1620, a political revolution led by a man called SHYAAM forged the KUBA KINGDOM with the Bushong at its heart
- Prior to this, few differences between Bushong and Lele; differences emerged as a consequence of Shyaam's reorganization
- Shyaam built a STATE and a pyramid of political institutions — significantly more centralized than before, with highly elaborate structures
- Shyaam and successors created: bureaucracy to raise taxes, legal system, police force to administer the law
- Leaders checked by councils they had to consult; there was even TRIAL BY JURY — apparently unique in sub-Saharan Africa prior to European colonialism
- Nevertheless, the centralized state was a tool of extraction and highly absolutist — nobody voted for Shyaam; state policy dictated from the top
- Political revolution → economic revolution: agriculture reorganized, new technologies adopted, new higher-yield crops from Americas (maize, cassava, chili peppers), intense mixed-farming cycle introduced
- Food produced per capita DOUBLED
- Age of marriage lowered to 20 (brought men into agricultural labor younger) vs. Lele men marrying at 35 and spending youth fighting/raiding
- Connection is simple: King Shyaam and supporters wanted to EXTRACT taxes and wealth → had to produce surplus above subsistence → encouraged economic activity to have something to extract
- Like Stalin, Shyaam created institutions to generate wealth necessary to support the system
- Growth was necessarily LIMITED: no creative destruction in Kuba Kingdom, no technological innovation after initial change — situation unchanged when Belgian colonial officials encountered the kingdom in late 19th century

### Key Insight: Contingency of State Centralization (pp. 156)
- Why Bushong and not Lele had the political revolution is not deterministic — Lele could have had their own Shyaam
- What Shyaam accomplished was an institutional innovation not tied to geography, culture, or ignorance
- Most likely due to CONTINGENT NATURE of history — same contingency at work when Middle Eastern societies 12,000 years ago embarked on Neolithic Revolution

### The Long Summer: Neolithic Revolution (pp. 156-157)
- ~15,000 BC: Ice Age ended as Earth's climate warmed
- Greenland ice cores: average temperatures rose by as much as 15°C in a short span
- Warming coincided with rapid increases in human populations and greater availability of wild plants/foods
- ~14,000 BC: rapid reverse — Younger Dryas cooling period
- After 9600 BC: temperatures rose again by 7°C in less than a decade → stayed high since
- Archaeologist Brian Fagan calls it the "Long Summer" — huge critical juncture, background to Neolithic Revolution
- Fundamental difference between farming/herding and hunting-gathering: farming based on DOMESTICATION of plant and animal species, active intervention to change genetics
- Domestication = technological change enabling humans to produce far more food
- Example: domestication of maize from teosinte (wild ancestor) — teosinte cobs very small (few cm); by selecting larger ears and plants whose ears stayed on stalk, humans created modern maize
- Earliest evidence of farming/herding/domestication: Middle East, specifically the HILLY FLANKS (south of modern Israel, through Palestine, west bank of Jordan, Syria, southeastern Turkey, northern Iraq, western Iran)
- ~9500 BC: first domestic plants (emmer, two-row barley) found in Jericho (Palestine) and Tell Aswad (Syria) — both Natufian culture sites
- Jericho had population of possibly 500 people by this time
- Why Natufians? Not because they were uniquely endowed with wild species — ancestors of domesticated plants and animals spread over millions of square km across Eurasia
- What made Natufians special: they were SEDENTARY before they started domesticating — one piece of evidence is gazelle teeth
- Gazelle teeth: composed of cementum (bony connective tissue) growing in layers; spring/summer layers differ in color from winter layers → can determine season of death by examining last layer
- At Natufian sites, gazelles killed in ALL seasons → year-round residence
- Abu Hureyra on the Euphrates: one of the most intensively researched Natufian settlements

### Abu Hureyra and the Transition to Sedentary Life (pp. 157-158)
- Abu Hureyra: settlement began ~9500 BC, inhabitants continued hunter-gatherer lifestyle for another 500 years before switching to agriculture
- Population of the village prior to farming: between 100 and 300
- Advantages of sedentary life: moving about is costly (children and old people have to be carried), impossible to store food when mobile, tools like grinding stones/sickles useful but heavy to carry
- Evidence that even mobile hunter-gatherers stored food in select locations such as caves
- Maize stores very well — key reason it became so intensively cultivated throughout the Americas
- Ability to deal with storage and accumulate food stocks was a key incentive for adopting sedentary life
- While collectively desirable to become sedentary, doesn't necessarily happen — a mobile group would have to agree, or someone would have to FORCE them
- Some archaeologists suggested increasing population density and declining living standards forced people to settle — but Natufian site density is no greater than previous groups
- Skeletal/dental evidence: hypoplasia (thin lines in tooth enamel caused by food shortage) is LESS prevalent in Natufian people than in later farming people — they were NOT being forced by hunger

### Sedentary Life Required Political Innovation (pp. 158-159)
- Sedentary life had minuses: conflict resolution much harder — can't just walk away when you have permanent buildings and assets
- Villages needed more effective ways of resolving conflict and more elaborate notions of property
- Decisions about land access, fruit-picking rights, fishing spots all required rules and institutions
- ARGUMENT: for sedentary life to emerge, hunter-gatherers would have had to be FORCED to settle down — preceded by an institutional innovation concentrating power in the hands of a group that would become the political elite, enforce property rights, maintain order, and extract resources
- A political revolution similar to King Shyaam's, even if smaller scale, likely was the breakthrough that led to sedentary life

### Archaeological Evidence for Hierarchy BEFORE Farming (pp. 159)
- Natufians developed a complex society with hierarchy, order, and inequality — beginnings of extractive institutions — BEFORE they became farmers
- Evidence from Natufian GRAVES: some people buried with large amounts of obsidian and dentalium shells (from Mediterranean coast near Mount Carmel); necklaces, garters, bracelets made from canine teeth, deer phalanges, shells
- Other people buried WITHOUT any of these things — clear inequality
- Shells and obsidian were traded; control of this trade was a source of power accumulation
- Natufian site of Ain Mallaha (just north of Sea of Galilee): ~50 round huts, many storage pits, and a large intensively plastered building close to a cleared central place — almost certainly the house of a chief
- Some burials much more elaborate; evidence of skull cult/ancestor worship (especially at Jericho)
- CONCLUSION: Natufians were probably already societies with elaborate institutions determining inheritance of elite status, engaged in trade with distant places, with nascent religion and political hierarchies

### The Chicken-and-Egg: Institutions CAUSED Farming (pp. 159-161)
- Emergence of political elites most likely created the transition FIRST to sedentary life, THEN to farming
- Natufian sites show sedentary life did NOT necessarily mean farming — people could settle down but still live by hunting and gathering (Long Summer made wild crops bountiful)
- Most people may have been quite satisfied with subsistence life based on hunting/gathering
- KEY EXAMPLE: when the steel axe was introduced among Australian Aboriginal peoples known as Yir Yoront, it led NOT to more intense production but to MORE SLEEPING — it allowed subsistence requirements to be met more easily
- Traditional geography-based explanation (Jared Diamond's argument): fortuitous availability of domesticable species drove farming → sedentary life → political hierarchy → complex institutions
- Authors' counter-argument: evidence from Natufians suggests this puts the cart before the horse
- Institutional changes occurred in societies BEFORE they transitioned to farming and were probably the CAUSE of both sedentarism and the Neolithic Revolution
- This pattern is supported not only by Hilly Flanks evidence but also by evidence from the Americas, sub-Saharan Africa, and East Asia

### Consequences of the Neolithic Revolution (pp. 160-161)
- Transition to farming led to greater agricultural productivity and significant population expansion
- At sites like Jericho and Abu Hureyra, early farming villages were much larger than prefarming ones
- Villages grew between 2x and 6x when transition took place
- Consequences traditionally attributed to farming: greater occupational specialization, more rapid technological progress, development of more complex and possibly less egalitarian political institutions
- BUT whether this happened in a particular place was NOT determined by availability of plant/animal species — it was a consequence of the society's institutional, social, and political innovations that would have allowed sedentary life and then farming to emerge
- Long Summer + presence of crop/animal species allowed this to happen but did not determine WHERE or WHEN exactly
- This was determined by interaction of a critical juncture (Long Summer) with small but important institutional differences
- Like Bushong under Shyaam, societies reorganized to take advantage of new opportunities — political elites were the main beneficiaries
- Other places with only slightly different institutions did not permit their elites to take similar advantage → lagged behind in political centralization → paved the way for subsequent divergence
- Farming spread into Europe from Middle East starting ~6500 BC, mostly via migration of farmers
- In Europe, institutions drifted away from parts of the world like Africa where initial institutions had been different

### The Natufian Legacy Did Not Lead to Lasting Prosperity (pp. 161-162)
- Natufian institutional innovations, though they underpinned the Neolithic Revolution, did NOT lead to long-run prosperity for their homelands (modern Israel, Palestine, Syria)
- Syria and Palestine are relatively poor parts of the modern world
- Israel's prosperity was largely imported by Jewish settlement after WWII (high education levels, advanced technologies)
- Early Natufian growth did not become sustained for the SAME REASON Soviet growth fizzled: it was growth under EXTRACTIVE institutions
- For Natufian society, this type of growth likely created deep conflicts over who would control institutions and the extraction they enabled
- For every elite benefiting from extraction, there is a non-elite who would love to replace him
- Sometimes infighting simply replaces one elite with another; sometimes it destroys the whole extractive society → state and societal collapse
- This is what the Maya city-states experienced

### The Unstable Extraction: The Maya (pp. 162-166)
- Farming emerged independently in several places, including modern Mexico
- Maya city-states in southern Mexico, Belize, Guatemala, and western Honduras built a fairly sophisticated civilization under their own brand of extractive institutions
- Maya experience illustrates TWO fundamental limits to extractive growth:
  1. Lack of technological progress
  2. Political instability — different groups fight to become the extractors
- Maya cities first began to develop ~500 BC; early cities eventually failed sometime in the first century AD
- A new political model emerged → Classic Era (AD 250-900): full flowering of Maya culture and civilization
- This more sophisticated civilization ALSO collapsed over the next 600 years
- By the time Spanish conquistadors arrived (early 16th century), great temples and palaces of Tikal, Palenque, and Calakmul had receded into the forest — not rediscovered until 19th century
- Maya cities never unified into an empire — ~50 city-states recognizable by their own glyphs, speaking 31 different but closely related Mayan languages
- Mayas developed a WRITING SYSTEM — at least 15,000 remaining inscriptions describing elite life, culture, and religion
- Long Count CALENDAR: sophisticated system for recording dates, counted years from a fixed date (3114 BC), used by all Maya cities — very similar to our own calendar

### Tracking Maya Rise and Fall Through Inscriptions (pp. 163-164)
- By counting dated buildings across all Maya cities, archaeologists can track building activity over time
- ~AD 500: few dated monuments; AD 514: just 10 Long Count-dated monuments
- Steady increase: 20 by AD 672, 40 by mid-8th century
- After this: number of dated monuments COLLAPSES — by 9th century, down to 10/year; by 10th century, ZERO
- These dated inscriptions give a clear picture of Maya expansion and subsequent contraction from late 8th century

### Copán: A Detailed Case Study (pp. 164-165)
- Copán in western Honduras: Altar Q records names of all kings starting from dynasty founder K'inich Yax K'uk' Mo' ("King Green-Sun First Quetzal Macaw")
- Named after the sun AND two exotic birds of the Central American forest whose feathers were greatly valued
- K'inich Yax K'uk' Mo' came to power in Copán AD 426 (known from Long Count date on Altar Q)
- Founded a dynasty that would reign for 400 years
- Notable successors: the 13th ruler's glyph translates as "18 Rabbit"; followed by "Smoke Monkey"; then "Smoke Shell" (died AD 763)
- Last name on altar: King Yax Pasaj Chan Yoaat ("First Dawned Sky Lightening God") — 16th ruler, assumed throne at death of Smoke Shell
- After him, only one more known king: Ukit Took ("Patron of Flint") — from a fragment of an altar; probably not even real claimant to throne but a pretender
- After Yax Pasaj, buildings and inscriptions stopped → dynasty shortly overthrown

### Mapping Copán's Rise and Fall with Obsidian Hydration (pp. 165)
- Archaeologists AnnCorinne Freter, Nancy Gonlin, and David Webster mapped rise and fall of Copán settlement over 850 years (AD 400-1250)
- Used OBSIDIAN HYDRATION technique: calculates water content of obsidian on the date it was mined; water content falls at known rate → can date when obsidian was mined
- Could map where dated obsidian pieces were found in Copán Valley and trace city's expansion/contraction
- POPULATION STATS:
  - AD 400-449: population negligible, ~600 people
  - Rose steadily to peak of 28,000 in AD 750-799
  - Though not large by contemporary standards, this was massive for the period — Copán had a LARGER POPULATION than London or Paris at the time
  - Other Maya cities (Tikal, Calakmul) were undoubtedly much larger
  - AD 800: population peak → then decline began
  - By AD 900: fallen to ~15,000
  - By AD 1200: population had returned to what it was 800 years previously (~600)

### Maya Economic and Political Institutions (pp. 165-166)
- Basis for Maya Classical Era economic development: same as Bushong and Natufians — creation of EXTRACTIVE INSTITUTIONS with some degree of state centralization
- ~AD 100 at Tikal (Guatemala): a new type of dynastic kingdom emerged based on the *ajaw* (lord/ruler)
- King called *k'uhul ajaw* (divine lord) with hierarchy of aristocrats beneath him
- Divine lord organized society with cooperation of these elites and also communicated with the gods
- No popular participation in political institutions, but did bring STABILITY
- *K'uhul ajaw* raised tribute from farmers, organized labor to build great monuments
- These institutions created basis for impressive economic expansion: extensive occupational specialization (skilled potters, weavers, woodworkers, tool and ornament makers)
- Traded obsidian, jaguar pelts, marine shells, cacao, salt, and feathers over long distances
- Probably had MONEY — like Aztecs, used cacao beans for currency
- Creation of extractive political institutions very similar to Bushong: Yax Ehb' Xook at Tikal played role similar to King Shyaam
- New political institutions → significant increase in economic prosperity, much of which extracted by new elite based around *k'uhul ajaw*
- By ~AD 300, system consolidated → little further technological change
- Some evidence of improved irrigation and water management, but agricultural technology remained rudimentary
- Building and artistic techniques became more sophisticated, but overall little innovation

### Maya Collapse: Warfare and Instability (pp. 166-168)
- No creative destruction, but there WERE other forms of destruction
- Wealth created by extractive institutions and Maya elite led to CONSTANT WARFARE that WORSENED over time
- Sequence of conflicts recorded in Maya inscriptions using special glyphs
- Planet Venus was the celestial patron of war — certain phases of its orbit considered particularly auspicious for waging war
- "Star wars" glyph: shows a star showering the earth with liquid (water or blood)
- Inscriptions reveal patterns of alliance and competition: long contests for power between larger states (Tikal, Calakmul, Copán, Palenque)
- These larger states subjugated smaller states into vassal status (evidence from glyphs marking royal accessions — smaller states show they are being dominated by outside rulers)
- Map 10: shows main Maya cities and inter-city contacts (hierarchy, diplomatic contacts, conflicts) — reconstructed by archaeologists Nikolai Grube and Simon Martin
- Large cities like Calakmul, Dos Pilas, Piedras Negras, Yaxchilan had extensive diplomatic contacts; some dominated by others; they also fought each other
- OVERWHELMING FACT about Maya collapse: it coincides with overthrow of the *k'uhul ajaw* political model
- In Copán: after Yax Pasaj's death ~AD 810, no more kings; royal palaces abandoned
- 20 miles north, city of Quiriguá: last king Jade Sky ascended between AD 795 and 800; last dated monument is AD 810 (same year Yax Pasaj died); city abandoned soon after
- Throughout Maya area: political institutions that provided context for expansion of trade, agriculture, and population VANISHED
- Royal courts did not function, monuments and temples not carved, palaces emptied
- As political and social institutions unraveled → economy contracted and population fell

### Collapse Details (pp. 168)
- In some cases, major centers collapsed from widespread violence (Petexbatun region of Guatemala — great temples pulled down, stone used to build extensive defensive walls)
- Similar to what happened in the later Roman Empire
- In other places like Copán, fewer signs of violence but monuments defaced or destroyed
- In some places, elite remained even after initial overthrow of *k'uhul ajaw* — in Copán, evidence of elite continuing to erect new buildings for at least another 200 years before they too disappeared
- Elsewhere elites seem to have gone at the same time as the divine lord
- Archaeological evidence does not allow definitive conclusion on WHY *k'uhul ajaw* was overthrown — but it took place in context of intensified inter-city warfare, likely opposition and rebellion within the cities, perhaps by different factions of the elite

### What Goes Wrong? — Chapter 5 Synthesis (pp. 169-171)
- Extractive institutions are so common in history because they have a powerful logic: they can generate some limited prosperity while distributing it to a small elite
- For this growth to happen, there MUST be political centralization — once in place, the state/elite has incentives to invest, generate wealth, and encourage others to invest so it can extract from them
- Can even MIMIC some processes that inclusive institutions set in motion (e.g., structuring incentives for managers and workers in Soviet Union)
- The POTENTIAL for creating extractive growth gives an impetus to political centralization — why Shyaam created Kuba Kingdom, why Natufians set up hierarchy, why Mayas built civilization
- Growth generated by extractive institutions is VERY DIFFERENT from growth under inclusive institutions:
  1. NOT SUSTAINABLE — extractive institutions do not foster creative destruction, generate at best limited technological progress
  2. Growth lasts only so long — Soviet example: caught up rapidly using advanced Western technologies + reallocating resources from inefficient agriculture to industry, but was relatively short-lived, already running out of steam by the 1970s
- Lack of creative destruction/innovation is NOT the only reason for limits — the Maya city-states illustrate a MORE OMINOUS end
- Extractive institutions create significant gains for the elite → strong incentives for OTHERS to fight to replace the current elite
- Infighting and instability are thus INHERENT features of extractive institutions
- They not only create inefficiencies but often REVERSE any political centralization, sometimes leading to total breakdown of law and order → descent into chaos (as Maya experienced after their Classical Era)
- Though inherently limited, extractive growth may appear spectacular while it's happening — many in the West were awestruck by Soviet growth from 1920s through 1970s
- Same awe now directed at breakneck pace of Chinese growth today
- KEY WARNING: China under Communist Party is ANOTHER example of growth under extractive institutions, and is similarly unlikely to generate sustained growth unless it undergoes fundamental political transformation toward inclusive political institutions

---

## CHAPTER 6: DRIFTING APART (pp. 171-210)

### How Venice Became a Museum (pp. 171-172)
- Venice: group of islands at the far north of the Adriatic Sea
- In the Middle Ages, Venice was possibly the RICHEST PLACE in the world, with the most advanced set of inclusive economic institutions underpinned by nascent political inclusiveness
- Gained independence in AD 810 — fortuitous time as Europe recovered from Roman Empire collapse and kings like Charlemagne reconstituted strong central political power
- This led to stability, greater security, expansion of trade — Venice was uniquely positioned (nation of seafarers in the middle of the Mediterranean)
- From the East came spices, Byzantine-manufactured goods, and slaves
- Venice became rich
- POPULATION GROWTH stats:
  - By 1050: already expanding economically for at least a century, population of 45,000
  - Increased by 50%+ to 70,000 by 1200
  - By 1330: increased by another 50% to 110,000 — Venice was then as big as Paris, probably THREE TIMES the size of London
- One of the key bases for economic expansion: a series of contractual innovations making economic institutions much more INCLUSIVE
- Most famous: the *commenda* — a rudimentary type of JOINT STOCK COMPANY, formed only for the duration of a single trading mission
- Involved two partners: a "sedentary" one who stayed in Venice (put up capital) and a "traveling" one

### The Commenda and Social Mobility (pp. 172)
- *Commenda*: traveling partner accompanied the cargo; sedentary partner put in the lion's share of capital
- Young entrepreneurs who did not have wealth themselves could get into trading by traveling with merchandise — KEY CHANNEL OF UPWARD SOCIAL MOBILITY
- Losses shared according to capital contributed; profits split based on two types of contract:
  - UNILATERAL *commenda*: sedentary merchant provided 100% of capital, received 75% of profits
  - BILATERAL *commenda*: sedentary merchant provided 67% of capital, received 50% of profits
- Studying official documents shows how powerful *commenda* was for fostering upward social mobility — documents full of NEW NAMES, people not previously among the Venetian elite
- KEY STATS: In government documents of AD 960, 971, and 982, the number of new names comprised 69%, 81%, and 65% of those recorded, respectively

### Venice's Political Opening (pp. 172-173)
- Economic inclusiveness and rise of new families through trade forced the political system to become more open
- The DOGE governed Venice, selected for life by the General Assembly
- General Assembly was a general gathering of all citizens but in practice dominated by a core group of powerful families
- Though doge was very powerful, his power was gradually reduced over time by changes in political institutions
- After 1032: doge elected along with newly created DUCAL COUNCIL, whose job was to ensure doge did not acquire absolute power
- First doge hemmed in by this council: DOMENICO FLABIANICO — a wealthy silk merchant from a family that had NOT previously held high office
- Institutional change followed by huge expansion of Venetian mercantile and naval power
- 1082: Venice granted extensive trade privileges in Constantinople; a Venetian Quarter created there, soon housing 10,000 Venetians
- Inclusive economic and political institutions beginning to work in tandem

### The Great Council and Further Reforms (pp. 173)
- Economic expansion created more pressure for political change, which exploded after the murder of the doge in 1171
- First important innovation: creation of a GREAT COUNCIL — the ultimate source of political power in Venice from this point on
- Council made up of officeholders of the Venetian state (judges etc.), dominated by aristocrats
- Each year 100 new members nominated to the council by a nominating committee (4 members chosen by lot from existing council) — automatically selected
- Council chose members for two subcouncils: the SENATE and the COUNCIL OF FORTY (various legislative and executive tasks)
- Great Council also chose the Ducal Council (expanded from 2 to 6 members)
- Second innovation: creation of another council, chosen by the Great Council BY LOT, to nominate the doge — though choice had to be ratified by General Assembly (which nominated only one person), this effectively gave the choice of doge to the council
- Third innovation: new doge had to swear an oath of office that circumscribed ducal power; constraints continually expanded — subsequent doges had to obey magistrates, have all decisions approved by Ducal Council
- Ducal Council also ensured doge obeyed all decisions of the Great Council

### Political Reforms Lead to Economic Innovation (pp. 173-174)
- Political reforms led to further institutional innovations: independent magistrates, courts, a court of appeals, new private contract and BANKRUPTCY laws
- New Venetian economic institutions allowed creation of new legal business forms and new types of contracts
- Rapid financial innovation; beginnings of modern BANKING around this time in Venice
- Dynamic toward fully inclusive institutions looked unstoppable

### The Tension: Creative Destruction Threatens Elites (pp. 174)
- BUT there was a tension: economic growth supported by inclusive institutions was accompanied by creative destruction
- Each new wave of enterprising young men who became rich via *commenda* reduced profits of established elites AND challenged their political power
- Existing elites sitting in the Great Council always had a temptation to CLOSE DOWN the system to these new people

### La Serrata — "The Closure" (pp. 174-175)
- At Great Council's inception, membership determined each year — 4 electors randomly chosen to nominate 100 members, automatically selected
- October 3, 1286: proposal to Great Council that nominations be confirmed by a majority in the COUNCIL OF FORTY (tightly controlled by elite families) → this would give elite veto power over new nominations → DEFEATED
- October 5, 1286: another proposal passed — automatic confirmation if your FATHERS AND GRANDFATHERS had served on the council; otherwise confirmation by Ducal Council required
- October 17: further change — appointment to Great Council must be approved by Council of Forty, the doge, and the Ducal Council
- Debates of 1286 presaged *La Serrata* ("The Closure") of Venice
- February 1297: decided that if you had been a member of Great Council in the previous 4 years, you received automatic nomination and approval; new nominations now had to be approved by Council of Forty (with only 12 votes needed)
- After September 11, 1298: current members and their families no longer needed confirmation
- Great Council now effectively SEALED to outsiders — initial incumbents became a hereditary aristocracy
- Seal came in 1315 with the *Libro d'Oro* ("Gold Book") — an official registry of the Venetian nobility

### Resistance and Repression (pp. 175-176)
- Those outside the new nobility did not let their powers erode without a struggle
- Political tensions mounted between 1297 and 1315
- Great Council partially responded by making itself bigger to co-opt its most vocal opponents — it grew from 450 to 1,500 members
- Complemented by REPRESSION: police force introduced for the first time in 1310, steady growth in domestic coercion

### The Economic Serrata (pp. 176)
- Having implemented a political *Serrata*, the Great Council moved to adopt an ECONOMIC *Serrata*
- Switch toward extractive political institutions followed by move toward extractive economic institutions
- Most important: they BANNED the use of *commenda* contracts — one of the great institutional innovations that had made Venice rich
- This shouldn't be a surprise: *commenda* benefited new merchants, and the established elite was trying to exclude them — just one step toward more extractive economic institutions
- Starting 1314: Venetian state began to take over and NATIONALIZE trade
- Organized state galleys to engage in trade
- From 1324 on: charged individuals HIGH LEVELS OF TAXES if they wanted to engage in trade
- Long-distance trade became the preserve of the NOBILITY
- This was the beginning of the end of Venetian prosperity

### Venice's Decline (pp. 176)
- With main lines of business monopolized by the increasingly narrow elite, decline was under way
- Venice had appeared to be on the brink of becoming the world's first inclusive society — but it fell to a coup
- Political and economic institutions became more extractive → economic decline
- By 1500: population had shrunk to 100,000
- Between 1650 and 1800: while Europe's population rapidly expanded, Venice's CONTRACTED
- Today: Venice's only economy (apart from a bit of fishing) is TOURISM
- Instead of pioneering trade routes and economic institutions, Venetians make pizza, ice cream, and blow colored glass for foreigners
- Tourists come to see the pre-*Serrata* wonders: the Doge's Palace and the lions of St. Mark's Cathedral (looted from Byzantium when Venice ruled the Mediterranean)
- Venice went from economic powerhouse to MUSEUM

### Chapter Framework: Why Institutions Diverge (pp. 176-177)
- Chapter focuses on historical development of institutions in different parts of the world and why they evolved differently
- Chapter 4 showed how Western Europe diverged from Eastern Europe and then England from rest of Western Europe — consequence of small institutional differences + institutional drift + critical junctures
- Tempting to think these differences are tip of a deep historical iceberg — but it isn't so, for TWO reasons:
  1. Moves toward inclusive institutions CAN BE REVERSED (as Venice shows) — no simple cumulative process of institutional improvement
  2. Small institutional differences that play a crucial role during critical junctures are EPHEMERAL — can be reversed, then can reemerge and be reversed again
- England, where the decisive step toward inclusive institutions would take place in the 17th century, was a BACKWATER — not only in millennia following Neolithic Revolution in the Middle East but also at the beginning of the Middle Ages following the fall of the Western Roman Empire
- British Isles were marginal to the Roman Empire, certainly of less importance than continental Western Europe, North Africa, the Balkans, Constantinople, or the Middle East
- When Western Roman Empire collapsed (5th century AD), BRITAIN suffered the most complete decline
- But the political revolutions that would bring the Industrial Revolution would take place not in Italy, Turkey, or western continental Europe, but in the British Isles

### Roman Virtues: The Republic (pp. 178-182)
- Tiberius Gracchus: Roman plebeian tribune clubbed to death in 133 BC by Roman senators; body thrown into the Tiber
- His murderers were aristocrats like himself, assassination masterminded by his cousin Publius Cornelius Scipio Nasica
- Tiberius had an impeccable aristocratic pedigree — descended from Lucius Aemilius Paullus (hero of Illyrian and Second Punic wars) and Scipio Africanus (defeated Hannibal)
- What pitted Tiberius against powerful senators: his willingness to stand against them on the question of LAND ALLOCATION and the rights of plebeians (common Roman citizens)
- Roman Republic created ~510 BC when citizens overthrew their king Lucius Tarquinius Superbus ("Tarquin the Proud")
- Republic had cleverly designed INCLUSIVE political institutions:
  - Governed by magistrates elected for a year
  - Office held by multiple people at the same time → reduced ability of any one person to consolidate power
  - System of checks and balances distributing power fairly widely
  - Even if not all citizens had equal representation (voting was indirect)
- BUT: large number of SLAVES (perhaps 1/3 of population) had no rights or political representation
- Roman political institutions had PLURALISTIC elements: plebeians had their own assembly, could elect the plebeian tribune (power to veto actions by magistrates, call the Plebeian Assembly, propose legislation)
- It was the plebeians who put Tiberius Gracchus in power in 133 BC
- Plebeian power forged by "SECESSION" — form of strike where plebeians (particularly soldiers) withdrew to a hill outside the city, refused to cooperate with magistrates until complaints dealt with
- Supposedly during one such secession in the 5th century BC that citizens gained the right to elect their tribune and enact laws governing their community
- Political and legal protection created economic opportunities for citizens and some inclusivity in economic institutions → trade flourished throughout the Mediterranean under the Roman Republic

### Evidence of Roman Economic Growth (pp. 180-181)
- Archaeological evidence of economic growth under the Republic:
  - Web of port cities connected by trade: Athens, Antioch, Alexandria → Rome, Carthage, Cadiz → London
  - Mediterranean SHIPWRECKS: can track economic expansion — only ~20 wrecks dated to 500 BC (probably not Roman ships, perhaps Carthaginian); then number increases rapidly; by the time of Christ's birth, reached a PEAK OF 180
  - Shipwrecks show growth but need perspective: probably 2/3 of ship contents were property of the Roman state — taxes, tribute, grain and olive oil from North Africa for free distribution in Rome
  - MONTE TESTACCIO ("Pottery Mountain") near the Tiber in Rome: a small hill made up of approximately 53 MILLION amphorae — discarded over the centuries when unloaded from ships; amphorae (clay vessels for wine/olive oil) often contained information about who made them and when
  - RADIOCARBON DATING of shipwrecks: plants incorporate carbon-14 during photosynthesis; after death, carbon-14 deteriorates via radioactive decay; comparing remaining carbon-14 fraction to atmospheric levels gives estimate of when the tree was cut down
  - GREENLAND ICE CORE PROJECT (1990-1992): drilled through 3,030 meters of ice covering ~250,000 years of human history; snowflakes pick up small quantities of atmospheric pollution (lead, silver, copper)
  - KEY FINDING: distinct increase in atmospheric pollutants starting ~500 BC; atmospheric lead, silver, and copper increased steadily, reaching a peak in the 1st century AD
  - Remarkably, the atmospheric quantity of lead is reached again only in the 13TH CENTURY — showing how intense Roman mining was
  - Ice core findings clearly indicate economic expansion

### Rome's Unsustainability (pp. 181-182)
- Roman growth was unsustainable — occurring under institutions that were partially inclusive and partially extractive
- Though citizens had political and economic rights, slavery was widespread and very extractive
- The elite (senatorial class) dominated both economy and politics
- Despite Plebeian Assembly and plebeian tribune, REAL power rested with the SENATE (members came from large landowners constituting the senatorial class — according to historian Livy, Senate created by Rome's first king Romulus, consisted of 100 men; their descendants made up the senatorial class, though new blood was added)
- Distribution of land was very UNEQUAL, most likely becoming more so by the 2nd century BC — this was at the root of the problems Tiberius Gracchus brought to the fore as tribune
- As Rome expanded throughout Mediterranean, it experienced influx of great riches — but bounty captured mostly by a FEW wealthy families of senatorial rank
- Inequality between rich and poor increased
- Senators owed wealth to: control of lucrative provinces + very large estates throughout Italy, manned by GANGS OF SLAVES captured in Rome's wars
- Where did the LAND for these estates come from? Rome's armies during the Republic consisted of CITIZEN-SOLDIERS — small landowners who fought when necessary and then returned to their plots
- As campaigns got longer, soldiers away for years at a time → landholdings fell into disuse → soldiers' families in debt/starvation → plots gradually abandoned and absorbed by senators' estates
- Large mass of LANDLESS citizens gathered in Rome, often after being decommissioned from the army, with no land to return to → sought work in Rome
- By late 2nd century BC: dangerous boiling point — gap between rich and poor at unprecedented levels + hordes of discontented citizens ready to rebel
- BUT: political power rested with the rich landowners (senatorial class) who benefited from these changes → no intention of changing the system

### Tiberius Gracchus's Land Reform (pp. 182-183)
- According to historian Plutarch, Tiberius Gracchus while traveling through Etruria (central Italy) became aware of the hardship of citizen-soldier families
- Stood for plebeian tribune in 133 BC, used his office to propose LAND REFORM:
  - A commission would investigate whether public lands were being illegally occupied
  - Would redistribute land in excess of the legal limit of 300 ACRES to landless Roman citizens
  - The 300-acre limit was in fact part of an OLD LAW, ignored and not implemented for centuries
- Tiberius's proposal sent SHOCKWAVES through senatorial class → they blocked implementation for a while
- When Tiberius used the mob's power to remove another tribune who threatened to veto his land reform, his commission was finally founded — but the Senate prevented implementation by STARVING the commission of funds
- Things came to a head when Tiberius claimed funds left by the king of the Greek city Pergamum for his land reform commission
- He also attempted to stand for tribune a SECOND TIME (partly fearing persecution by the Senate after stepping down) → gave senators pretext to charge he was trying to declare himself king
- He and his supporters were attacked — Tiberius Gracchus was one of the first to fall, and many supporters were killed
- His death did not solve the problem — many others would attempt to reform land distribution and other aspects of Roman economy/society → many met a similar fate
- Tiberius's brother GAIUS was also murdered by landowners after taking the mantle from his brother

### The Republic Falls (pp. 183-184)
- Tensions resurfaced periodically:
  - "SOCIAL WAR" between 91 and 87 BC
  - Lucius Cornelius SULLA: aggressive defender of senatorial interests, viciously suppressed demands for change AND severely curtailed powers of the plebeian tribune
  - Same issues were a central factor in support Julius CAESAR received from the people of Rome in his fight against the Senate
- Republic's core political institutions were overthrown by Julius Caesar in 49 BC when he moved his legion across the RUBICON (river separating Roman provinces of Cisalpine Gaul from Italy)
- Rome fell to Caesar → civil war → Caesar murdered by disgruntled senators (Brutus and Cassius) in 44 BC
- Roman Republic would never be re-created
- New civil war: between Caesar's supporters (Mark Anthony, Octavian) and his foes → Anthony and Octavian fought each other → Octavian emerged triumphant at the BATTLE OF ACTIUM in 31 BC
- After 28 BC: Octavian ruled as AUGUSTUS CAESAR for the next 45 years — created the ROMAN EMPIRE
- Preferred title *princep* ("first among equals"), called regime the PRINCIPATE
- Map 11 shows the Roman Empire at its greatest extent in AD 117 (includes the Rubicon)
- Transition from republic → principate → empire laid the seeds of Rome's decline
- Partially inclusive political institutions were gradually undermined
- Even if the Republic had created a tilted playing field favoring the senatorial class, it was NOT an absolutist regime and had never concentrated so much power in one position
- Changes unleashed by Augustus, as with the Venetian *Serrata*, were at first political but then would have significant ECONOMIC consequences
- By the 5th century AD: Western Roman Empire had declined economically and militarily and was on the brink of collapse

### Roman Vices: The Fall (pp. 186)
- Flavius AETIUS: one of the larger-than-life characters of the late Roman Empire, hailed as "the last of the Romans" by Edward Gibbon (author of *The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire*)
- Between AD 433 and 454 (until murdered by emperor Valentinian III), Aetius was probably the most powerful person in the Roman Empire — a general who shaped both domestic and foreign policy
- Fought crucial battles against barbarians AND other Romans in civil wars
- Unique among powerful generals in NOT seeking the emperorship himself
- Since death of Marcus Aurelius in AD 180 until collapse of Western Roman Empire in AD 476: hardly a decade without a civil war or a palace coup against an emperor
- Few emperors died of natural causes or in battle — MOST were murdered by usurpers or their own troops
- Aetius's career illustrates changes from Roman Republic to late Empire:
  - His involvement in incessant civil wars and his power in every aspect of the empire contrast with much more limited power of generals/senators in earlier periods
  - Highlights how the fortunes of Romans changed radically in the intervening centuries
- By the late Roman Empire, so-called "barbarians" (initially dominated, incorporated into Roman armies or used as slaves) now DOMINATED many parts of the empire
- Aetius had been held hostage by barbarians as a young man — first by the Goths (under Alaric), then by the Huns
- Alaric was both a ferocious enemy AND an ally — in 405 appointed one of the senior-most generals of the Roman army; by 408 he was fighting AGAINST the Romans, invading Italy and SACKING ROME
- The Huns: also both powerful foes and frequent allies; held Aetius hostage; later fought alongside him in a civil war; then under ATTILA fought a major battle against the Romans in 451 (just across the Rhine); this time the Romans were defended by the Goths under THEODORIC
- Roman elites tried to appease barbarian commanders, often not to protect Roman territories but to gain the upper hand in internal power struggles

### Vandals, Geiseric, and the Final Collapse (pp. 187)
- Vandals under their king GEISERIC ravaged large parts of the Iberian Peninsula, then conquered the Roman bread baskets in North Africa from AD 429 onward
- Roman response to Geiseric: offer emperor Valentinian III's child daughter as a bride — Geiseric was already married to the daughter of one of the Gothic leaders
- Geiseric annulled his marriage under the pretext that his wife was trying to murder him — mutilated her (cut off ears and nose) and sent her back to her family
- The bride-to-be was kept in Italy due to her young age; she later married another powerful general, Petronius Maximus — who masterminded the murder of Aetius by Valentinian III
- Maximus himself shortly murdered in a plot he hatched; declared himself emperor but his reign was very short — ended by a major Vandal offensive under Geiseric that saw Rome fall and be savagely plundered

### The Real Cause of Rome's Decline (pp. 187-188)
- By the early 5th century, barbarians were literally at the gate
- Some historians argue this was because of more formidable opponents during the late Empire
- BUT: the success of the Goths, Huns, and Vandals was a SYMPTOM, not the cause, of Rome's decline — during the Republic, Rome had dealt with much more organized and threatening opponents (e.g., the Carthaginians)
- The decline of Rome had causes VERY SIMILAR to the Maya city-states: increasingly extractive political and economic institutions generated their demise through infighting and civil war
- Origins go back at least to Augustus's seizure of power → changes that made political institutions much more extractive:
  - Changes in structure of the army that made secession impossible → removed crucial element ensuring political representation for common Romans
  - Emperor TIBERIUS (followed Augustus in AD 14): ABOLISHED the Plebeian Assembly, transferred its powers to the Senate
  - Instead of a political voice, Roman citizens got free handouts of wheat (later olive oil, wine, pork) and entertainment by circuses and gladiatorial contests
  - Augustus's reforms: army relied less on citizen-soldiers, more on the PRAETORIAN GUARD (elite group of professional soldiers created by Augustus) → Guard became independent broker of who would become emperor, often through civil wars and intrigue
  - Augustus strengthened the aristocracy against common Roman citizens → growing inequality (which had underpinned the conflict between Tiberius Gracchus and the aristocrats) continued, perhaps even strengthened

### Property Rights and State Land Expansion (pp. 188-189)
- Accumulation of power at the center made property rights of common Romans LESS SECURE
- STATE LANDS expanded with the empire via confiscation → grew to as much as HALF of the land in many parts of the empire
- Property rights became particularly unstable because of concentration of power in the emperor and his entourage
- In a pattern not too different from the Maya city-states, infighting to take control of this powerful position increased
- Civil wars became regular occurrence, even before the chaotic 5th century
- Example: SEPTIMIUS SEVERUS seized power from Didius Julianus (who had made himself emperor after the murder of Pertinax in AD 193) — Severus was the third emperor in the so-called "Year of the Five Emperors"
- Severus then waged war against rival claimants (generals Pescennius Niger and Clodius Albinus, defeated in AD 194 and 197 respectively) and CONFISCATED all the property of his losing opponents
- Though able rulers like Trajan (AD 98-117), Hadrian, and Marcus Aurelius could stanch decline in the next century, they could not or did not want to address the FUNDAMENTAL INSTITUTIONAL PROBLEMS
- None proposed abandoning the empire or re-creating effective political institutions along the lines of the Roman Republic
- Marcus Aurelius was followed by his son COMMODUS, who was more like Caligula or Nero than his father

### Rising Instability in the Empire (pp. 189)
- Rising instability evident from layout of towns and cities
- By the 3rd century AD: every sizeable city in the empire had a DEFENSIVE WALL
- Many cases: monuments plundered for stone used in fortifications
- In Gaul: before Roman arrival (125 BC), it was usual to build settlements on HILLTOPS (more easily defended); with initial arrival of Rome, settlements moved to the PLAINS; in the 3rd century, this trend REVERSED — settlements moved back to hilltops

### Economic Extraction Under the Empire (pp. 189-190)
- Along with mounting political instability came economic changes moving toward greater extraction
- Though citizenship expanded (by AD 212 nearly all inhabitants were citizens), this change went along with changes in STATUS between citizens
- Any sense of equality before the law deteriorated — by reign of HADRIAN (AD 117-138), clear differences in types of laws applied to different categories of citizens
- Role of citizens was completely different from the Republic, when they could exercise power through assemblies
- SLAVERY remained constant throughout Rome — some controversy over whether the fraction of slaves declined over the centuries
- Equally important: more agricultural workers reduced to semi-servile status and TIED TO THE LAND
- These servile "*coloni*" extensively discussed in legal documents (*Codex Theodosianus* and *Codex Justinianus*)
- *Coloni* probably originated during reign of DIOCLETIAN (AD 284-305)
- Rights of landlords over *coloni* progressively increased:
  - Emperor CONSTANTINE in AD 332: allowed landlords to CHAIN a *colonus* they suspected of trying to escape
  - From AD 365: *coloni* were not allowed to sell their own property without landlord's permission

### Tracing Roman Decline (pp. 190-191)
- Shipwrecks and Greenland ice cores can also trace the DECLINE
- By AD 500: peak of 180 shipwrecks was reduced to just 20
- As Rome declined, Mediterranean trade collapsed — some scholars argue it did not return to its Roman height until the 19TH CENTURY
- Greenland ice: Romans used silver for coins, lead for pipes and tableware — after peaking in the 1st century AD, deposits of lead, silver, and copper in the ice cores DECLINED

### Roman Economic Growth — Limited and Without Creative Destruction (pp. 190-191)
- Economic growth during the Republic was impressive but LIMITED and not sustained, even taking into account that it occurred under partially inclusive institutions
- Growth was based on: relatively high agricultural productivity, significant tribute from provinces, long-distance trade — but NOT underpinned by technological progress or creative destruction
- Romans inherited basic technologies: iron tools and weapons, literacy, plow agriculture, building techniques
- Early Republic created others: cement masonry, pumps, the water wheel
- BUT THEREAFTER: technology was STAGNANT throughout the Roman Empire period
  - In shipping: little change in ship design or rigging; Romans never developed the STERN RUDDER, instead steering ships with oars
  - Water wheels spread very slowly → never revolutionized the Roman economy
  - Even great achievements like aqueducts and city sewers used EXISTING technology (Romans perfected it but didn't invent new ones)
- Growth without creative destruction could occur for a while, but it did not last — as property rights became more insecure and economic rights of citizens followed the decline of their political rights, economic growth likewise declined

### Roman Emperors Actively Blocked Innovation (pp. 191-192)
- New technologies in the Roman period seem to have been driven by the STATE — good news until the government decides it is not interested in technological development
- TWO KEY STORIES of emperors actively blocking innovation:
  1. **Emperor Tiberius and unbreakable glass**: Pliny the Elder relates that during Tiberius's reign, a man invented UNBREAKABLE GLASS and went to the emperor anticipating a great reward. He demonstrated his invention. Tiberius asked if he had told anyone else; when the man replied no, Tiberius had him dragged away and KILLED, "lest gold be reduced to the value of mud." Two insights: (a) the man went to the emperor for a reward rather than setting up a business → shows the role of government in controlling technology; (b) Tiberius was happy to DESTROY the innovation because of fear of creative destruction's adverse economic effects
  2. **Emperor Vespasian (AD 69-79) and the column transporter**: A man invented a device for transporting columns to the Capitol at relatively small cost. Columns were large, heavy, and very difficult to transport — moving them from mines involved labor of thousands of people at great government expense. Vespasian did NOT kill the man, but REFUSED to use the innovation, declaring: "How will it be possible for me to FEED THE POPULACE?" The concern was not economic impact but POLITICAL creative destruction — Vespasian was concerned that unless he kept people busy and under control, it would be politically destabilizing. Roman plebeians had to be kept busy and pliant → having jobs like moving columns complemented the bread and circuses dispensed for free to keep the population content
- Both examples came SOON AFTER the collapse of the Republic — Roman emperors had far more power to block change than Roman rulers during the Republic

### Slavery and the Impossibility of Innovation (pp. 192-193)
- Another important reason for lack of technological innovation: the prevalence of SLAVERY
- As territories expanded, vast numbers were enslaved and brought back to Italy to work on large estates
- Many citizens in Rome did not need to work — they lived off government handouts
- Where was innovation to come from? Innovation comes from NEW people with NEW ideas developing new solutions — in Rome, the people doing the producing were SLAVES and later semi-servile *coloni*, with few incentives to innovate (their masters, not they, would benefit)
- KEY PRINCIPLE: economies based on repression of labor and systems such as slavery and serfdom are NOTORIOUSLY NONINNOVATIVE
- True from the ancient world to the modern era — in the United States, the NORTHERN states took part in the Industrial Revolution, NOT the South
- Slavery and serfdom created huge wealth for those who owned slaves/controlled serfs, but it did not create technological innovation or prosperity for SOCIETY

### No One Writes from Vindolanda (pp. 193-195)
- By AD 43: Roman emperor CLAUDIUS had conquered England (but not Scotland)
- Last futile attempt to conquer Scotland made by Roman governor AGRICOLA, who gave up in AD 85 and built a series of forts to protect England's northern border
- One of the biggest forts: VINDOLANDA — 35 miles west of Newcastle, at the far northwest of the Roman Empire (Map 11)
- Later incorporated into Hadrian's 85-MILE defensive wall
- In AD 103, when Roman centurion CANDIDUS was stationed there, it was an isolated fort
- Candidus exchanged letters with his friend OCTAVIUS about supplying the Roman garrison
- KEY QUOTE (Octavius to Candidus): "I have several times written to you that I have bought about five thousand modii of ears of grain, on account of which I need cash. Unless you send me some cash, at least five hundred denarii, the result will be that I shall lose what I have laid out as a deposit, about three hundred denarii, and I shall be embarrassed..."
- Letter reveals: advanced monetary economy with financial services, constructed roads (even if sometimes in bad condition), a fiscal system raising taxes to pay Candidus's wages, LITERACY on both sides, and a postal service
- Roman England also benefited from: mass manufacture of high-quality pottery (particularly in Oxfordshire), urban centers with baths and public buildings, house construction using mortar and tiles for roofs
- By the 4th century: all were in decline
- After AD 411: Roman Empire gave up on England — troops withdrawn, those left were not paid, administrators expelled by local population
- By AD 450: ALL trappings of economic prosperity were gone
  - Money vanished from circulation
  - Urban areas were ABANDONED, buildings stripped of stone
  - Roads overgrown with weeds
  - Only pottery: crude and handmade (not manufactured)
  - People FORGOT how to use mortar
  - Literacy declined substantially
  - Roofs made of branches, not tiles
  - NOBODY WROTE FROM VINDOLANDA ANYMORE

### England as a Historical Backwater (pp. 195-196)
- After AD 411, England experienced economic collapse and became a poor backwater — and NOT for the first time
- When Neolithic Revolution started in the Middle East ~9500 BC, inhabitants of Jericho and Abu Hureyra were living in small towns and farming; inhabitants of England were still HUNTING AND GATHERING → and would do so for at least another 5,500 years
- Even then the English didn't invent farming or herding — these were brought from outside by migrants who had been spreading across Europe from the Middle East for thousands of years
- As England caught up with these major innovations, Middle East was inventing CITIES, WRITING, and POTTERY
- By 3500 BC: large cities like Uruk and Ur emerged in Mesopotamia — Uruk may have had population of 14,000 in 3500 BC, and 40,000 soon afterward
- Potter's wheel invented in Mesopotamia at about the same time, as was wheeled transportation
- Egyptian capital Memphis emerged as a large city soon thereafter; writing appeared independently in both regions
- While Egyptians were building the great pyramids of Giza around 2500 BC, the English constructed their most famous ancient monument, STONEHENGE — not bad by English standards, but not even large enough to have housed one of the ceremonial boats buried at the foot of King Khufu's pyramid
- England continued to lag behind and to borrow from the Middle East and rest of Europe up to and including the Roman period
- Despite this inauspicious history, it was in England that the first truly inclusive society emerged and where the Industrial Revolution got under way
- English divergence had historical roots (Black Death, discovery of the Americas), but the view from Vindolanda suggests these roots were NOT that deep and certainly NOT historically predetermined
- They were not planted in the Neolithic Revolution, or even during the centuries of Roman hegemony
- By AD 450, at the start of what historians call the DARK AGES, England had slipped back into poverty and political chaos — no effective centralized state for hundreds of years

### Diverging Paths (pp. 196-198)
- Rise of inclusive institutions and industrial growth in England did NOT follow as a direct legacy of Roman (or earlier) institutions
- This doesn't mean nothing significant happened with the fall of the Western Roman Empire — a major event affecting most of Europe
- Since different parts of Europe shared the same critical junctures, their institutions would drift in a similar fashion, perhaps in a "distinctly European way"
- Fall of the Roman Empire was a crucial part of these common critical junctures — European path CONTRASTS with sub-Saharan Africa, Asia, and the Americas, which developed differently partly because they did not face the same critical junctures
- Roman England collapsed with a BANG (less true in Italy or Roman Gaul/France, or North Africa, where many old institutions lived on in some form)
- Change from single Roman state to a plethora of states run by Franks, Visigoths, Ostrogoths, Vandals, and Burgundians was significant — these states were far weaker, buffeted by incursions from peripheries
- From the north: Vikings and Danes in longboats
- From the east: Hunnic horsemen
- Emergence of ISLAM as a religion and political force in the century after the death of Mohammed in AD 632 → creation of new Islamic states in most of Byzantine Empire, North Africa, and Spain
- These common processes rocked Europe → a particular type of society called FEUDAL emerged
- Feudal society was decentralized because strong central states had atrophied (even if some rulers like Charlemagne attempted to reconstruct them)
- Feudal institutions relied on unfree, coerced labor (SERFS) → obviously extractive → basis for long period of extractive and slow growth during Middle Ages
- BUT feudalism was also consequential for later developments:
  1. During the reduction of rural population to the status of serfs, SLAVERY DISAPPEARED from Europe — when you can reduce the entire rural population to serfdom, no need for a separate class of slaves
  2. Feudalism created a POWER VACUUM in which independent cities specializing in production and trade could flourish
- When the balance of power changed after the Black Death and serfdom began to crumble in Western Europe → stage was set for a much more PLURALISTIC society without any slaves

### Ethiopia and the Aksum Parallel (pp. 198-199)
- Critical junctures that gave rise to feudal society were not completely restricted to Europe
- Relevant comparison: ETHIOPIA, which developed from the Kingdom of AKSUM, founded in the north of the country around 400 BC
- Aksum was relatively developed: engaged in international trade with India, Arabia, Greece, and the Roman Empire
- Comparable to the Eastern Roman Empire in many ways: used money, built monumental public buildings and roads, had very similar technology in agriculture and shipping
- Ideological parallels too: in AD 312, Roman emperor Constantine converted to Christianity; King EZANA of Aksum did the same at about the same time
- Map 12 shows the historical state of Aksum in modern-day Ethiopia and Eritrea, with outposts across the Red Sea in Saudi Arabia and Yemen
- Just as Rome declined, so did Aksum, following a pattern close to the Western Roman Empire
- The role played by Huns and Vandals in Rome's decline was taken by the ARABS, who in the 7th century expanded into the Red Sea and down the Arabian Peninsula
- Aksum lost its colonies in Arabia and its trade routes → precipitated economic decline: money stopped being coined, urban population fell, state refocused into the interior of the country and up into the highlands of modern Ethiopia

### Ethiopian Feudalism: The Gult System (pp. 199-200)
- In Europe, feudal institutions emerged following the collapse of central state authority — the SAME thing happened in Ethiopia
- Based on a system called *GULT* — a grant of land by the emperor
- *Gult* derived from an Amharic word meaning "he assigned a fief"
- In exchange for the land, the *gult* holder had to provide services to the emperor (particularly military ones)
- In turn, the *gult* holder had the right to EXTRACT TRIBUTE from those who farmed the land
- Historical sources suggest *gult* holders extracted between ONE-HALF and THREE-QUARTERS of the agricultural output of peasants
- This system was an independent development with notable similarities to European feudalism, but probably EVEN MORE EXTRACTIVE
- At the height of feudalism in England, serfs faced less onerous extraction and lost about HALF of their output in one form or another

### Ethiopia Diverges from Europe (pp. 200)
- Ethiopia was NOT representative of Africa — elsewhere, slavery was not replaced by serfdom; African slavery and the institutions that supported it continued for many more centuries
- Even Ethiopia's ultimate path would be very different from Europe's
- After the 7th century, Ethiopia remained isolated in the mountains of East Africa, cut off from the processes that subsequently influenced Europe's institutional path (emergence of independent cities, nascent constraints on monarchs, expansion of Atlantic trade after discovery of Americas)
- In consequence, Ethiopia's version of absolutist institutions remained largely UNCHALLENGED
- The African continent would later interact in a very different capacity with Europe and Asia:
  - East Africa: major supplier of slaves to the Arab world
  - West and Central Africa: drawn into the world economy during European expansion associated with the Atlantic trade as SUPPLIERS OF SLAVES
- How the Atlantic trade led to sharply divergent paths between Western Europe and Africa is yet another example of institutional divergence from critical junctures + existing institutional differences
- While in England the profits of the slave trade helped to ENRICH those who opposed absolutism, in Africa they helped to CREATE AND STRENGTHEN absolutism

### The Americas: A Separate Path (pp. 200-201)
- Farther away from Europe, the processes of institutional drift were obviously even freer to go their own way
- Americas cut off from Europe around 15,000 BC by the melting of the ice that linked Alaska to Russia
- Similar institutional innovations as the Natufians occurred — leading to sedentary life, hierarchy, inequality, in short, EXTRACTIVE INSTITUTIONS
- These took place first in Mexico and in Andean Peru and Bolivia → led to American Neolithic Revolution, with domestication of maize
- In these places that early forms of extractive growth took place (as seen with Maya city-states)
- BUT just as big breakthroughs toward inclusive institutions in Europe did NOT come from places where the Roman world had the strongest hold, inclusive institutions in the Americas did NOT develop in the lands of these early civilizations
- These densely settled civilizations interacted in a perverse way with European colonialism to create a "REVERSAL OF FORTUNE" — making places that were previously relatively wealthy in the Americas relatively poor
- Today it is the US and Canada (which were then far behind the complex civilizations in Mexico, Peru, and Bolivia) that are much richer than the rest of the Americas

### Consequences of Early Growth (pp. 201)
- Long period between the Neolithic Revolution (~9500 BC) and the British Industrial Revolution (late 18th century) is littered with SPURTS of economic growth triggered by institutional innovations that ultimately FALTERED
- Ancient Rome: institutions of the Republic created some economic vitality and allowed construction of a massive empire — unraveled after the coup of Julius Caesar and the construction of the empire under Augustus
- It took centuries for the Roman Empire to finally vanish, and the decline was drawn out — but once relatively inclusive republican institutions gave way to more extractive institutions of the empire, economic regress became all but inevitable
- Venetian dynamics were similar: prosperity forged by institutions with important inclusive elements, but undermined when existing elite closed the system to new entrants and banned the economic institutions (like *commenda*) that had created the republic's prosperity
- However notable, it was NOT Rome's inheritance that led directly to the rise of inclusive institutions in England and the British Industrial Revolution
- Historical factors shape how institutions develop, but this is NOT a simple, predetermined, cumulative process — Rome and Venice illustrate how early steps toward inclusivity were REVERSED
- Economic and institutional landscape Rome created throughout Europe and the Middle East did NOT inexorably lead to firmly rooted inclusive institutions
- In fact, these would emerge first and most strongly in ENGLAND, where the Roman hold was WEAKEST and where it disappeared most decisively (5th century AD)
- History plays a major role through INSTITUTIONAL DRIFT creating institutional differences (albeit sometimes small) which then get amplified when they interact with critical junctures
- Because these differences are often small, they can be reversed easily and are NOT necessarily the consequence of a simple cumulative process
- Of course, Rome had long-lasting effects on Europe: Roman law influenced the laws and institutions of barbarian kingdoms; Rome's fall created the decentralized political landscape that developed into feudal order
- Disappearance of slavery and emergence of independent cities were long, drawn out, and historically contingent by-products of this process
- These would become particularly consequential when the BLACK DEATH shook feudal society deeply → out of the ashes emerged stronger towns and cities, and a peasantry no longer tied to the land and newly free of feudal obligations
- It was precisely these critical junctures unleashed by the fall of the Roman Empire that led to a

### Chapter 6 Conclusion: Europe's Distinctive Path (pp. 202)
- strong institutional drift affecting all of Europe in a way that has no parallel in sub-Saharan Africa, Asia, or the Americas
- By the 16th century, Europe was institutionally very distinct from sub-Saharan Africa and the Americas
- Though not much richer than the most spectacular Asian civilizations in India or China, Europe differed in key ways — it had developed REPRESENTATIVE INSTITUTIONS of a sort unseen there
- These would play a critical role in the development of inclusive institutions
- In the next two chapters, small institutional differences WITHIN Europe would be the ones that really matter — and these FAVORED ENGLAND, because it was there that the feudal order had made way most comprehensively for commercially minded farmers and independent urban centers where merchants and industrialists could flourish
- These groups were already demanding more secure property rights, different economic institutions, and political voice from their monarchs
- This whole process would come to a head in the 17th century

---

## CHAPTER 7: THE TURNING POINT (pp. 203-260)

### Trouble with Stockings (pp. 203-205)
- In 1583, WILLIAM LEE returned from University of Cambridge to become the local priest in Calverton, England
- Queen Elizabeth I (1558-1603) had recently issued a ruling that her people should always wear a knitted cap
- Lee watched his mother and sisters sitting in the evening twilight plying their needles — if garments were made by two needles and one line of thread, why not SEVERAL needles to take up the thread?
- This was the beginning of the MECHANIZATION OF TEXTILE PRODUCTION
- Lee became obsessed with making a machine, neglecting his church duties and family — KEY QUOTE: "My duties to Church and family I began to neglect. The idea of my machine and the creating of it ate into my heart and brain."
- Finally in 1589, his "STOCKING FRAME" knitting machine was ready
- Traveled to London to seek an interview with Elizabeth I to show her the machine and ask for a PATENT
- With help of his local MP Richard Parkyns, met Henry Carey, Lord Hundson (member of Queen's Privy Council), who arranged for the Queen to see the machine
- Queen Elizabeth's reaction was DEVASTATING — she refused to grant Lee a patent
- KEY QUOTE (Elizabeth I): "Thou aimest high, Master Lee. Consider thou what the invention could do to my poor subjects. It would assuredly bring to them ruin by depriving them of employment, thus making them beggars."
- Lee moved to France to try his luck — failed there too
- Returned to England, asked JAMES I (1603-1625, Elizabeth's successor) for a patent — James I ALSO REFUSED on the same grounds
- Both feared that mechanization of stocking production would be POLITICALLY DESTABILIZING — throwing people out of work, creating unemployment and political instability, threatening royal power
- The stocking frame was an innovation promising huge productivity increases, but it also promised CREATIVE DESTRUCTION

### The Key Idea: Fear of Creative Destruction (pp. 205-206)
- Reaction to Lee's invention illustrates a key idea of the book
- Fear of creative destruction is the main reason there was no sustained increase in living standards between the Neolithic and Industrial Revolutions
- Technological innovation makes societies prosperous but also involves replacement of the old with the new → destruction of economic privileges and political power of certain people
- For sustained growth: need new technologies, new ways of doing things, from NEWCOMERS like Lee — more often than not
- Creative destruction threatens the livelihood of those who work with old technologies (hand-knitters would have been made unemployed by Lee's technology)
- More important: major innovations like the stocking frame also threaten to RESHAPE POLITICAL POWER
- It was NOT concern about the fate of the unemployed that led Elizabeth I and James I to oppose Lee's patent — it was their fear that THEY would become political losers — that those displaced would create political instability and threaten their power
- While it is often possible to bypass the resistance of workers (as with the Luddites), the elite, especially when their POLITICAL POWER is threatened, form a more formidable barrier to innovation
- Elites who stand to lose from creative destruction will not only not be the ones introducing new innovations but will ACTIVELY RESIST and try to STOP such innovations
- Society needs newcomers to introduce radical innovations, and these newcomers and the creative destruction they wreak must overcome several sources of resistance, including from powerful rulers and elites
- Prior to 17th-century England, extractive institutions were the norm throughout history — could generate some growth (as shown in last two chapters, especially when containing inclusive elements, as in Venice and Rome) but did not permit creative destruction → growth was not sustained
- Life expectancy of a resident of the Natufian village of Abu Hureyra was probably not that much different from that of a citizen of Ancient Rome, which was fairly similar to that of an average inhabitant of England in the 17th century
- In terms of incomes: in AD 301, emperor Diocletian issued the Edict on Maximum Prices — economic historian Robert Allen used these wages to calculate living standards and found them to be almost exactly the SAME as those of an unskilled worker in 17th-century Italy
- Farther north, in England, wages were HIGHER and increasing — things were changing. How this came to be is the topic of this chapter

### Ever-Present Political Conflict (pp. 206-209)
- Conflict over institutions and distribution of resources has been pervasive throughout history — shaped evolution of Ancient Rome, Venice
- In both Rome and Venice, conflict was ultimately resolved in favor of the elites, who increased their hold on power
- English history is also full of conflict between monarchy and subjects, between factions, between elites and citizens — but the outcome has NOT always been to strengthen those who held power

### Magna Carta (1215) (pp. 206-207)
- In 1215, the BARONS (layer of elite beneath the king) stood up to King JOHN and made him sign the MAGNA CARTA ("the Great Charter") at Runnymede
- Enacted some basic principles that were significant challenges to the authority of the king
- Most important: established that the king had to CONSULT with the barons in order to RAISE TAXES
- Most contentious clause: NUMBER 61 — "the barons shall choose any twenty-five barons of the realm they wish, who with all their might are to observe, maintain and cause to be observed the peace and liberties which we have granted and confirmed to them by this our present charter"
- In essence: barons created a council to make sure king implemented the charter — if he didn't, the 25 barons could seize castles, lands, and possessions "until, in their judgement, amends have been made"
- King John didn't like it — as soon as the barons dispersed, he got the POPE to annul it
- But both the political power of the barons and the influence of the Magna Carta remained
- England had taken its first hesitant step toward PLURALISM

### Parliament and the War of the Roses (pp. 207-208)
- Conflict continued; power of the monarchy was further constrained by the first elected PARLIAMENT in 1265
- Unlike the Roman Plebeian Assembly or modern elected legislatures, its members were originally feudal nobles, then knights and the wealthiest aristocrats of the nation
- Despite consisting of elites, English Parliament developed TWO distinguishing characteristics:
  1. It represented not only elites closely allied to the king but also a BROAD SET of interests — minor aristocrats involved in different walks of life, commerce, industry, and later the "GENTRY" (a new class of commercial and upwardly mobile farmers) → Parliament empowered a quite broad section of society by the standards of the time
  2. Largely as a result of the first characteristic, many members consistently OPPOSED the monarchy's attempts to increase its power → would become the mainstay of those fighting the monarchy in the English Civil War and the Glorious Revolution
- Despite Magna Carta and Parliament, political conflict continued over powers of the monarchy and who would be king
- This intra-elite conflict ended with the WAR OF THE ROSES — a long duel between the Houses of Lancaster and York
- Winners: the LANCASTRIANS, whose candidate Henry Tudor became HENRY VII in 1485

### Tudor Political Centralization (pp. 208-209)
- Two interrelated processes took place:
  1. INCREASING POLITICAL CENTRALIZATION, put in motion by the Tudors
     - After 1485, Henry VII DISARMED the aristocracy, in effect demilitarizing them → massively expanding the power of the central state
     - His son HENRY VIII, through chief minister THOMAS CROMWELL, implemented a "revolution in government" in the 1530s
     - Cromwell introduced a nascent BUREAUCRATIC STATE — instead of the government being just the private household of the king, it could become a separate set of enduring institutions
     - Complemented by Henry VIII's break with the ROMAN CATHOLIC CHURCH and the "DISSOLUTION OF THE MONASTERIES" — expropriated all Church lands, removing the power of the Church
     - This centralization of state institutions meant that for the first time, INCLUSIVE POLITICAL INSTITUTIONS became possible
  2. This process not only centralized state institutions but also INCREASED THE DEMAND for broader-based political representation
     - When barons and local elites recognized political power would be increasingly more centralized and this process was hard to stop, they made demands to have a say in how this centralized power was used
     - In England during the late 15th and 16th centuries, this meant greater efforts by these groups to have Parliament as a COUNTERWEIGHT against the Crown
     - Thus the Tudor project of political centralization initiated one pillar of inclusive institutions (centralization) but also indirectly contributed to PLURALISM, the other pillar

### Broadening of Political Conflict (pp. 209)
- Particularly significant: the WIDENING of political conflict, broadening the set of groups with the ability to make demands on the monarchy and political elites
- The PEASANTS' REVOLT OF 1381 was pivotal — after which the English elite were rocked by a long sequence of popular insurrections
- Political power was being redistributed not simply from the king to the lords, but also from the ELITE TO THE PEOPLE
- These changes, together with increasing constraints on the king's power, made the emergence of a broad coalition opposed to absolutism possible → laid the foundations for pluralistic political institutions

### Stuart England: Extractive Institutions and Monopolies (pp. 209-211)
- Despite the contested political and economic institutions the Tudors inherited and sustained, these were clearly EXTRACTIVE
- In 1603, Elizabeth I (Henry VIII's daughter, on throne since 1553) died without children → Tudors replaced by the STUART DYNASTY
- First Stuart king, JAMES I, inherited not only the institutions but the conflicts over them
- He desired to be an absolutist ruler — though the state had become more centralized and social change was redistributing power, political institutions were NOT yet pluralistic
- In the economy, extractive institutions manifested as MONOPOLIES — not just opposition to Lee's invention but monopolies in many goods
- In 1601, a list of monopolies was read out in Parliament — one member ironically asked, "Is not bread there?"
- By 1621: there were SEVEN HUNDRED monopolies
- KEY QUOTE (historian Christopher Hill): "a man lived in a house built with monopoly bricks, with windows... of monopoly glass; heated by monopoly coal, burning in a grate made of monopoly iron... He washed himself in monopoly soap, his clothes in monopoly starch. He dressed in monopoly lace, monopoly linen, monopoly leather, monopoly gold thread... His clothes were held up by monopoly belts, monopoly buttons, monopoly pins. They were dyed with monopoly dyes. He ate monopoly butter, monopoly currants, monopoly red herrings, monopoly salmon, and monopoly lobsters. His food was seasoned with monopoly salt, monopoly pepper, monopoly vinegar... He wrote with monopoly pens, on monopoly writing paper; read (through monopoly spectacles, by the light of monopoly candles) monopoly printed books."
- These monopolies gave individuals or groups SOLE RIGHT to control production of many goods → impeded allocation of talent, crucial to economic prosperity
- Both James I and his son and successor CHARLES I aspired to strengthen the monarchy, reduce Parliament's influence, and establish ABSOLUTIST institutions similar to those being constructed in Spain and France

### The Road to Civil War (pp. 211-212)
- Conflict between James I and Parliament came to a head in the 1620s
- Central to the conflict: control of trade both overseas and within the British Isles
- Crown's ability to grant monopolies was a key source of revenue and a way of granting exclusive rights to supporters — an extractive institution blocking entry and inhibiting the functioning of the market
- Highly damaging to economic activity and to the interests of many members of Parliament
- In 1623: Parliament scored a notable victory — passed the STATUTE OF MONOPOLIES, prohibiting James I from creating new DOMESTIC monopolies (though he could still grant monopolies on international trade, and existing monopolies stood)
- Parliament did not sit regularly and had to be CALLED into session by the king
- Convention after Magna Carta: king must convene Parliament to get assent for new taxes
- CHARLES I came to the throne in 1625, declined to call Parliament after 1629, and intensified James I's efforts to build a more solidly absolutist regime:
  - Induced FORCED LOANS (people had to "lend" him money, and he unilaterally changed the terms and refused to repay debts)
  - Created and sold monopolies in the one dimension the Statute of Monopolies had left to him: OVERSEAS trading ventures
  - Undermined INDEPENDENCE OF THE JUDICIARY and attempted to influence the outcome of legal cases
  - Levied many fines and charges, the most contentious being "SHIP MONEY" — in 1634, taxed coastal counties to pay for the Royal Navy; in 1635, extended the levy to inland counties; levied each year until 1640
- Charles's increasingly absolutist and extractive policies created RESENTMENT and resistance throughout the country
- In 1640: faced conflict with Scotland but without enough money to put a proper army in the field → forced to call Parliament to ask for more taxes
- The so-called SHORT PARLIAMENT sat for only three weeks — parliamentarians refused to talk about taxes and instead aired grievances until Charles dismissed them
- The Scots realized Charles lacked the nation's support → invaded England, occupying Newcastle
- Charles opened negotiations; Scots demanded Parliament be involved → Charles called what became known as the LONG PARLIAMENT (sat from 1640 until 1648, refusing to dissolve even when Charles demanded it)

### The English Civil War (pp. 212-213)
- In 1642: Civil War broke out between Charles and Parliament, though many in Parliament sided with the Crown
- Pattern of conflicts reflected the struggle over economic and political institutions
- Parliament wanted an end to absolutist political institutions; the king wanted them strengthened
- Economic roots of the conflict:
  - Many supported the Crown because they had been granted lucrative MONOPOLIES — e.g., rich and powerful merchants of Shrewsbury and Oswestry, whose local monopolies were protected by the Crown from competition by London merchants → these merchants sided with Charles I
  - On the other side, the metallurgical industry around BIRMINGHAM flourished precisely because monopolies were WEAK there and newcomers did not have to serve a 7-year apprenticeship as they did elsewhere → during the Civil War, they made swords and produced volunteers for the parliamentary side
  - Similarly, LANCASHIRE (county lacking guild regulation) saw the development before 1640 of the "NEW DRAPERIES" (lighter cloth) — the area concentrated in this production was the only part of Lancashire to support Parliament
- Under the leadership of OLIVER CROMWELL, the Parliamentarians (known as the ROUNDHEADS, after their hairstyle) defeated the royalists (known as CAVALIERS)
- Charles was tried and EXECUTED in 1649
- His defeat and the abolition of the monarchy did NOT, however, result in inclusive institutions → monarchy was replaced by the DICTATORSHIP OF OLIVER CROMWELL
- Following Cromwell's death, monarchy was RESTORED in 1660 — and clawed back many of the privileges that had been stripped from it in 1649
- Charles's son, CHARLES II, then set about creating absolutism in England
- Attempts intensified by his brother JAMES II, who ascended to the throne after Charles's death in 1685
- In 1688: James's attempt to reestablish absolutism created another crisis and another civil war
- This time Parliament was more UNITED and ORGANIZED → they invited the Dutch *Statholder* WILLIAM OF ORANGE and his wife MARY (James's Protestant daughter) to replace James
- William would bring an army and claim the throne, to rule not as an absolutist monarch but under a CONSTITUTIONAL MONARCHY forged by Parliament
- Two months after William's landing at BRIXHAM in Devon (Map 9), James's army disintegrated and he fled to France

### The Glorious Revolution (pp. 213-216)
- After victory in the Glorious Revolution, Parliament and William negotiated a new constitution
- Changes foreshadowed by William's "Declaration," made shortly prior to his invasion
- Further enshrined in the DECLARATION OF RIGHTS, produced by Parliament in February 1689
- Declaration read out to William at the same session where he was offered the crown
- After signing into law, became known as the BILL OF RIGHTS — though vague in many ways, it established some central constitutional principles:
  1. Determined the SUCCESSION TO THE THRONE in a way that departed significantly from hereditary principles — if Parliament could remove a monarch and replace him with one more to their liking once, why not again?
  2. Asserted that the monarch could not SUSPEND or DISPENSE with laws
  3. Reiterated the ILLEGALITY OF TAXATION without parliamentary consent
  4. Stated there could be no STANDING ARMY in England without parliamentary consent
  5. Clause 8: "The election of members of Parliament ought to be free" (though did not specify how "free" was to be determined)
  6. Clause 13: "Parliaments ought to be held frequently" (deliberately vague)
- Why the vagueness? Clauses have to be ENFORCED — during Charles II's reign, a Triennial Act had asserted Parliaments must be called at least every 3 years, but Charles ignored it and nothing happened because there was no method of enforcement
- After 1688: Parliament could have introduced a method for enforcing this clause (as the barons had done with their council after the Magna Carta) — they did NOT need to because AUTHORITY AND DECISION-MAKING POWER switched to Parliament after 1688
- Even without specific constitutional rules, William simply gave up on many of the practices of previous kings — stopped interfering in legal decisions, gave up previous "rights" such as getting customs revenues for life
- TAKEN TOGETHER: these changes in political institutions represented the TRIUMPH OF PARLIAMENT over the king and thus the end of ABSOLUTISM in England
- Subsequently: Great Britain (as England and Scotland were united by the ACT OF UNION in 1707) — from then on Parliament was FIRMLY IN CONTROL of state policy
- This made a HUGE DIFFERENCE because Parliament's interests were very different from those of the Stuart kings:
  - Many parliamentarians had important investments in trade and industry → strong stake in enforcing PROPERTY RIGHTS (Stuarts had frequently infringed on them)
  - When Stuarts controlled how government spent money, Parliament opposed greater taxes and balked at strengthening the state — now that Parliament itself controlled spending, it was HAPPY to raise taxes and spend on activities it deemed valuable, chief among them the NAVY (which would protect the overseas mercantile interests of many members)

### Pluralism After 1688: Petitioning (pp. 215-216)
- Even more important than the interests of parliamentarians was the emerging PLURALISTIC nature of political institutions
- English people now had access to Parliament and the policy/economic institutions made in Parliament in a way they never had when policy was driven by the king
- This was partially because members of Parliament were elected — but since England was far from being a democracy, this access provided only MODEST responsiveness
- Among the inequities: less than 2% of the population could vote (and these had to be men)
- Cities where the Industrial Revolution took place (Birmingham, Leeds, Manchester, Sheffield) had NO independent representation in Parliament
- Rural areas were overrepresented — the right to vote in "counties" was based on OWNERSHIP OF LAND, and many urban "boroughs" were controlled by a small elite who did not allow new industrialists to vote or run for office
- "ROTTEN BOROUGHS": boroughs that historically had the right to vote but had "rotted away" (population moved or, in the case of Dunwich on the east coast, had actually fallen into the ocean due to coastal erosion) — yet each still elected two members of Parliament (Old Sarum had 7 voters, Dunwich had 32)
- BUT there were other ways to influence Parliament — the most important was via PETITIONING
- This was MUCH more significant than the limited democracy for the emergence of pluralism after the Glorious Revolution
- Anybody could petition Parliament, and people DID
- Significantly, when people petitioned, Parliament LISTENED — this more than anything reflects the defeat of absolutism, the empowerment of a fairly broad segment of society, and the rise of pluralism in England after 1688
- The frantic petitioning activity shows that a broad group in society, far beyond those sitting in or even being represented in Parliament, had the power to influence the way the state worked — and they used it

### The End of Monopolies: The Royal African Company (pp. 216)
- Case of monopolies best illustrates how petitioning worked
- Monopolies were at the heart of extractive economic institutions in the 17th century — came under attack in 1623 with the Statute of Monopolies, were a serious bone of contention during the English Civil War
- The Long Parliament abolished all domestic monopolies that so impinged on people's lives
- Though Charles II and James II could not bring domestic monopolies back, they maintained the ability to grant OVERSEAS monopolies
- One example: the ROYAL AFRICAN COMPANY, whose monopoly charter was issued by Charles II in 1660
- This company held a monopoly on the lucrative African slave trade; its governor and major shareholder was Charles's brother James (soon to become James II)
- After 1688: the Company lost not just its governor but its main supporter
- James had assiduously protected the monopoly against "INTERLOPERS" — independent traders who tried to buy slaves in West Africa and sell them in the Americas
- This was very profitable trade and the Royal African Company faced a lot of challenges since all OTHER English trade in the Atlantic was FREE
- In 1689: the Company seized the cargo of an interloper named NIGHTINGALE — Nightingale sued for illegal seizure of goods
- Chief Justice HOLT ruled that the Company's seizure was UNLAWFUL because it was exercising a monopoly right created by royal prerogative
- Holt reasoned that monopoly privileges could be created only by STATUTE, and this had to be done by PARLIAMENT → Holt pushed ALL future monopolies, not just the Royal African Company, into the hands of Parliament
- Before 1688, James II would have quickly removed any judge who made such a ruling — after 1688, things were different
- Parliament now had to decide what to do with the monopoly → petitions began to fly
- 135 petitions came from interlopers demanding free access to trade in the Atlantic
- The Royal African Company responded in kind but could not match the number or scope of petitions demanding its demise
- KEY STATS on petitioning:
  - Only 5 of the 135 petitions were signed by the interlopers themselves
  - 73 of the interlopers' petitions came from provinces outside London (vs. 8 for the Company)
  - From the colonies (where petitioning was also allowed): interlopers gathered 27 petitions, the Company 11
  - Interlopers gathered far more signatures: 8,000 total vs. 2,500 for the Company
- The struggle continued until 1698, when the Royal African Company monopoly was ABOLISHED

### Economic Reforms After the Glorious Revolution (pp. 216)
- Along with the new locus for determination of economic institutions and the new responsiveness after 1688, parliamentarians started making a series of KEY CHANGES in economic institutions and government policy that would ultimately pave the way for the Industrial Revolution
- Property rights eroded under the Stuarts were STRENGTHENED
- Parliament began a process of reform in economic institutions to promote manufacturing rather than taxing and impeding it
- The "HEARTH TAX" — an annual tax for each fireplace or stove, which fell most heavily on manufacturers who were bitterly opposed to it — was ABOLISHED in 1689, soon after William and Mary ascended the throne
- Instead of taxing hearths, Parliament moved to start taxing LAND
- Redistributing the tax burden was not the only pro-manufacturing policy: a whole series of acts and legislations expanding the market and the profitability of WOOLEN TEXTILES was passed — made political sense since many parliamentarians who opposed James were heavily invested in these nascent manufacturing enterprises
- Parliament also passed legislation allowing for a complete reorganization of PROPERTY RIGHTS IN LAND, permitting the consolidation and elimination of many archaic forms of property and user rights
- Another priority: reforming FINANCE
  - Though there had been expansion of banking and finance in the period leading up to the Glorious Revolution, this process was further cemented by the creation of the BANK OF ENGLAND in 1694 — a source of funds for industry and another direct consequence of the Glorious Revolution
  - The Bank of England paved the way for a much more extensive "FINANCIAL REVOLUTION" — great expansion of financial markets and banking
  - By the early 18th century, loans would be available to EVERYONE who could put up the necessary collateral
  - Records of a relatively small bank, C. HOARE'S & CO. in London (surviving intact from 1702-1724), illustrate this: though the bank did lend money to aristocrats and lords, fully TWO-THIRDS of the biggest borrowers from Hoare's were NOT from the privileged social classes — instead they were merchants and businessmen

### Political Centralization Continued After 1688 (pp. 217-218)
- One more significant change from the Glorious Revolution: Parliament continued the process of POLITICAL CENTRALIZATION initiated by the Tudors
- Not just that constraints increased, or that the state regulated the economy differently, or spent money differently — but the CAPABILITY and CAPACITY of the state increased in all directions
- This illustrates the linkage between political centralization and pluralism: Parliament had OPPOSED making the state more effective and better resourced prior to 1688 because it could not control it — after 1688, it was a different story
- The state started expanding, with expenditures soon reaching around 10% OF NATIONAL INCOME
- Underpinned by expansion of the tax base, particularly the EXCISE TAX (levied on production of a long list of domestically produced commodities)
- This was a very large state budget for the period — LARGER than what many parts of the world have today
- State budgets in Colombia only reached this relative size in the 1980s; in many parts of sub-Saharan Africa (e.g., Sierra Leone), the state budget even today would be far smaller relative to the economy without large inflows of foreign aid

### The Excise Tax Bureaucracy (pp. 218)
- More important than the size of the state was the QUALITATIVE way it functioned and how those who controlled it and worked in it behaved
- Construction of state institutions reached back into the Middle Ages, with decisive steps taken by Henry VII and Henry VIII — but the state was still far from the modern form that would emerge after 1688
- Before 1688: many appointees were made on political grounds, not merit or talent, and the state had very limited capacity to raise taxes
- After 1688: Parliament began to improve revenue through taxation — well illustrated by the excise tax bureaucracy
- Excise tax bureaucracy expanded rapidly from 1,211 people in 1690 to 4,800 by 1780
- Excise tax inspectors stationed throughout the country, supervised by collectors on tours of inspection to measure and check the amount of bread, beer, and other goods subject to excise tax
- EXAMPLE: historian John Brewer reconstructed the excise rounds of Supervisor George COWPERTHWAITE
  - Between June 12 and July 5, 1710: traveled 290 miles in the Richmond district of Yorkshire
  - Visited 263 victualers, 71 maltsters, 20 chandlers, and one common brewer
  - Took 81 different measurements of production and checked the work of 9 excisemen
  - Eight years later, in the Wakefield district: traveled more than 19 miles a day on average, worked 6 days a week, normally inspecting 4 or 5 premises
  - On his day off (Sunday): made up his books — so we have a complete record of his activities
- Excise tax system had very elaborate record keeping — officers kept THREE different types of records, all of which were supposed to match one another; tampering was a serious offense
- This remarkable level of state supervision EXCEEDS what the governments of most poor countries can achieve today — and this was in 1710
- Also significantly, after 1688 the state began to rely more on TALENT and less on political appointees, and developed a powerful infrastructure to run the country

### The Industrial Revolution (pp. 218-224)
- Industrial Revolution was manifested in every aspect of the English economy — major improvements in transportation, metallurgy, and steam power
- BUT the most significant area of innovation was the MECHANIZATION OF TEXTILE PRODUCTION and the development of factories to produce manufactured textiles
- This dynamic process was unleashed by the institutional changes flowing from the Glorious Revolution
- Not just about the abolition of domestic monopolies (achieved by 1640), or about different taxes or access to finance — it was about a FUNDAMENTAL REORGANIZATION of economic institutions in favor of innovators and entrepreneurs, based on the emergence of more secure and efficient PROPERTY RIGHTS

### The Transportation Revolution (pp. 219-220)
- Improvements in the security and efficiency of property rights played a central role in the "TRANSPORTATION REVOLUTION" paving the way for the Industrial Revolution
- Investment in canals and roads (the so-called TURNPIKES) massively increased after 1688
- These investments reduced transportation costs → created an important prerequisite for the Industrial Revolution
- Prior to 1688, investment in infrastructure had been impeded by arbitrary acts of Stuart kings
- EXAMPLE: the case of the river SALWERPE in Worcestershire
  - In 1662 Parliament passed an act to encourage investment to make the Salwerpe navigable
  - The BALDWYN family invested £6,000 — in return they got the right to charge people for navigation on the river
  - In 1693: a bill was introduced to Parliament to TRANSFER the rights to charge for navigation to the Earl of Shrewsbury and Lord Coventry
  - Sir Timothy Baldwyn immediately challenged this — submitted a petition to Parliament claiming the proposed bill was essentially EXPROPRIATING his father, who had invested heavily in anticipation of the charges he could then levy
  - Baldwyn argued: "the new act tends to make void the said act, and to take away all the works and materials done in pursuance thereof" — this was exactly the sort of thing done by Stuart monarchs
  - KEY QUOTE (Baldwyn): "[I]t is of dangerous consequence to take away any person's right, purchased under an act of Parliament, without their consent"
  - The new act FAILED, and Baldwyn's rights were upheld → property rights were much more secure after 1688

### Land Reorganization (pp. 220)
- Underlying the transportation revolution was the reorganization of LAND that took place in the 18th century via parliamentary acts that changed the nature of property ownership
- Until 1688 there was even the legal fiction that all land in England was ultimately owned by the Crown — a direct legacy of feudal organization
- Many pieces of land were encumbered by numerous archaic forms of property rights and many cross-cutting claims
- Much land was held in so-called "equitable estates" — the landowner could not mortgage, lease, or sell the land
- Common land could often be used only for traditional uses
- There were enormous impediments to using land in economically desirable ways
- Parliament began to change this, allowing groups of people to petition Parliament to simplify and reorganize property rights → these alterations were subsequently embodied in HUNDREDS of acts of Parliament

### Domestic Protection vs. Inclusive Institutions (pp. 220-222)
- Reorganization of economic institutions also manifested in an agenda to PROTECT domestic textile production against foreign imports
- Not surprisingly, parliamentarians and their constituents were NOT opposed to all entry barriers and monopolies — those that would increase their own market and profits would be welcome
- However, crucially, the PLURALISTIC political institutions — the fact that Parliament represented, empowered, and listened to a broad segment of society — meant that these entry barriers would NOT choke other industrialists or completely shut out newcomers, as the *Serrata* did in Venice
- The powerful woolen manufacturers soon made this discovery
- In 1688: some of the most significant imports into England were textiles from India — calicoes and muslins (about 1/4 of all textile imports) and silks from China
- Before 1688: calicoes and silks imported by the EAST INDIA COMPANY, which enjoyed a government-sanctioned MONOPOLY on trade with Asia (sustained through heavy bribes to James II)
- After 1688: company was in a vulnerable position and soon under attack via an intense war of petitions
- Traders hoping to compete in trade with the Far East and India demanded Parliament sanction competition
- Company responded with counterpetitions and offers to lend Parliament money → the company LOST, and a new East India Company to compete with it was founded
- But textile producers did not just want more competition in the trade to India — they wanted imports of cheap Indian textiles (calicoes) TAXED or even BANNED because they faced strong competition from these cheap imports
- At this point the most important domestic manufacturers produced WOOLEN textiles, but producers of COTTON cloths were becoming both more important economically and more powerful politically

### The Wool vs. Cotton Battle (pp. 221-222)
- Wool industry mounted attempts to protect itself as early as the 1660s — promoted the "SUMPTUARY LAWS" (prohibited wearing lighter cloth) and lobbied Parliament to pass legislation in 1666 and 1678 making it ILLEGAL for someone to be buried in anything other than a woolen shroud
- Both measures protected the market for woolen goods and reduced competition from Asia
- Despite this, in this period the East India Company was too strong to restrict imports of Asian textiles
- The tide changed after 1688 — between 1696 and 1698, woolen manufacturers from East Anglia and the West Country allied with silk weavers from London, Canterbury, and the Levant Company
- Silk importers from the Levant (who had recently lost their monopoly) wished to exclude Asian silks to create a niche for silks from the Ottoman Empire
- This coalition started to present bills to Parliament to restrict wearing of Asian cottons and silks, and restrictions on dyeing and printing of Asian textiles in England
- In response, in 1701 Parliament passed "an Act for the more effectual imploying the poor, by incouraging the manufactures of this kingdom"
- From September 1701: decreed that all wrought silks, bengals, stuffs mixed with silk of Persia, China, or East-India, and all calicoes painted, dyed, printed, or stained, "shall not be worn"
- It was now illegal to WEAR Asian silks and calicoes in England (though still possible to import them for reexport or for the American colonies)
- Moreover, plain calicoes could be imported and FINISHED in England, and muslins were exempt from the ban
- After a long struggle, these loopholes (as domestic woolen manufacturers viewed them) were closed by the CALICOE ACT OF 1721: "After December 25, 1722, it shall not be lawful for any person or persons whatsoever to use or wear in Great Britain, in any garment or apparel whatsoever, any printed, painted, stained or dyed Calicoe"
- Though this removed competition from Asia for English woolens, it still left an active domestic cotton and linen industry competing against woolens — cotton and linen were mixed to produce a popular cloth called FUSTIAN
- Having excluded Asian competition, the wool industry now turned to clamp down on LINEN (primarily made in Scotland and Ireland) → gave scope to an English coalition to demand those countries' exclusion from English markets
- BUT there were limits to the power of the woolen manufacturers — their new attempts encountered strong opposition from fustian producers in the burgeoning industrial centers of Manchester, Lancaster, and Liverpool
- The pluralistic political institutions implied that ALL these different groups now had access to the policy process in Parliament via voting and, more important, PETITIONING
- Though petitions flew from both sides, the outcome was a VICTORY for the new interests against the wool industry
- The MANCHESTER ACT OF 1736 agreed that "great quantities of stuffs made from linen yarn and cotton wool have for several years past been manufactured, and have been printed and painted within this kingdom of Great Britain"
- It then asserted that "nothing in the said recited Act [of 1721] shall extend or be construed to prohibit the wearing or using in apparel, household stuff, furniture or otherwise, any sort of stuff made out of linen yarn and cotton wool, manufactured and printed or painted with any colour or colours within the kingdom of Great Britain"

### Significance of the Manchester Act (pp. 222-223)
- The Manchester Act was a significant victory for the nascent cotton manufacturers — but its historical and economic significance was much greater
- FIRST: it demonstrated the LIMITS of entry barriers that the pluralistic political institutions of parliamentary England would permit
- SECOND: over the next half century, technological innovations in the manufacture of cotton cloth would play a central role in the Industrial Revolution and fundamentally transform society by introducing the FACTORY SYSTEM
- After 1688, though domestically a level playing field emerged, INTERNATIONALLY Parliament strove to tilt it
- This was evident not only from the Calicoe Acts but also from the NAVIGATION ACTS (first passed in 1651, remained in force with alternations for the next 200 years)
- Aim: to facilitate England's MONOPOLIZATION of international trade — though crucially this was monopolization not by the state but by the PRIVATE SECTOR
- Basic principle: English trade should be carried in English ships; illegal for foreign ships to transport goods from outside Europe to England or its colonies, and similarly illegal for third-party countries' ships to ship goods from elsewhere in Europe to England
- This advantage for English traders and manufacturers naturally increased their profits and may have further encouraged innovation in these highly profitable activities

### By 1760: Innovation Takes Off (pp. 223-224)
- By 1760 the combination of all these factors — improved and new property rights, improved infrastructure, changed fiscal regime, greater access to finance, aggressive protection of traders and manufacturers — was beginning to have an effect
- After this date there was a JUMP in the number of patented inventions
- The great flowering of technological change that was to be at the heart of the Industrial Revolution began to be evident
- Innovations took place on many fronts, reflecting the improved institutional environment
- One crucial area: POWER — most famously the transformations in the use of the steam engine as a result of JAMES WATT's ideas in the 1760s
  - Watt's initial breakthrough: introduce a separate condensing chamber for the steam so that the cylinder housing the piston could be kept continually hot (instead of having to be warmed up and cooled down)
  - He subsequently developed many other ideas including more efficient methods of converting the motion of the steam engine into useful power, notably his "SUN AND PLANETS" gear system
  - In all these areas, Watt built on earlier work by English inventor THOMAS NEWCOMEN and also by DIONYSIUS PAPIN, a French physicist and inventor

### Papin's Steamboat: Creative Destruction Blocked (pp. 224-225)
- The story of PAPIN's invention is another example of how extractive institutions and the threat of creative destruction impeded technological change
- Papin developed a design for a "STEAM DIGESTER" in 1679; in 1690, extended this into a PISTON ENGINE
- In 1705: used this rudimentary engine to build the world's FIRST STEAMBOAT
- Papin was by this time a professor of mathematics at the University of Marburg in the German state of Kassel
- Decided to steam the boat down the river Fulda to the river Weser — any boat making this trip was forced to stop at the city of MÜNDEN
- At that time, river traffic on the Fulda and Weser was the MONOPOLY of a guild of boatmen
- Papin must have sensed trouble — his friend and mentor, the famous German physicist GOTTFRIED LEIBNIZ, wrote to the Elector of Kassel, petitioning that Papin should be allowed to "pass unmolested" through Kassel
- Leibniz's petition was REBUFFED — the curt answer was that "the Electoral Councillors have found serious obstacles in the way of granting the above petition, and, without giving their reasons, have directed me to inform you of their decision, and that in consequence the request is not granted by his Electoral Highness"
- Undeterred, Papin decided to make the journey anyway — when his steamer arrived at Münden, the boatmen's guild first tried to get a local judge to IMPOUND the ship (unsuccessful); the boatmen then set upon Papin's boat and SMASHED it and the steam engine to pieces
- Papin died a pauper and was buried in an UNMARKED GRAVE
- In Tudor or Stuart England, Papin might have received similar hostile treatment — but after 1688, this all changed
- Indeed, Papin was intending to sail his boat to LONDON before it was destroyed

### Metallurgy Innovations (pp. 225)
- In metallurgy, key contributions made in the 1780s by HENRY CORT — introduced new techniques for dealing with impurities in iron, allowing for much better quality WROUGHT IRON
- This was critical for the manufacture of machine parts, nails, and tools
- Production of vast quantities of wrought iron using Cort's techniques was facilitated by the innovations of ABRAHAM DARBY and his sons, who pioneered the use of coal to smelt iron beginning in 1709
- Process enhanced in 1762 by JOHN SMEATON's adaptation of water power to operate blowing cylinders in making coke
- After this, charcoal vanished from the production of iron, replaced by coal — much cheaper and more readily available

### The Textile Revolution (pp. 225-226)
- Though innovation was obviously cumulative, there was a distinct acceleration in the middle of the 18th century — nowhere more visible than in TEXTILE PRODUCTION
- Basic operation: SPINNING (taking plant or animal fibers like cotton or wool and twisting them together to form yarn) → then WEAVING
- One of the great medieval innovations: the SPINNING WHEEL (appeared around 1280 in Europe, probably disseminating from the Middle East)
- Methods of spinning did not change until the 18th century
- Significant innovations began in 1738 when LEWIS PAUL patented a new method of spinning using rollers (didn't work well)
- It was the innovations of RICHARD ARKWRIGHT and JAMES HARGREAVES that truly revolutionized spinning
- In 1769: Arkwright (one of the dominant figures of the Industrial Revolution) patented his "WATER FRAME" — a huge improvement over Lewis's machine
  - Formed a partnership with JEDEDIAH STRUTT and SAMUEL NEED (hosiery manufacturers)
  - In 1771: they built one of the world's FIRST FACTORIES at CROMFORD
  - New machines powered by water (Arkwright later made the crucial transition to STEAM power)
  - By 1774: his firm employed 600 workers; expanded aggressively to factories in Manchester, Matlock, Bath, and New Lanark in Scotland
- Arkwright's innovations complemented by Hargreaves's invention in 1764 of the SPINNING JENNY
  - Further developed by SAMUEL CROMPTON in 1779 into the "MULE"
  - Later by RICHARD ROBERTS into the "SELF-ACTING MULE"
- KEY STAT: the effects of these innovations were truly revolutionary — earlier in the century, it took 50,000 HOURS for hand spinners to spin 100 pounds of cotton; Arkwright's water frame could do it in 300 hours, and the self-acting mule in 135 hours
- Along with mechanization of spinning came mechanization of WEAVING:
  - Important first step: JOHN KAY's invention of the FLYING SHUTTLE in 1733 (initially just increased hand weaving productivity, but opened the way to mechanized weaving)
  - EDMUND CARTWRIGHT introduced the POWER LOOM in 1785 — a first step in a series of innovations replacing manual skills in weaving
- English textile industry not only was the driving force behind the Industrial Revolution but also REVOLUTIONIZED THE WORLD ECONOMY
- English exports, led by cotton textiles, DOUBLED between 1780 and 1800
- The growth in this sector pulled ahead the whole economy — the combination of technological and organizational innovation provides the MODEL for economic progress that transformed the economies of the world that became rich

### New Men Drive Innovation (pp. 226-228)
- New people with new ideas were crucial to this transformation
- In TRANSPORTATION: several waves of innovations — first canals, then roads, finally railways — in each, the innovators were NEW MEN
  - JAMES BRINDLEY: early canal innovator, employed by the Duke of Bridgewater to build the BRIDGEWATER CANAL (linking industrial Manchester to the port of Liverpool); born in rural Derbyshire, a MILLWRIGHT by profession; had no previous experience with transportation problems
  - Other great canal engineers: THOMAS TELFORD (started life as a stonemason), JOHN SMEATON (instrument maker and engineer)
  - JOHN MCADAM: invented TARMAC around 1816, was the second son of a minor aristocrat
  - RICHARD TREVITHICK: built the FIRST STEAM TRAIN in 1804; his father was involved in mining in Cornwall, and Richard entered the same business early, fascinated by steam engines used for pumping out mines
  - GEORGE STEPHENSON: more significant than Trevithick — son of ILLITERATE parents, inventor of the famous train "THE ROCKET," began work as an engineman at a COAL MINE
- In the critical COTTON TEXTILE industry:
  - Some pioneers had previous involvement in woolen cloth production and trade — e.g., JOHN FOSTER, who employed 700 handloom weavers in the woolen industry before switching to cotton and opening Black Dyke Mills in 1835
  - But men like Foster were a MINORITY — only about ONE-FIFTH of the leading industrialists at this time had previously been involved in anything like manufacturing
  - Not surprising: the cotton industry developed in NEW TOWNS in the north of England; factories were a completely new way of organizing production
  - The woolen industry had been organized very differently, by "PUTTING OUT" materials to individuals in their homes who spun and wove on their own → most of those in the woolen industry were ill-equipped to switch to cotton as Foster did
  - Newcomers were needed to develop and use the new technologies — the rapid expansion of cotton DECIMATED the wool industry — creative destruction in action

### Creative Destruction Redistributes Political Power (pp. 228-229)
- Creative destruction redistributes not simply income and wealth but also POLITICAL POWER, as William Lee learned when Elizabeth I rejected his invention because she feared its political consequences
- As the industrial economy expanded in Manchester and Birmingham, the new factory owners and middle-class groups that emerged around them began to protest their DISENFRANCHISEMENT and the government policies opposed to their interests
- Their prime candidate for reform: the CORN LAWS, which banned the import of "corn" (all grains and cereals, but principally wheat) if the price got too low — thus ensuring that profits of large landowners were kept high
- Good for big landowners who produced wheat, but BAD for manufacturers who had to pay HIGHER WAGES to compensate for the high price of bread
- With workers concentrated in new factories and industrial centers, it became easier to ORGANIZE AND RIOT
- By the 1820s, the political exclusion of new manufacturers and manufacturing centers was becoming untenable

### The Peterloo Massacre and the First Reform Act (pp. 229)
- August 16, 1819: a meeting to protest the political system and government policies was planned at ST. PETER'S FIELDS, Manchester
- Organizer: JOSEPH JOHNSON (local brush manufacturer and one of the founders of the radical newspaper *Manchester Observer*)
- Other organizers: JOHN KNIGHT (cotton manufacturer and reformer) and JOHN THACKER SAXTON (editor of the *Manchester Observer*)
- 60,000 protestors gathered, many holding banners: "No Corn Laws," "Universal Suffrage," and "Vote by Ballot" (meaning voting should take place secretly, not openly as it did in 1819)
- Authorities were nervous → a force of 600 cavalry of the Fifteenth Hussars assembled
- As speeches began, a local magistrate issued a warrant for the arrest of the speakers → police tried to enforce it → met opposition from the crowd → fighting broke out → Hussars CHARGED the crowd
- Within a few chaotic minutes: 11 PEOPLE DEAD and probably 600 WOUNDED
- The *Manchester Observer* called it the PETERLOO MASSACRE
- But given the changes that had already taken place in economic and political institutions, long-run repression was NOT a solution in England — the Peterloo Massacre would remain an isolated incident
- Following the riot, political institutions in England gave way to the pressure and the destabilizing threat of much wider social unrest, particularly after the 1830 revolution in France against CHARLES X (who had tried to restore the absolutism destroyed by the French Revolution of 1789)
- In 1832: the government passed the FIRST REFORM ACT
  - ENFRANCHISED Birmingham, Leeds, Manchester, and Sheffield
  - Broadened the base of voting so that manufacturers could be represented in Parliament
  - Consequent shift in political power moved policy in the direction favored by these newly represented interests
  - In 1846: they managed to get the hated Corn Laws REPEALED
- This demonstrated again that creative destruction meant a redistribution not just of income but also of political power — and changes in the distribution of political power in time would lead to further redistribution of income
- It was the INCLUSIVE NATURE of English institutions that allowed this process to take place — those who suffered from and feared creative destruction were no longer able to stop it

### Why in England? (pp. 230-231)
- The Industrial Revolution started and made its biggest strides in England because of her uniquely inclusive economic institutions, built on foundations laid by the inclusive political institutions brought about by the Glorious Revolution
- The Glorious Revolution strengthened and rationalized property rights, improved financial markets, undermined state-sanctioned monopolies in foreign trade, and removed barriers to the expansion of industry
- The Glorious Revolution made the political system open and responsive to the economic needs and aspirations of society
- These inclusive economic institutions gave men of talent and vision such as JAMES WATT the opportunity and incentive to develop their skills and ideas and influence the system in ways that benefited them and the nation
- Naturally these men, once they had become successful, had the same urges as any other person — they wanted to BLOCK others from entering their businesses and competing against them, and feared the process of creative destruction that might put them out of business, as they had previously bankrupted others
- But after 1688, this became HARDER to accomplish — in 1775, Richard Arkwright took out an encompassing patent that he hoped would give him a monopoly on the rapidly expanding cotton spinning industry in the future — he could NOT get the courts to enforce it
- Why did this unique process start in England and in the 17th century?
- Why did England develop pluralistic political institutions and break away from extractive institutions?
- Political developments leading up to the Glorious Revolution were shaped by several INTERLINKED processes:
  1. Central was the political conflict between absolutism and its opponents — the outcome not only stopped attempts to create stronger absolutism but also empowered those wishing to fundamentally change institutions
  2. The opponents of absolutism did not simply attempt to build a different TYPE of absolutism (this was not simply the House of Lancaster defeating the House of York in the War of the Roses) — instead, the Glorious Revolution involved the emergence of a new regime based on CONSTITUTIONAL RULE AND PLURALISM
- This outcome was a consequence of the DRIFT in English institutions and the way they interacted with critical junctures
- After the Black Death: Western and Eastern Europe diverged — small differences in political and economic institutions meant that in the West, the balance of power led to institutional improvement; in the East, to institutional deterioration
- But this was NOT a path that would necessarily and inexorably lead to inclusive institutions — many more crucial turns would have to be taken
- Though the Magna Carta had attempted to establish basic institutional foundations for constitutional rule, many other parts of Europe (even Eastern Europe) saw similar struggles with similar documents — yet after the Black Death, Western Europe significantly drifted away from the East
- Documents such as the Magna Carta started to have more BITE in the West; in the East, they came to mean little
- In England, even before the 17th-century conflicts, the norm was established that the king could not raise new taxes without the CONSENT OF PARLIAMENT
- No less important was the slow, incremental drift of power away from elites to citizens more generally — exemplified by the political mobilization of rural communities, seen in moments such as the Peasants' Revolt of 1381
- This drift of institutions now interacted with another critical juncture: the massive expansion of trade into the ATLANTIC
- As discussed in Chapter 4, one crucial way in which this influenced future institutional dynamics depended on whether or not the Crown was able to MONOPOLIZE this trade
- In England, the somewhat greater power of Parliament meant that the Tudor and Stuart monarchs COULD NOT do so → this created a new class of merchants and businessmen who aggressively opposed the plan to create absolutism
- KEY STATS: By 1686 in London alone, there were 702 merchants exporting to the Caribbean and 1,283 importing; North America had 691 exporting and 626 importing merchants
- They employed warehousemen, sailors, captains, dockworkers, clerks — all of whom broadly shared their interests
- Other vibrant ports (Bristol, Liverpool, Portsmouth) were similarly full of such merchants
- These new men wanted different economic institutions, and as they got wealthier through trade they became more powerful
- The same forces were at work in France, Spain, and Portugal — but there the kings were much more able to

## CHAPTER 8: NOT ON OUR TURF: BARRIERS TO DEVELOPMENT

### The Children of Samaale (pp. 260-266)
- Ethiopian absolutism persisted until recent past — emperors and nobility benefited hugely while extractive institutions meant poverty for the masses
- Most enduring implication: Ethiopian society failed to take advantage of industrialization opportunities during 19th and early 20th centuries, underpinning abject poverty today
- CORE ARGUMENT: Absolutism was not the ONLY barrier to inclusive economic institutions — many parts of the world, especially Africa, lacked even a minimal state that could provide law and order, a prerequisite for a modern economy
- Without political centralization, even elites who wanted industrialization couldn't have achieved much
- SOMALIA CASE STUDY: Organized into six clan families — Dir, Darod, Isaq, Hawiye (four largest, trace ancestry to mythical ancestor Samaale), plus Digil and Rahanweyn (sedentary agriculturalists in the south)
- Clans contain many subgroups; most significant are *diya*-paying groups — closely related kinspeople who pay and collect *diya* ("blood wealth") as compensation for murder of members
- Somali clans and diya-paying groups locked in almost continual conflict over scarce resources — water, grazing land — and constantly raided each other's herds
- Leaders called sultans and elders had no real power; political power widely dispersed, with every adult male having a say through informal councils
- No written law, no police, no legal system — Sharia law used as framework for informal laws within *diya*-paying groups
- Informal laws encoded in *heer* — explicit obligations, rights, and duties
- SPECIFIC EXAMPLE: Hassan Ugaas lineage *heer* recorded by British district commissioner on March 8, 1950 — about 1,500 men, subclan of Dir family in British Somaliland
- Heer clauses focused on blood wealth: 20 camels for murder by outsider (next of kin gets 100, rest shared), 33⅓ camels for wounding, same rate for internal homicide
- Even motor accidents covered by blood wealth when modern transportation arrived
- Clause 6: insulting another Hassan Ugaas member at council = 150 shillings to offended party

### Clan Warfare and Blood Feuding (pp. 262-264)
- SPECIFIC EXAMPLE: Early 1955, Habar Tol Ja'lo and Habar Yuunis clans grazing near Domberelly
- Man from Yuunis wounded in dispute with Tol Ja'lo over camel herding
- Yuunis retaliated, attacking Tol Ja'lo and killing a man
- Blood wealth compensation offered and accepted (in camels, as usual)
- At the handing-over ceremony, a Tol Ja'lo member killed a Yuunis man, mistaking him for the murderer's diya-paying group member
- Result: all-out warfare — within 48 hours, 13 Yuunis and 26 Tol Ja'lo killed
- Warfare continued for another year until English colonial elders brokered a blood-wealth deal paid over three years
- Blood wealth always paid in shadow of force and feuding; payment didn't necessarily stop conflict — it usually just died down then flared up again

### Lack of Political Centralization and Economic Consequences (pp. 264-266)
- Political power widely dispersed in Somali society — almost pluralistic, but without a centralized state to enforce order or property rights, this did NOT lead to inclusive institutions
- Nobody respected the authority of another — including the British colonial state when it arrived
- Lack of political centralization made it impossible for Somalia to benefit from the Industrial Revolution — unimaginable to invest in or adopt new technologies from Britain
- SUBTLE IMPLICATION: Somali politics affected technology adoption — African societies didn't use wheeled transport, plow agriculture, or writing (even though Somalis had a written script, they didn't use it)
- KINGDOM OF TAQALI: Northwest of Somalia, in Nuba Hills of southern Sudan — formed late 18th century by warriors led by Isma'il, independent until amalgamated into British Empire in 1884
- Taqali kings had access to Arabic writing but only used it for external diplomatic correspondence
- Historian Janet Ewald (late 1970s) investigated: citizens resisted writing because they feared the state would use it to control resources (claim land ownership) and impose systematic taxation
- Various elites also opposed political centralization — preferred oral to written interaction with citizens because it gave them maximum discretion; written laws set benchmarks that were harder to reverse
- Neither rulers nor ruled saw writing as advantageous — ruled feared how rulers would use it, rulers saw absence of writing as aiding their precarious grip on power
- The POLITICS of Taqali kept writing from being introduced — same forces likely inhibited Somali use of writing and other basic technologies

### Why Political Centralization Was Impossible in Somalia (pp. 265-266)
- Centralizing politically would have meant some clans subject to control of others — they rejected this
- Balance of military power in society made centralized institutions difficult
- Any clan attempting to centralize power faced stiff resistance and would lose existing power/privileges
- Without political centralization: no security of property rights → no incentives to invest in productivity-enhancing technologies
- While industrialization was under way elsewhere in 19th-20th centuries, Somalis were feuding and fending for their lives — economic backwardness became more ingrained

### Enduring Backwardness (pp. 266-267)
- CORE SYNTHESIS: Industrial Revolution created a transformative critical juncture for the whole world during 19th century and beyond
- Nations under extractive political and economic institutions did not generate incentives for growth
- Spain and Ethiopia: absolutist control choked economic incentives long before dawn of 19th century
- Austria-Hungary, Russia, Ottoman Empire, China: rulers feared creative destruction — not only neglected progress but took EXPLICIT STEPS to block spread of industry and new technologies
- Absolutism is NOT the only form of extractive political institutions preventing industrialization
- Inclusive political and economic institutions necessitate some degree of political centralization — state must enforce law and order, uphold property rights, encourage economic activity through public services
- Even today: Afghanistan, Haiti, Nepal, Somalia have states unable to maintain rudimentary order — economic incentives all but destroyed
- Political centralization resisted for SAME REASON as absolutist regimes resist change: fear that change will reallocate political power from those who dominate today to new individuals and groups
- Thus: absolutism blocks moves toward pluralism AND traditional elites/clans block moves toward state centralization
- Societies lacking centralization in 18th-19th centuries were particularly disadvantaged in the age of industry
- Societies that had already taken steps toward inclusive institutions (US, Australia) or where absolutism was more seriously challenged (France, Japan) took advantage of new economic opportunities
- The usual pattern of interaction between critical junctures and existing institutional differences played out again — this time with even bigger effects on prosperity and poverty of nations

## CHAPTER 9: REVERSING DEVELOPMENT

### Spice and Genocide (pp. 289-295)
- MOLUCCAN ARCHIPELAGO in modern Indonesia — three groups of islands: northern Moluccas (independent kingdoms of Tidore, Ternate, Bacan), middle (island kingdom of Ambon), south (Banda Islands, small archipelago not yet politically unified)
- In early 17th century, Moluccas were central to world trade as the ONLY producers of cloves, mace, and nutmeg
- Nutmeg and mace grew ONLY in the Banda Islands — inhabitants exported rare spices in exchange for food and manufactured goods from Java, Melaka, India, China, Arabia
- First European contact: 16th century, Portuguese mariners seeking to bypass Ottoman-controlled Middle Eastern trade routes
- Cape of Good Hope rounded by Bartolomeu Dias in 1488; India reached by Vasco da Gama in 1498
- Portuguese captured Melaka in 1511 — key entrepôt on western Malaysian Peninsula
- KEY QUOTE (Portuguese traveler Tomé Pires, 1515): "The trade and commerce between the different nations for a thousand leagues on every hand must come to Melaka... Whoever is lord of Melaka has his hands at the throat of Venice."
- Portuguese tried but FAILED to monopolize the spice trade — opponents were not negligible
- Between 14th-16th centuries, significant economic development in Southeast Asia based on spice trade — city-states like Aceh, Banten, Melaka, Makassar, Pegu, Brunei expanded rapidly
- These states had absolutist forms of government similar to Europe — kings claiming absolute power, relying on trade revenues, granting monopolies
- DUTCH ARRIVAL changed everything — Dutch realized monopolizing supply more profitable than competing
- 1600: Dutch persuaded ruler of Ambon to sign exclusive clove trade agreement
- 1602: Dutch East India Company (VOC) founded — second European joint stock company (after English East India Company), had its own army and power to wage war and colonize
- Dutch captured Portuguese fort in Ambon (1605), forcibly removed all other traders
- Expanded to northern Moluccas — forced rulers of Tidore, Ternate, Bacan to agree no cloves could be grown/traded in their territories; treaty with Ternate even allowed Dutch to destroy any clove trees found
- AMBON: Dutch intensified existing extractive systems — stipulated each household tied to soil, must cultivate certain number of clove trees, deliver forced labor
- BANDA ISLANDS: Different challenge — many small autonomous city-states, no hierarchical political structure, run by village meetings, no central authority to coerce into signing monopoly treaty
- Dutch governor of Batavia, JAN PIETERSZOON COEN, devised alternative plan — founded Batavia on Java as Dutch East India Company capital
- 1621: Coen sailed to Banda with a fleet and MASSACRED almost the entire population — probably about 15,000 people
- All leaders executed, only a few left alive to preserve mace/nutmeg production knowledge
- After genocide, Coen created plantation society: islands divided into 68 parcels, given to 68 Dutchmen (mostly former/current VOC employees)
- New plantation owners bought slaves from East India Company to populate empty islands, forced to produce spices at fixed prices
- RESULT: By end of 17th century, Dutch reduced world supply of these spices by ~60%, price of nutmeg had doubled
- Cost: 15,000 innocent lives and establishment of extractive institutions condemning islands to underdevelopment

### The Reversal of Southeast Asian Development (pp. 294-295)
- Dutch spread their Moluccas strategy to the entire region — profound implications for economic and political institutions
- Long commercial expansion of several states (started 14th century) went INTO REVERSE
- Even polities not directly colonized by VOC turned inward and abandoned trade — nascent economic and political change halted
- States abandoned export crops and ceased commercial activity out of fear — autarky safer than facing the Dutch
- SPECIFIC EXAMPLES: In 1620, state of Banten on Java cut down pepper trees hoping Dutch would leave them in peace
- 1686: Dutch merchant visited Maguindanao (southern Philippines) — told "Nutmeg and cloves can be grown here... They are not there now because the old Raja had all of them ruined before his death. He was afraid the Dutch Company would come to fight with them about it."
- 1699: Ruler of Maguindanao "had forbidden the continued planting of pepper so that he could not thereby get involved in war"
- There was de-urbanization and population decline — in 1635 the Burmese moved their capital from Pegu (coast) to Ava, far inland up the Irrawaddy River
- Counterfactual: without Dutch aggression, Southeast Asian states might have continued commercialization toward inclusive institutions — but Dutch colonialism fundamentally changed their trajectory
- People stopped trading, turned inward, became MORE absolutist — in next two centuries, unable to take advantage of Industrial Revolution
- By end of 18th century, nearly all were part of European colonial empires

### The All-Too-Usual Institution: Slavery and Africa (pp. 295-301)
- CORE ARGUMENT: European expansion into Atlantic fueled inclusive institutions in Britain (Ch. 7) BUT simultaneously sowed seeds of underdevelopment by imposing/strengthening extractive institutions elsewhere
- Slavery was NOT peculiar — classical scholar Moses Finlay pointed out it was present in almost every society historically
- In Roman period, slaves came from Slavic peoples (Black Sea), Middle East, Northern Europe
- By 1400, Europeans stopped enslaving each other, but Africa did not undergo the transition from slavery to serfdom
- Before early modern period: vibrant slave trade in East Africa, large numbers transported across Sahara to Arabian Peninsula
- Large medieval West African states (Mali, Ghana, Songhai) made heavy use of slaves in government, army, agriculture
- ESCALATION: Sugar plantation colonies in Caribbean (beginning early 17th century) caused dramatic escalation
- KEY STATISTICS on Atlantic slave trade by century:
  - 16th century: ~300,000 slaves traded (mostly from Central Africa, heavy involvement of Kongo and Portuguese in Luanda)
  - Trans-Saharan trade in same period: ~550,000 (still larger)
  - 17th century: ~1,350,000 in Atlantic trade (situation reversed, majority shipped to Americas)
  - 18th century: ~6,000,000 shipped across Atlantic, ~700,000 across Sahara
  - TOTAL: well over 10,000,000 Africans shipped out of continent as slaves
- Map 15: Slave exports between 1400-1900 as percent of population in 1400 — in Angola, Benin, Ghana, Togo, total cumulative exports amounted to MORE than entire population in 1400
- GUNS FOR SLAVES: Europeans exchanged guns and ammunition for slaves — by 1730, about 180,000 guns imported per year along West African coast alone
- Between 1750-early 19th century, British alone sold 283,000-394,000 guns per year
- Between 1750-1807, British sold extraordinary 22,000 tons of gunpowder (avg 384,000 kg/year) plus 91,000 kg of lead per year
- On Loango coast (north of Kongo): Europeans sold ~50,000 guns per year
- INSTITUTIONAL DESTRUCTION: Slave trade initiated two adverse political processes:
  1. Many polities became MORE absolutist, organized around single objective of enslaving and selling others
  2. Paradoxically, warring and slaving ultimately DESTROYED whatever legitimate state authority existed in sub-Saharan Africa
- Law became tool of enslavement — no matter the crime, penalty was slavery
- KEY QUOTE (English merchant Francis Moore, 1730s Senegambia): "Since this slave trade has been us'd, all punishments are changed into slavery; there being an advantage on such condemnations, they strain for crimes very hard, in order to get the benefit of selling the criminal."
- ORACLE OF AROCHUKWA: Famous example in eastern Nigeria — oracle widely believed to speak for a prominent deity, respected by Ijaw, Ibibio, Igbo peoples
- Oracle housed in cave lined with human skulls in gorge of Cross River
- Priests in league with Aro slavers and merchants — people "swallowed" by the oracle were actually led through cave to waiting European ships on Cross River
- SLAVING STATES: Kongo first African state to experience metamorphosis into slaving state (until destroyed by civil war)
- Oyo (Nigeria), Dahomey (Benin), Asante (Ghana) — major slaving states
- OYO EXPANSION: Middle of 17th century, directly related to increase in slave exports — military revolution involving horse imports from north, powerful cavalry
- Between 1690-1740, Oyo established monopoly on what became the Slave Coast — estimated 80-90% of slaves sold on coast were war captives
- ASANTE: After 1700, expanded from interior like Oyo, triggered Akan Wars — last independent state Gyaman conquered in 1747
- 375,000 slaves exported from Gold Coast between 1700-1750, preponderance were war captives
- DEMOGRAPHIC IMPACT: Historian Patrick Manning estimates population of West and West-Central Africa slave-export regions was 22-25 million in early 18th century
- Without slave trade, at ~0.5% annual growth, population should have been 46-53 million by 1850 — IN FACT it was about ONE-HALF of this
- Difference not only due to ~8 million exported as slaves (1700-1850) but also millions killed by continual internal warfare aimed at capturing slaves
- Slavery and slave trade further disrupted family/marriage structures, may have reduced fertility

### Abolition and "Legitimate Commerce" (pp. 300-303)
- Late 18th century: strong abolition movement in Britain led by William Wilberforce
- 1807: British Parliament passed bill making slave trade illegal; US followed next year
- British government actively enforced by stationing naval squadrons in Atlantic
- 1834: Slavery itself abolished in British Empire
- CRITICAL POINT: End of slave trade after 1807 did NOT mean slavery's impact melted away — many African states had become organized around slaving, British ending the trade didn't change this reality
- Slavery became MORE prevalent within Africa itself after external demand dried up
- "LEGITIMATE COMMERCE" — new exports replaced slave trade: palm oil, kernels, peanuts, ivory, rubber, gum arabic
- BUT these were produced in same extractive context where slavery was a way of life
- ASANTE EXAMPLE: Prior to 1807, heavily involved in slave export to Cape Coast and Elmina castles
- After 1807, Asante political elite reorganized — slaves settled on large plantations around capital Kumase, later spread throughout empire (most of interior Ghana)
- Slaves produced gold, kola nuts, food, and served as porters (Asante didn't use wheeled transportation)
- In Dahomey: king had large palm oil plantations near Whydah and Porto Novo, all based on slave labor
- ABOLITION PARADOX: Rather than making slavery wither, it led to REDEPLOYMENT of slaves within Africa — used domestically for coerced production of legitimate commerce goods
- In Nigeria in 1820s-30s: once-great Oyo Kingdom collapsed through civil wars, rise of Yoruba city-states (Illorin, Ibadan) directly involved in slave trade to its south
- 1830s: Capital of Oyo sacked; Yoruba cities fought nearly continuous series of wars with Dahomey in first half of century, generating massive slave supply
- Kidnapping rampant — in some parts of Nigeria parents wouldn't let children play outside
- Slavery EXPANDED in Africa throughout 19th century — in West African kingdoms of Asante, Dahomey, and Yoruba city-states, well over HALF of population were slaves
- French colonial records for western Sudan (Senegal to Chad): 30% of population enslaved in 1900
- Formal colonization after the Scramble for Africa failed to destroy slavery — it continued well into 20th century
- Sierra Leone: slavery only abolished in 1928 (despite Freetown being established for repatriated slaves)
- Liberia (founded for freed American slaves, 1840s): as late as 1960s, estimated one-quarter of labor force coerced in conditions close to slavery
- Given extractive institutions based on slave trade, industrialization did not spread to sub-Saharan Africa — stagnation or retardation while rest of world transformed

### Making a Dual Economy (pp. 303-304)
- "DUAL ECONOMY" paradigm proposed in 1955 by Sir Arthur Lewis — still shapes thinking about less-developed countries
- Lewis's model: many underdeveloped economies split into modern sector (urban, industrial, advanced technology) and traditional sector (rural, agriculture, backward institutions)
- Traditional sector characterized by communal land ownership (no private property rights), inefficient labor use
- Lewis argued labor could be reallocated from traditional to modern sector without reducing rural output
- "Problem of development" for generations of economists: moving people/resources from traditional to modern sector
- Lewis received Nobel Prize in 1979
- SOUTH AFRICA as test case: Lewis and development economists correct that it's a dual economy — Natal (east of Great Kei River) vs. Transkei (west)
- Natal: private property rights, functioning legal systems, markets, commercial agriculture, industry — beachfront properties, lush sugarcane, beautiful roads
- Transkei: communal property in land, all-powerful traditional chiefs, brown deforested land, makeshift huts, open fires
- BUT the dual economy paradigm MISSES the critical point: Transkei's backwardness is NOT a historic remnant or natural state
- The dual economy was CREATED by South African white elites to produce a reservoir of cheap labor for their businesses and reduce competition from black Africans
- Underdevelopment was deliberately manufactured, not naturally evolved over centuries
- South Africa and Botswana avoided the worst of slave trade effects — first major European interaction came when Dutch East India Company founded Cape Town base in Table Bay, 1652
- Western South Africa sparsely settled by hunter-gatherers (Khoikhoi people)

### South Africa: The Creation of a Dual Economy (pp. 305-315)
- Ciskei and Transkei inhabitants (Xhosa people) were far removed from slave markets — just far enough inland not to attract attention, avoiding adverse currents of West and Central Africa
- 19th century: isolation changed — Europeans attracted by South Africa's temperate climate (free of malaria/yellow fever that made West Africa "white man's graveyard")
- British took over Cape Town from Dutch during Napoleonic Wars — precipitated long series of Xhosa wars as settlement frontier expanded inland
- 1835: Remaining Dutch-descent Europeans (Afrikaners/Boers) began the Great Trek away from British coastal control, founding Orange Free State and Transvaal
- KEY DISCOVERIES: Vast diamond reserves in Kimberly (1867) and rich gold mines in Johannesburg (1886)
- This mineral wealth convinced British to extend control — resistance led to Boer Wars (1880-1881 and 1899-1902)
- After initial unexpected defeat, British merged Afrikaner states with Cape Province and Natal to found Union of South Africa in 1910
- Mining boom and European expansion generated demand for food and agricultural products — creating NEW economic opportunities for native Africans

### African Agricultural Dynamism Before Reversal (pp. 306-308)
- Historian Colin Bundy documented Xhosa response to economic opportunities
- As early as 1832 (before mining boom), Moravian missionary in Transkei noted new economic dynamism and demand for European consumer goods
- 1876: Civil commissioner John Hemming visited Fingoland in Ciskei — "struck with the very great advancement made by the Fingoes" — brick houses, fruit trees, irrigation, plows, vast cultivated land
- African farmers readily adopted new technology (plows, wagons, irrigation) when given opportunity
- 1879: Magistrate of Umzimkulu (Griqualand East, Transkei) noted "growing desire of the part of natives to become proprietors of land — they have purchased 38,000 acres"
- Three years later: ~8,000 African farmers in the district had bought and started working 90,000 acres
- Private property in land weakened chiefs, enabled new men to buy land and make wealth — unthinkable just decades earlier
- STEPHEN SONJICA: Self-made farmer from Ciskei — in 1911 address, told how his father had said "Buy land? Don't you know that all land is God's, and he gave it to the chiefs only?"
- Sonjica got job in King William's Town, secretly opened bank account, saved 80 pounds, bought oxen/plow/farm equipment, purchased small farm — recommended farming with "modern methods of profit making"
- 1869: Methodist missionary W. J. Davis collected 46 pounds in cash "for the Lancashire Cotton Relief Fund" — prosperous African farmers donating money for relief of poor English textile workers!

### Chiefs Resist and Europeans Destroy (pp. 308-310)
- Traditional chiefs saw economic dynamism as eroding their wealth and power
- 1879: Chief magistrate Matthew Blyth observed opposition to land surveying — "some of the chiefs objected... the chiefs see that the granting of individual titles will destroy their influence among the headmen"
- Chiefs resisted improvements (irrigation ditches, fences) — recognized these as prelude to individual property rights
- Chiefs and witch doctors tried to prohibit "European ways" (new crops, tools, plows, trade items)
- But integration into British colonial state weakened chiefs' power — resistance would not be enough
- 1884 (Fingoland): European observer noted people had "transferred their allegiance to us. Their chiefs have been changed to a sort of titled landowner... without political power"
- Even a MODICUM of inclusive institutions and erosion of chief power was sufficient for vigorous African economic boom
- BUT this boom would be SHORT-LIVED — between 1890 and 1913 it came to an abrupt end and went into reverse

### The Deliberate Destruction of African Prosperity (pp. 309-311)
- TWO FORCES worked to destroy rural African prosperity:
  1. Antagonism by European farmers competing with successful African farmers who drove down crop prices
  2. Europeans wanted cheap labor for burgeoning mining economy — could only ensure cheap supply by IMPOVERISHING Africans
- 1897 TESTIMONY: George Albu, chairman of Association of Mines, explained the logic of impoverishing Africans to a Commission of Inquiry
- His proposal to cheapen labor: "simply telling the boys that their wages are reduced"
- When asked if he'd favor government-enforced labor if Africans retired to their kraals: "Certainly... I would make it compulsory... Why should a nigger be allowed to do nothing? I think a kaffir should be compelled to work"
- His solution: "Tax him" — and don't allow Africans to hold land, forcing them to work for whites

### The Natives Land Act of 1913 (pp. 310-313)
- NATIVES LAND ACT OF 1913: The key legislation that simultaneously removed competition with white farmers AND developed low-wage labor force
- Anticipating Lewis's dual economy concept, divided South Africa into two parts: modern prosperous and traditional poor — EXCEPT the prosperity and poverty were being CREATED by the act itself
- 87% of land given to Europeans (who represented ~20% of population)
- Remaining 13% to Africans
- Had many predecessors — Europeans had gradually been confining Africans onto smaller reserves
- But 1913 act definitively institutionalized the situation, set stage for Apartheid regime
- Transkei and Ciskei designated as African "Homelands" (later called Bantustans)
- Apartheid rhetoric claimed African peoples were not natives but descended from Bantu who migrated from Eastern Nigeria ~1,000 years before — thus had no more (in practice less) entitlement to land than European settlers
- Act also included provisions to stop black sharecroppers and squatters from farming on white-owned land except as labor tenants
- Secretary for native affairs: "The effect of the act was to put a stop... to all transactions involving anything in the nature of partnership between Europeans and natives in respect of land"

### The Consequences of the Land Act (pp. 312-315)
- After 1913: vast numbers of Africans evicted from their lands (taken by whites), crowded into Homelands too small for independent living
- As intended: forced to look for work in white economy, supplying labor cheaply
- Economic incentives collapsed — advances of previous 50 years ALL reversed; people gave up plows, reverted to farming with hoes (if they farmed at all)
- Not only economic incentives destroyed — political changes also reversed; power of chiefs (previously in decline) was STRENGTHENED because creating cheap labor force required removing private property in land, reaffirming chiefs' control
- 1951: Bantu Authorities Act — reached apogee of restoring chief power
- KEY QUOTE (G. Findlay, 1940): "Tribal tenure is a guarantee that the land will never be properly worked and will never really belong to the natives. Cheap labour must have a cheap breeding place, and so it is furnished to the Africans at their own expense."
- EVIDENCE OF REVERSAL: Transkei and Ciskei entered prolonged economic decline after 1913
- Historian Francis Wilson's mining company employment records: miners' wages FELL 30% between 1911 and 1921
- In 1961: despite relatively steady growth in South African economy, wages still 12% LOWER than 1911
- South Africa became most unequal country in the world
- Government ensured blacks couldn't enter European part of economy (87% of land): no African could own property or start a business there
- JOB RESERVATION (from 1904): No African allowed to be amalgamator, assayer, banksman, blacksmith, boiler maker, brass finisher, brassmolder, bricklayer... and on and on — banned from ALL skilled mining jobs
- This was the first "COLOUR BAR" — extended to entire economy in 1926, lasted until 1980s
- STATE REFUSED TO INVEST IN BLACK EDUCATION — policy peaked in 1950s under Hendrik Verwoerd (architect of Apartheid regime that lasted until 1994)
- BANTU EDUCATION ACT: Verwoerd's speech in 1954: "The Bantu must be guided to serve his own community in all respects. There is no place for him in the European community above the level of certain forms of labour"
- CRITIQUE OF LEWIS'S DUAL ECONOMY: In South Africa, the dual economy was NOT a natural outcome of development — it was CREATED BY THE STATE
- The modern sector's success RELIED ON the backward sector — white employers made huge profits by paying very low wages to black unskilled workers
- Black workers purposefully kept unskilled and barred from high-skill occupations so white workers wouldn't face competition
- Blacks were "trapped" in traditional economy, in the Homelands — but this was not a problem growth would solve; the Homelands were what ENABLED the white economy
- White South African economic growth was ULTIMATELY LIMITED — extractive institutions, growth without creative destruction
- Over 80% of South African population marginalized — blacks could not become skilled workers, businessmen, entrepreneurs, engineers, scientists
- White South Africans shared living standards of Western Europeans; black South Africans scarcely richer than rest of sub-Saharan Africa
- By 1970s, economy had stopped growing
- POLITICAL INSTITUTIONS: Before 1994 overthrow, all power vested in whites — only ones allowed to vote and run for office
- At Union of South Africa founding (1910): Orange Free State and Transvaal had explicit racial franchises; Natal and Cape Colony allowed blacks to vote IF they had sufficient property (which they typically didn't)
- By 1930s: blacks explicitly disenfranchised everywhere in South Africa
- Dual economy ended in 1994 — NOT through Lewis's natural economic development, but through BLACK POLITICAL MOBILIZATION
- After Soweto uprising of 1976, protests became more organized and stronger, ultimately bringing down Apartheid
- It was the empowerment of blacks who organized and rose up that ended the dual economy — political force ended what political force had created

### Development Reversed (pp. 315-318) — Chapter 9 Conclusion
- World inequality today exists because during 19th-20th centuries, some nations took advantage of Industrial Revolution while others were unable to
- Technological change is only one engine of prosperity but perhaps the most critical
- This chapter showed that extractive institutions underpinning poverty were IMPOSED or strengthened by the very same process that fueled European growth: European commercial and colonial expansion
- Profitability of European colonial empires was often built on DESTRUCTION of independent polities and indigenous economies, or on creation of extractive institutions from the ground up (as in Caribbean — native populations collapsed, Europeans imported African slaves, set up plantation systems)
- Counterfactual: we will never know what trajectories of Banda Islands, Aceh, Burma would have been — they might have had their own Glorious Revolution based on growing trade
- But Dutch East India Company stamped out indigenous development (genocide in Banda), made other city-states in Southeast Asia pull back from commerce
- INDIA: British reversed development — India was largest producer/exporter of textiles in 18th century world
- English East India Company (founded 1600, two years before Dutch version) spent 17th century trying to monopolize Indian exports
- After Glorious Revolution challenged its monopoly, and British textile producers got Parliament to BAN CALICO IMPORTS (its most profitable item), East India Company switched to building continental empire under Robert Clive
- Battles of Plassey (1757) and Buxar (1764): EIC vanquished local powers in Bengal
- EIC looted local wealth and intensified (perhaps even exceeded) Mughal rulers' extractive taxation
- This coincided with massive contraction of Indian textile industry (no market in Britain anymore)
- De-urbanization and increased poverty — soon Indians were buying textiles FROM Britain and growing opium for EIC to sell in China
- AFRICA: Atlantic slave trade repeated same pattern — states turned into war machines capturing and selling slaves; as conflict grew, whatever political centralization had been achieved crumbled
- Where slave trade was escaped (South Africa): Europeans imposed different extractive institutions — designed to create reservoir of cheap labor, creating dual economy, preventing 80% of population from skilled occupations, commercial farming, entrepreneurship
- CORE CONCLUSION: Economic development may sometimes feed on, and even CREATE, underdevelopment in some other part of the domestic or world economy

## CHAPTER 10: THE DIFFUSION OF PROSPERITY

### Honor Among Thieves (pp. 319-320)
- 18th-century Britain transported criminals to penal colonies — first to American colonies, then (after 1783 independence) to Australia
- Captain James Cook explored eastern Australia, April 29, 1770, named Botany Bay
- January 1788: fleet of 11 ships under Captain Arthur Phillip arrived at Botany Bay, set up camp at Sydney Cove (now heart of Sydney), colony named New South Wales
- Story of Henry and Susannah Cable: married convicts transported on the Alexander, captained by Duncan Sinclair
  - Lady Cadogan organized campaign to reunite family, raised £20 for goods — goods vanished on arrival
  - Convicts had no rights under British law — couldn't own property, sue in court, or even give evidence
  - But in Australia, judge advocate David Collins issued a writ — convicts COULD bring cases in Australian courts
  - KEY MOMENT: Australia began building inclusive institutions from the very start, even for convicts

## PAGES 321-340: CHAPTER 10 (cont.) — The Diffusion of Prosperity

### The Cable Case and Australian Law (pp. 321-322)
- Henry and Susannah Cable were illiterate — put "crosses" at the bottom of the writ
- Words "new settlers of this place" were crossed out and replaced (probably by Judge Collins) — if described as convicts, no hope
- First civil case adjudicated in Australia — Collins convened court with jury of soldiers
- Captain Sinclair lost, had to pay fifteen pounds
- First criminal case also broke British precedent: convict found guilty of stealing another convict's bread (worth two pence) — under British law, convicts couldn't own property, so no theft possible
- KEY: Australia was NOT Britain, and its law would diverge in criminal and civil law as well as economic/political institutions

### Australia's Path to Inclusive Institutions (pp. 322-326)
- Penal colony initially: convicts + guards (soldiers). Few "free settlers" until 1820s
- Transportation continued to NSW until 1840, to Western Australia until 1868
- Convicts did "compulsory work" — essentially forced labor. Guards kept what convicts produced
- Like Virginia Company's Jamestown, forced labor didn't work — no incentives
- Punishment: lashing or banishment to Norfolk Island (13 sq miles, 1000+ miles east of Australia)
- KEY DIFFERENCE from Latin America: no dense indigenous populations to exploit, no precious metals, no plantation-viable soil/crops, slave trade was active but not profitable for NSW
- Guards had to give convicts incentives — extra time to work for themselves and sell what they produced
- Convicts allowed to become entrepreneurs and hire other convicts
- Given land and full rights restored after completing sentences
- Henry Cable example: by 1798 owned the Ramping Horse hotel + a shop; bought a ship, traded sealskins; by 1809 owned 9 farms (~470 acres) + shops and houses in Sydney

### The Squattocracy vs. Ex-Convicts (pp. 324-326)
- John Macarthur: arrived as soldier in 1790, resigned army 1796, became richest man in Australia via sheep farming
- Blue Mountains crossed 1813 — vast grasslands on the other side, "sheep heaven"
- Macarthur and fellow sheep magnates = the Squatters (Squattocracy) — elite of Australia
- 1806: Governor William Bligh appointed (same Bligh of H.M.S. Bounty mutiny fame)
- Bligh challenged rum monopolists → Rum Rebellion led by Macarthur → Bligh locked up
- British sent more soldiers, arrested Macarthur, shipped him to Britain — but he returned
- Conflict between elite (Squatters, former guards) and rest of society (ex-convicts, their families)
  - Ex-convicts wanted: end to transportation, trial by jury, access to free land
  - Elite wanted: legal title to squatted land, continued transportation (cheap labor, low wages)
- William Wentworth: writer/explorer/journalist, led ex-convict cause. Father was accused highway robber transported to Australia
  - Founded newspaper the *Australian*
  - Advocated elected assembly, trial by jury, end to transportation
  - Macarthur dismissed Wentworth's supporters: "sentenced to be hung," "London Jew," "son of two convicts," "married to a convict who was formerly a tambourine girl"

### Australian Democracy Emerges (pp. 326-328)
- 1823: governor's powers limited by creation of a council (initially from Squatter/elite appointees, including Macarthur)
- 1831: Governor Richard Bourke allowed ex-convicts to sit on juries for first time
- 1840: transportation to NSW stopped
- 1842: legislative council created — two-thirds elected, one-third appointed. Ex-convicts could stand/vote if they held property
- By 1850s: adult white male suffrage introduced
- Victoria (carved from NSW 1851) and Tasmania became first places in world to introduce effective SECRET BALLOT — still called "the Australian ballot"
- Parallel to Jamestown, Virginia 181 years earlier — similar initial conditions (no indigenous exploitation, no precious metals) led to inclusive institutions in both cases
- KEY ARGUMENT: US and Australia took different path to inclusive institutions than England (which needed Civil War and Glorious Revolution). In colonies, would-be autocrats like Lord Baltimore/John Macarthur could never establish strong enough grip on society

### Breaking the Barriers: The French Revolution (pp. 329-333)
- Pre-1789 France: absolutist monarchy for three centuries. Society divided into Three Estates:
  - First Estate: aristocrats (nobility)
  - Second Estate: clergy
  - Third Estate: everybody else
- Different laws for different estates — nobility and clergy exempt from taxes, owned vast land, could impose own taxes on peasants
- Guilds regulated manufacturing, blocked entry of entrepreneurs, prevented new businesses
- *Ancien régime* prided itself on continuity — entry by entrepreneurs "would create instability"
- Serfdom in decline but feudal dues and restrictions on mobility persisted
- August 4, 1789: National Constituent Assembly proposed new constitution
  - Article 1: "completely abolishes the feudal system" — all serfdom abolished without indemnification
  - Article 9: tax privileges "abolished forever" — taxes to be collected equally from all citizens
  - Article 11: "All citizens, without distinction of birth, are eligible to any office or dignity" — no profession shall imply derogation
- Revolution also: abolished Church's authority to levy special taxes, turned clergy into state employees, abolished guilds and occupational restrictions
- Despite decades of instability, Terror, and war — irreversible step away from absolutism
- Culminated in Third Republic (1870) — parliamentary system similar to what Glorious Revolution created in England

### Path to the French Revolution (pp. 333-335)
- Louis XIV (Sun King): ruled 1661-1715, consolidated absolutism, never convened Estates-General
- Finance minister Jean-Baptiste Colbert oversaw government-sponsored industry — extractive growth benefiting mainly First and Second Estates
- State had chronic fiscal problems: wars, standing army, royal court, palaces
- Louis XVI (1774): inherited fiscal crisis worsened by Seven Years' War (1756-63, lost Canada)
- Reform attempts by Turgot, Jacques Necker, Charles Alexandre de Calonne — all failed
- Calonne persuaded Louis XVI to summon Assembly of Notables → Assembly demanded only Estates-General could endorse reforms
- Estates-General (last convened 1614) gathered at Versailles 1789 — irreconcilable differences
- Third Estate saw chance to increase political power; May 5, 1789 ended without resolution
- National Constituent Assembly formed July 9; Louis XVI sacked Necker → radicalization
- Storming of the Bastille: July 14, 1789 — revolution began in earnest
- Jacobin Club formed; nobles fled as émigrés; constitution finalized September 29, 1791 (constitutional monarchy)
- War with Austria (1792, "first coalition") → increased radicalism → the Terror under Robespierre and Saint-Just → executions of Louis XVI, Marie Antoinette, Brissot, Danton, Desmoulins
- Terror ended July 1794 (execution of Robespierre) → Directory (1795-99) → Consulate (Ducos, Sieyès, Napoleon) → Napoleon's personal rule
- Napoleon's military victories (Austerlitz, Jena-Auerstadt, Wagram) allowed him to impose reforms and his legal code across wide territories
- After Napoleon's fall (1815): period of retrenchment, but forces of 1789 would inevitably lead to inclusive institutions

### Exporting the Revolution (pp. 335-340)
- Pre-revolution: severe restrictions on Jews throughout Europe
- Frankfurt's Judengasse: no more than 500 Jewish families, confined to quarter-mile-long walled ghetto no more than 12 feet wide
  - Could not leave at night, on Sundays, during Christian festivals
  - Max 2 new families admitted per year, max 12 marriages per year, only if both over 25
  - Could not farm, trade in weapons/spices/wine/grain; had to wear yellow rings (men) and striped veil (women) until 1726
- Mayer Amschel Rothschild: leading dealer in coins, metals, antiques in Frankfurt by 1780s — but couldn't open business outside ghetto
- 1791: French National Assembly emancipated French Jewry; armies emancipated Jews in Rhineland
- 1796: French bombarded Frankfurt, demolishing half of Judengasse — ~2000 Jews left homeless, forced outside ghetto
- Rothschilds freed from restrictions, seized new opportunities (e.g., contract to supply grain to Austrian army)
- Full emancipation in Frankfurt: 1811, by Grand Duke Karl von Dalberg (appointed by Napoleon). Mayer Amschel told his son: "[Y]ou are now a citizen"
- Congress of Vienna (1815) brought some reverses, but no going back for Rothschilds — sons built largest bank in 19th-century Europe (branches in Frankfurt, London, Paris, Naples, Vienna)
- French armies and Napoleon invaded continental Europe, destroying medieval institutions everywhere:
  - Austrian Netherlands → Belgian/Dutch reform (Batavian Republic)
  - Switzerland: feudal lords defeated, guilds abolished
  - Germany: Nassau-Usingen example — peasants subject to 230 different payments/dues/services, including "blood tithe" after animal slaughter, bee tithe, wax tithe
  - Cologne and Aachen: guilds blocked spinning/weaving textile machines
- Napoleon codified Roman law + equality before the law into Code Napoleon — saw it as his greatest legacy, imposed in every territory he controlled
- Reforms not always irreversible (Hanover restored old elites) but in many places feudalism, guilds, nobility permanently destroyed
- By mid-19th century: industrialization underway in almost all French-conquered areas; Austria-Hungary, Russia, Poland, Spain (where French hold was temporary) remained stagnant

### Seeking Modernity: Japan's Meiji Restoration (pp. 339-340)
- Autumn 1867: Ōkubo Toshimichi (Satsuma domain courtier) traveled to Edo, met Chōshū domain leaders in Yamaguchi
- October 14: agreed to join forces, march armies to Edo, overthrow the shogun — secret Satcho Alliance formed
- Pre-Meiji Japan: controlled by Tokugawa family since 1600, shogun title since 1603
  - Emperor sidelined to purely ceremonial role
  - Feudal lords (including Shimazu family of Satsuma) ruled their domains with samurai retainers
  - Strict occupational categories, trade restrictions, high taxation on farmers
  - Shogun monopolized/controlled foreign trade, banned foreigners
  - Extractive political and economic institutions — Japan was poor
- Satsuma domain (south) remained quite autonomous, traded independently via Ryūkyū Islands
- Ōkubo Toshimichi: born 1830 in Kagoshima (Satsuma capital), son of a samurai

## PAGES 341-360: CHAPTER 10 (cont.) / CHAPTER 11: THE VIRTUOUS CIRCLE

### Meiji Restoration Details (pp. 341-344)
- Ōkubo Toshimichi's talent spotted by Shimazu Nariakira (lord of Satsuma), who promoted him in bureaucracy
- Nariakira already planned to overthrow shogun, expand trade with Asia/Europe, abolish feudal institutions, build modern state — died 1858
- Successor Shimazu Hisamitsu was more circumspect initially
- To rally support, reformers wrapped cause in outrage over sidelining of the emperor
- Treaty with Tosa domain: "a country does not have two monarchs, a home does not have two masters"
- Real intention: not just restore emperor but completely change political and economic institutions
- Sakamoto Ryūma (Tosa side) presented shogun with 8-point plan:
  1. Political power returned to Imperial Court
  2. Two legislative bodies (Upper/Lower house), government measures based on "general opinion"
  3. Men of ability from lords, nobles, AND people at large employed as councillors; traditional offices abolished
  4. Foreign affairs based on "appropriate regulations" from general opinion
  5. Old legislation set aside, new adequate code selected
- Shogun Yoshinobu agreed to resign; January 3, 1868: Meiji Restoration declared
- Emperor Kōmei died, son Meiji restored to power; Satsuma and Chōshū occupied Edo and imperial capital Kyōto
- Ōkubo Toshimichi wanted Tokugawas crushed forever — persuaded emperor to confiscate their lands
- January 27: former shogun Yoshinobu attacked; civil war raged until summer, Tokugawas vanquished

### Meiji Reforms (pp. 342-343)
- 1869: feudalism abolished, 300 fiefs surrendered to government, turned into prefectures with appointed governors
- Modern bureaucratic state replaced feudal system; centralized taxation
- 1869: equality of all social classes before the law; restrictions on internal migration and trade abolished
- Samurai class abolished (required putting down rebellions)
- Individual property rights on land introduced; freedom to enter any trade
- State heavily invested in infrastructure: 1869 steamship line Tokyo-Osaka, first railway Tokyo-Yokohama
- Satsuma domain lord had been a leader: built factories for pottery, cannon, cotton yarn; imported English textile machinery; first modern cotton spinning mill in Japan (1861); two modern shipyards
- Ōkubo Toshimichi as minister of finance oversaw beginning of industrialization
- By 1890: Japan was first Asian country to adopt written constitution — constitutional monarchy with elected parliament (Diet) and independent judiciary
- These changes were decisive for Japan becoming primary beneficiary of Industrial Revolution in Asia

### Why Japan Succeeded and China Didn't (pp. 343-345)
- Mid-19th century: both China and Japan were poor, languishing under absolutist regimes
- SIMILARITIES: both banned overseas trade, suspicious of change, opposed to economic/political reform
- KEY DIFFERENCES in political structure:
  - China: centralized bureaucratic empire ruled by absolute emperor. Constraints mainly = threat of rebellion (e.g., Taiping Rebellion 1850-1864, millions died). Opposition NOT institutionalized
  - Japan: shogunate had sidelined emperor but power was NOT absolute. Domains like Satsuma maintained independence, could even conduct own foreign trade
- British Industrial Revolution created military vulnerability for both:
  - China: humbled by British in First Opium War (1839-1842)
  - Japan: U.S. warships under Commodore Matthew Perry pulled into Edo Bay (1853)
- Reality that economic backwardness = military backwardness drove Shimazu Nariakira's plan
- In Japan, the shogun could be (and was) overthrown by a coalition of domains
- In China, overthrowing the emperor was much harder — happened only in 1911
- China instead tried to match British militarily by importing modern weapons; Japan built its own armaments industry
- Result: Japan transformed institutions → rapid economic growth; China's extractive institutions persisted → eventually worsened under Mao's communist revolution (1949)

### Roots of World Inequality — Chapter Summary (pp. 345-348)
- Three paths to inclusive institutions:
  1. **England's path**: Glorious Revolution, centuries of struggle against absolutism
  2. **Colonial path** (US, Australia): settlers demanded inclusive institutions because no indigenous population to exploit; elites (Lord Baltimore, Macarthur) couldn't establish extractive control
  3. **French Revolution path**: destroyed absolutism in France and exported reforms across Europe via invasion/Napoleon
- Japan followed path similar to France — revolution (Meiji Restoration) to change the system
- In colonies where Europeans COULD exploit (Moluccas, Caribbean, South America), extractive institutions were imposed → industrialization blocked
- In rest of Europe: Industrial Revolution intensified conflict over institutions
  - Western Europe: shared institutional drift with Britain, French Revolution as catalyst → inclusive institutions → industrialization
  - Eastern Europe (Austria-Hungary, Russia): feudalism INTENSIFIED in response → fell further behind; absolutist monarchies lasted until WWI
  - China: reacted like Eastern Europe (resisted reform)
  - Japan: reacted like Western Europe (revolutionary institutional change)
- Africa: slave trade locked much of continent into extractive institutions
- Ethiopia: absolutism remained resilient in isolation
- KEY CONCLUSION: "The rich countries of today are those that embarked on the process of industrialization and technological change starting in the nineteenth century, and the poor ones are those that did not"

## CHAPTER 11: THE VIRTUOUS CIRCLE

### The Black Act (pp. 349-355)
- Windsor Castle's forest: Baptist Nunn, keeper, in 1722 was shot at by "Blacks" — men with blackened faces demanding money
- The Blacks: groups of local men across southern England killing/maiming deer, burning haystacks, destroying fences and fish ponds
- Not mere lawlessness — response to encroachment on common people's traditional rights by newly powerful Whig elites
- Glorious Revolution 1688 was pluralistic: merchants, industrialists, gentry, aristocracy — no single group could impose will unilaterally
- Stuart restoration attempts continued: James II's son James Francis Edward Stuart ("Old Pretender") — Jacobite revolts in 1708, 1715, 1719; Charles Edward Stuart ("Young Pretender") in 1745-46 reached Derby before defeat
- Whig party (founded 1670s, representing new mercantile/economic interests) dominated Parliament 1714-1760
- Whigs tempted to abuse power but constrained by:
  - Competing groups (especially Tory Party)
  - The very institutions they'd created to prevent Stuart absolutism
  - Pluralistic nature of society — even those without formal representation had been empowered
- "Blacking" was precisely a response to perceptions that Whigs were exploiting their position

### William Cadogan Case Study (pp. 353-354)
- William Cadogan: successful general in War of Spanish Succession (1701-1714), suppressed Jacobite revolts
- Made baron 1716, earl 1718 by George I; influential member of Regency Council of Lords Justices
- Bought ~1000 acres at Caversham near Windsor, built grand house, laid out 240-acre deer park
- Encroached on surrounding rights — evicted people, abrogated traditional grazing/peat/firewood rights
- January 1, 1722 and again July: park raided by mounted, armed Blacks — first attack killed 16 deer

### The Black Act and Its Failure (pp. 354-356)
- May 1723: Parliament passed Black Act — created 50 new offenses punishable by hanging
- Made it a crime to carry weapons or have a blackened face; "blacking" itself soon punishable by hanging
- Baptist Nunn set up informer network in Windsor Forest; several arrested
- PM Robert Walpole and Cadogan directly involved — Walpole had vested interest in Richmond Park (created from common land by Charles I)
- Case of John Huntridge (Nov 10, 1724): accused of aiding deer stealers and abetting known Blacks
- Prosecution initiated by Regency Council (Walpole and Cadogan dominated)
- Walpole personally extracted evidence from informant Richard Blackburn
- Trial lasted 8-9 hours — jury found Huntridge INNOCENT, partly on procedural grounds (evidence collection irregularities)
- KEY: The jury was made up of Huntridge's "peers" — major landowners and gentry who OUGHT to have sympathized with Walpole, but upheld rule of law
- Black Act stayed on books until 1824, and many were hanged/transported, but the principle held: the rule of law constrained even the most powerful

### Rule of Law as Product of Pluralism (pp. 355-358)
- Rule of law ≠ rule BY law. Even with harsh law (Black Act), Whigs were constrained by additional principles
- The Glorious Revolution tore down "divine" rights of kings AND privileges of elites
- Rule of law = laws applied equally to all, nobody above the law
- This is "a very strange concept in historical perspective" — under absolutism, whatever is fair for king/aristocracy is banned for the rest
- Rule of law is NOT imaginable under absolutist institutions — it is a CREATION of pluralist political institutions
- E. P. Thompson quote: rulers were "prisoners of their own rhetoric; they played games of power according to rules which suited them, but they could not break those rules or the whole game would be thrown away"
- What prevented Parliament from creating new absolutism: "take away law, and the royal prerogative... might flood back upon their properties and lives"
- Moreover: "The law... in its forms and traditions, entailed principles of equity and universality which... had to be extended to all sorts and degrees of men"

### The Logic of the Virtuous Circle (pp. 358-360)
- FOUR mechanisms of virtuous circle:
  1. **Pluralism + rule of law**: constrains power, prevents any subset from imposing will on others without constraint
  2. **Inclusive economic institutions → inclusive political institutions**: more equitable income distribution empowers broader segments, levels playing field, reduces incentives for power grabs
  3. **Independent media**: pluralism allows media to flourish, helping groups organize against threats to inclusion (England stopped censoring media after 1688)
  4. **Positive feedback**: inclusive economic institutions → efficient markets, education, innovation → by 1831 clamping down on popular demands would also destroy these economic gains

- Virtuous circle is neither inevitable nor irreversible — Young Pretender reached Derby in 1745; Peterloo Massacre 1819 showed elites considered repression
- But elites pulled back from repression each time — the logic of the system made force increasingly unattractive and infeasible

### The Slow March of Democracy (pp. 359-360)
- Black Act showed common Britons they had more rights than they realized — could defend interests in courts and Parliament via petitions/lobbying
- But pluralism ≠ democracy yet: most adult men couldn't vote, women couldn't vote
- Virtuous circle: preserves what's achieved AND opens door to greater inclusiveness
- First three decades of 19th century: increasing social unrest
  - Luddite Riots (1811-1816): workers vs. new technologies
  - Spa Fields Riots (1816, London)
  - Peterloo Massacre (1819, Manchester)
  - Swing Riots (1830): agricultural workers vs. falling living standards and new technology
  - July Revolution in Paris (1830) added urgency
- Consensus forming: discontent reaching boiling point, only way to avoid revolution was meeting demands
- 1831 election: single issue = political reform. Whigs won under Earl Grey
- Earl Grey was NO radical — quote: "There is no-one more decided against annual Parliaments, universal suffrage and the ballot, than I am. My object is not to favour, but to put an end to such hopes and projects... reforming to preserve and not to overthrow"
- Chartist movement (after 1838): campaign for universal suffrage, named after "People's Charter" (parallel to Magna Carta)
- Chartist J. R. Stephens: "The question of universal suffrage... is a knife and fork question, a bread and cheese question... by universal suffrage I mean to say that every working man in the land has a right to a good coat on his back, a good hat on his head, a good roof for the shelter of his household, a good dinner upon his table"
- First Reform Act (1832): modest — doubled voting franchise from 8% to 16% of adult males (2% to 4% of total population). Eliminated rotten boroughs, gave representation to Manchester, Leeds, Sheffield
- Why did British elites concede rather than repress?
  - E. P. Thompson: "they took halting steps in the first direction. But in the end, rather than shatter their own self-image and repudiate 150 years of constitutional legality, they surrendered to the law"
  - Inclusive economic institutions had already changed the calculus: no serfs, little labor coercion, few monopolies — less to lose from reform
  - Inclusive institutions → urbanized, concentrated, organized population — much harder to repress than peasantry or serfs
- Hampden Club: one of first organizations seeking parliamentary reform, named after MP who resisted Charles I's ship money tax

## PAGES 361-380: CHAPTER 11 (cont.) — The Virtuous Circle

### Chartist Demands and Further Reform (pp. 361-362)
- People's Charter of 1838 demanded:
  - Vote for every man 21+, not undergoing punishment
  - The ballot (secret ballot) to protect voters
  - No property qualification for MPs — rich or poor
  - Payment of members — so honest tradesmen could serve
  - Equal constituencies — same representation for same number of electors
  - Annual Parliaments — to prevent bribery/intimidation
- Chartists disintegrated after 1848, succeeded by National Reform Union (1864) and Reform League (1865)
- July 1866: major pro-reform riots in Hyde Park
- Second Reform Act (1867): electorate doubled, working-class voters became majority in all urban constituencies
- Secret ballot introduced shortly after; moves to eliminate "treating" (buying votes with money/food/alcohol)
- Third Reform Act (1884): electorate doubled again, 60% of adult males enfranchised
- Representation of the People Act (1918): vote to all adult males 21+ and women 30+ (taxpayers or married to taxpayers) — quid pro quo during WWI
- Women got vote on same terms as men in 1928

### Parallel Economic Reforms (pp. 362-364)
- Corn Laws repealed 1846: had banned import of grains/cereals to keep prices high for large landowners; new Manchester/Birmingham MPs pushed for cheap corn and low wages — landed interests defeated
- 1871: PM Gladstone opened civil service to public examination — meritocratic, continuing Tudor-era political centralization
- Masters and Servants Acts repealed: had allowed employers to use law to reduce worker mobility
- 1906-1914 (Liberal Party under Asquith and Lloyd George): major expansion of public services — health and unemployment insurance, government-financed pensions, minimum wages, redistributive taxation
- Taxes as proportion of national product: more than doubled in last three decades of 19th century, then doubled again in first three decades of 20th
- Tax system became "progressive" — wealthier bore heavier burden
- Education Act of 1870: first commitment to universal education. Free by 1891. School-leaving age: 11 (1870s), then 12 (1899)
- Proportion of 10-year-olds in school: 40% in 1870 → 100% in 1900
- Education Act of 1902: expanded resources for schools, introduced grammar schools — foundation of secondary education
- KEY: "gradual virtuous circle" — each decade brought a step (sometimes small, sometimes large) toward democracy; virtuous circle reduced stakes of each step, making conflicts more likely to be resolved by inclusion rather than repression
- Edmund Burke (1790) wrote against French Revolution: "It is with infinite caution that any man should venture upon pulling down an edifice" — wrong about French Revolution being pointless, but right that gradual reform is more durable

### Busting Trusts (pp. 365-371)
- US inclusive institutions rooted in colonial struggles (Virginia, Maryland, Carolinas) + reinforced by Constitution (separation of powers)
- By mid-19th century: all white males could vote; Homestead Act (1862) made frontier land available to settlers
- Post-Civil War: rapid economic growth in the North → vast fortunes → Robber Barons consolidated monopolies
- Cornelius Vanderbilt: "What do I care about the Law? Hain't I got the power?"
- John D. Rockefeller: Standard Oil Company (1870), eliminated rivals in Cleveland, monopolized transportation/retailing of oil. By 1882 had a massive trust. By 1890 controlled 88% of refined oil flows. Became world's first billionaire (1916). Contemporary cartoons showed Standard Oil as octopus wrapping around oil industry and Capitol Hill
- John Pierpont Morgan: founded J.P. Morgan (later JPMorgan Chase). With Andrew Carnegie, founded U.S. Steel Company (1901) — first corporation over $1 billion capitalized
- 1890s: large trusts in nearly every sector, many controlling 70%+ of market (Du Pont, Eastman Kodak, International Harvester)
- Populist movement: emerged from agrarian crisis (late 1860s onward). National Grange of the Order of Patrons of Husbandry (Grangers) founded 1867
  - 1873-1874: Grangers won control of 11 midwestern state legislatures
  - People's Party (1892): got 8.5% of popular vote in presidential election
  - Populists fell behind William Jennings Bryan's unsuccessful Democratic campaigns
- Progressive movement emerged from Populist ashes:
  - Teddy Roosevelt: became president after McKinley's assassination (1901). Former uncompromising NY governor who fought "machine politics"
  - First address to Congress: trusts have "features and tendencies hurtful to the general welfare... combination and concentration should be, not prohibited, but supervised and within reasonable limits controlled"
- KEY LEGISLATION:
  - Interstate Commerce Act (1887): created Interstate Commerce Commission, initiated federal regulation of industry
  - Sherman Antitrust Act (1890): basis for attacks on trusts — still major part of US antitrust law
  - Presidents who took action: Theodore Roosevelt (1901-09), William Taft (1909-13), Woodrow Wilson (1913-21)
  - 1902: Roosevelt used Sherman Act to break up Northern Securities Company (J.P. Morgan)
  - Hepburn Act (1906): strengthened ICC powers
  - Taft: prosecuted trusts even more aggressively — high point was breakup of Standard Oil (1911). Also promoted federal income tax (Sixteenth Amendment, 1913)
  - Wilson: Clayton Antitrust Act (1914), created Federal Trade Commission. Also created Federal Reserve Board (1913)
  - Pujo Committee (led by Louisiana congressman Arsene Pujo): investigated "money trust" in financial industry
- Wilson quote from *The New Freedom* (1913): "If monopoly persists, monopoly will always sit at the helm of government. I do not expect to see monopoly restrain itself. If there are men in this country big enough to own the government of the United States, they are going to own it"
- KEY: 59 of the petitions to Congress before the Sherman Act came from farming states and farm organizations (Farmers' Union, Farmers' Alliance, Patrons of Animal Husbandry)
- ARGUMENT: Markets left alone can become dominated by monopolies — inclusive ECONOMIC institutions require not just markets but INCLUSIVE markets backed by inclusive political institutions. Contrast with Mexico (Carlos Slim's monopoly — no political body to restrict it)

### Role of Free Media: The Muckrakers (pp. 371-372)
- Roosevelt coined term "muckraker" (1906) — from Bunyan's *Pilgrim's Progress* — for intrusive journalists
- Ida Tarbell: *History of the Standard Oil Company* (1904) — key role in moving public opinion, leading to breakup (1911)
- Louis Brandeis: lawyer/author, later Supreme Court justice appointed by Wilson. Wrote *Other People's Money and How Bankers Use It* — influenced Pujo Committee
- William Randolph Hearst: serialized David Graham Phillips's articles "The Treason of the Senate" in *The Cosmopolitan* (1906) → galvanized campaign for direct Senate elections → Seventeenth Amendment (1913)
- KEY: Robber Barons hated muckrakers but inclusive political institutions made it impossible to stamp them out. Free media is essential to virtuous circle

### Packing the Court (pp. 372-380)
- FDR elected 1932 during Great Depression. Inaugural 1933: one-quarter of labor force unemployed, industrial production fallen by half
- New Deal legislation:
  - National Industrial Recovery Act (NIRA): Title I — restrained competition, gave workers union rights, regulated standards. Title II — Public Works Administration (Thirtieth St railroad station, Triborough Bridge, Grand Coulee Dam, Overseas Highway to Key West)
  - Signed June 16, 1933 — immediately faced court challenges
  - May 27, 1935: Supreme Court unanimously struck down NIRA Title I as unconstitutional — "extraordinary conditions do not create or enlarge constitutional power"
  - Social Security Act: introduced modern welfare state (pensions, unemployment, aid to families, disability)
  - National Labor Relations Act: strengthened union rights, collective bargaining, right to strike
- FDR reelected 1936 with 61% of vote; then attempted court-packing
- Fireside Chat (March 9, 1937): described government as "three-horse team" — Congress and executive pulling together, courts not. Complained Supreme Court had upheld policies by only 5-to-4
- Proposed Judiciary Reorganization Bill: compulsory retirement at 70, allowing president to appoint up to 6 new justices
- Only ~40% of public supported the plan
- Louis Brandeis (now Supreme Court justice): despite sympathizing with FDR's legislation, spoke AGAINST attempts to erode Court's power
- House of Representatives refused to deal with bill
- Senate Judiciary Committee sent back negative report: bill was "needless, futile and utterly dangerous abandonment of constitutional principle... without precedent or justification"
- Senate voted 70-20 to strip all court-packing elements
- KEY: FDR's powers remained constrained — Social Security and NLRA both ruled constitutional anyway
- LESSON: Inclusive political institutions resist attempts to undermine their own continuation — same logic as Walpole and the Black Act

### Contrast: Argentina's Court-Packing SUCCESS (pp. 378-380)
- Argentina's 1853 constitution created Supreme Court modeled on US
- 1887 decision gave it similar role to US Supreme Court in reviewing constitutionality
- 1946: Juan Domingo Perón elected president (former colonel, rose to prominence after 1943 military coup as minister of labor, built coalition with trade unions)
- Shortly after election, Chamber of Deputies impeached 4 of 5 Supreme Court justices; 4th resigned. Senate approved. Perón appointed 4 new justices
- Result: Perón exercised unchecked power, ruled as dictator; his judges ruled conviction of Ricardo Balbín (opposition Radical Party leader) was constitutional
- Perón removed in 1955 coup → long sequence of military/civilian transitions, each regime picking own Supreme Court justices
- 1990: Carlos Saúl Menem (Perónist Party) became president after democratic transition from Raúl Alfonsín (Radical Party)
  - Should have had no reason to change court — but Menem tried to get justices to resign
  - Offered Justice Carlos Fayt an ambassadorship; Fayt sent back copy of his book *Law and Ethics* inscribed "Beware I wrote this"
  - Within 3 months Menem proposed expanding Court from 5 to 9 — Senate/Chamber passed it quickly
  - With his majority, Menem rewrote constitution to remove term limits, then tried again after reelection (blocked by factions within his own Perónist Party)
- KEY CONTRAST: In US, pluralistic institutions created broad segments willing to defend Court's independence. In Argentina, extractive institutions meant legislators were happy to undermine Court because much to gain from overthrowing constraints. Without pluralism, no group defends institutional checks because each fears its own power will be challenged next

### Positive Feedback and Virtuous Circles — Chapter Summary (pp. 380)
- Inclusive institutions emerge during critical junctures from significant conflict between elites resisting change and those wanting to limit elite power
- Once in place, they create VIRTUOUS CIRCLE via positive feedback:
  1. Pluralism → rule of law → laws cannot be used selectively → opens door for greater participation
  2. Inclusive political institutions support inclusive economic institutions → removes slavery/serfdom, reduces monopoly, creates dynamic economy → less to gain from power grabs
  3. Under extractive institutions (Austria-Hungary, Russia), elites had too much to lose → met calls for inclusion with repression
  4. In Britain by 18th century, inclusive economic institutions already in place → elites had less at stake → repression increasingly infeasible against urbanized, organized population

## PAGES 381-400: CHAPTER 12: THE VICIOUS CIRCLE

### You Can't Take the Train to Bo Anymore (pp. 382-390)
- Sierra Leone became British colony 1896; Freetown founded late 18th century for freed slaves
- Interior: many small kingdoms. British used treaties, gave rulers title "paramount chief"
- King Suluku of Kono made Paramount Chief Suluku; chieftaincy of Sandor created
- Hut Tax Rebellion (Jan 1898): 5 shillings per house → civil war. Strongest in south (Mendeland/Mende)
- Railway from Freetown: route CHANGED after rebellion — went south to Bo/Mendeland for military access
- Independence 1961: Sir Milton Margai/SLPP (southern support). 1964: Albert Margai. 1967: APC under Siaka Stevens (Limba, northern) won narrowly
- Stevens pulled up the railway to Mendeland, sold track/rolling stock — to weaken Mende/SLPP opponents
- Like Tsar Nicholas I fearing railways would bring revolution — Stevens believed railways would strengthen opponents
- Made himself president 1971; one-party state 1978; stayed in power until 1985 by killing/harassing opponents

### Colonial Continuity (pp. 385-390)
- Marketing boards: colonial invention to "smooth price fluctuations" — became tool to heavily tax farmers
  - Mid-1960s: palm kernel 56%, cocoa 48%, coffee 49% of world price
  - By 1985 (Momoh): 37%, 19%, 27%. Under Stevens: sometimes as low as 10% — 90% extracted
  - Money not for public services — to enrich Stevens and buy political support
- Paramount chiefs: life tenure, from "ruling houses." 2005: Sandor elected Sheku Fasuluku, Suluku's great-great-grandson
- Chiefs as "custodians of the land" — can't buy/sell/use as collateral; outsiders can't plant perennial crops
- Robert Bates (political scientist, 1980s): marketing boards removed incentives to invest/fertilize/preserve soil

### Diamonds: Sierra Leone vs. Australia (pp. 388-390)
- Diamonds in Kono (Jan 1930): alluvial. British gave monopoly to Sierra Leone Selection Trust (De Beers)
- 1936: De Beers created Diamond Protection Force (private army larger than colonial government)
- 1950s: overwhelmed by illegal miners. 1955: some fields opened. 1970: Stevens nationalized → NDMC (51% govt stake)
- Australia (gold, 1851): also alluvial. Squatters wanted monopoly/fences. Inclusive model won: anyone could buy mining license. Diggers pushed universal suffrage/secret ballot in Victoria

### Indirect Rule Legacy (pp. 390-392)
- Indirect rule: created hereditary aristocracy where none existed; replaced fluid system with rigid, life-tenure chiefs beholden to Freetown/Britain
- Margai family: sided with British during Hut Tax Rebellion, chief Nyama deposed; Margais became chiefs until 2010
- Stevens emasculated army, created paramilitary: ISU ("I Shoot U") and SSD ("Siaka Stevens's Dogs")
- April 29, 1992: just 30 soldiers under Captain Valentine Strasser overthrew APC
- Pattern replicated across Africa: Ghana, Kenya, Zambia — extractive institutions re-created

### Vicious Circle Mechanisms (pp. 392-393)
- Extractive institutions → enrich few → resources to build armies, buy judges, rig elections
- No checks on power → absolute power corrupts (Lord Acton)
  - Sam Bangura (central bank governor, 1980): criticized Stevens → murdered, thrown from top floor onto Siaka Stevens Street
- High stakes of political game → infighting to control power (Maya city-states, Rome)
- African conflicts: not to create pluralism but to capture power → Angola, Burundi, Chad, Côte d'Ivoire, DRC, Ethiopia, Liberia, Mozambique, Nigeria, Congo-Brazzaville, Rwanda, Somalia, Sudan, Uganda, Sierra Leone

### From Encomienda to Land Grab: Guatemala (pp. 393-400)
- Jan 14, 1993: President De León Carpio, Finance Minister Aitkenhead Castillo, Development Minister Castillo Sinibaldi — ALL descendants of 16th-century conquistadors
- Marta Casaús Arzú (sociologist): 22 core families + 26 connected families have controlled Guatemala since 1531; elite = ~1% of population in 1990s
- Conquest: ~2 million Mayas; population not recovered until 1920s due to disease
- Encomienda → repartimiento/mandamiento → Consulado de Comercio (trade monopoly)
- Cadiz Constitution → independence → Rafael Carrera dictatorship (1839-1871) maintained colonial institutions
- Consulado sabotaged infrastructure: refused Pacific port at Suchitepéquez (would undermine Caribbean monopoly); refused roads from Los Altos (would create competing merchants)
- Coffee boom → 1871 "Liberal" coup (García Granados, then Barrios after 1873) — same families, abolished Consulado but not extractive politics
- Land grab: 1871-1883, ~1 million acres of indigenous communal land + frontier privatized to elite
- Barrios (1876) to governors: provide farm owners "the number of workers they need, be it fifty or one hundred"
- Decree 177 (1877): repartimiento institutionalized — 60 workers for 15-30 days, renewable
- Libreta system: workbook with employer/debt details; indebted workers couldn't leave
- Vagrancy laws: can't prove employment → forced labor
- Repartimiento lasted to 1920s; libreta/vagrancy laws to 1945
- Jorge Ubico (president 1931-1944, unopposed): banned words "obreros," "sindicatos," "huelgas" — jailed for using them
- June 24, 1944: Memorial de los 311 → Ubico resigned July 1 → brief democracy → 1954 coup → civil war → democracy only 1986
- KEY: Form of extraction changed over 500 years but extractive nature and elite identity persisted — vicious circle

### From Slavery to Jim Crow (pp. 399-400)
- U.S. South: extractive institutions dominated by plantation owners
- 1860: manufacturing output less than PA, NY, or MA individually; only 9% urban (vs. 35% in Northeast); railroad density 3x lower than North
- 1840: Mississippi River counties up to 95% enslaved; 1880: areas with heavy slavery had basically zero manufacturing
- Patents 1837-1859: corn/wheat averaged 12/10 per year; cotton (South's main crop) just 1 per year
- Civil War defeat → slavery abolished, black men allowed to vote — reform at bayonet point

## PAGES 401-420: CHAPTER 12 (cont.) / CHAPTER 13: WHY NATIONS FAIL TODAY

### Jim Crow and the Persistence of Extraction (pp. 401-407)
- Despite abolition and black voting rights, vicious circle reasserted — Jim Crow replaced slavery
- Jim Crow: from "Jump Jim Crow" blackface satire; refers to entire gamut of segregationist legislation after 1865, persisted nearly a century
- Planters "lost the war but would win the peace" — still organized, still owned the land
- "Forty acres and a mule" promised during war (Gen. Sherman), but President Andrew Johnson revoked orders in 1865
- Congressman Julian: "Of what avail would be an act of congress totally abolishing slavery... if the old agricultural basis of aristocratic power shall remain?"
- Sociologist Jonathan Wiener: 5 Alabama Black Belt counties — of 236 planter elite (1850), 101 maintained position in 1870; of 25 with largest landholdings in 1870, 18 (72%) were elite in 1860, 16 in 1850
- Civil War exemption: one slaveholder per 20 slaves exempted from military service → big planters survived while 600,000+ died
- W.E.B. Du Bois: South became "simply an armed camp for intimidating black folk"
- Alabama Black Code (1865): vagrancy + anti-enticement laws — impeded labor mobility, like Guatemala's Decree 177
- Reconstruction (1865-1877): Union Army enforced changes, but "Redeemers" systematically fought back
- 1877: Hayes needed southern electoral votes → agreed to withdraw Union soldiers → "redemption"
- Poll taxes + literacy tests disenfranchised blacks (and poor whites) → one-party Democratic regime under planter elite
- Alabama constitution 1901, Section 256: mandated separate schools — amendment to strike it NARROWLY DEFEATED in 2004
- KKK: often financed by elite. Southern politicians in Washington blocked any federal projects threatening elite control
- 1900: 13.5% South urbanized vs. 60% Northeast; still hand labor and mule power
- Crumbled only after WWII + civil rights movement (1950s-60s); rapid convergence began then

### The Iron Law of Oligarchy (pp. 407-413)
- Ethiopia's Solomonic dynasty → 1974 Derg coup (Marxist officers)
- Haile Selassie: held court at Grand Palace, special pillow bearer with 52 pillows (Selassie was small, feet couldn't touch ground). Extreme extractive institutions, no development
- Derg initially 108 military reps. Major Mengistu Haile Mariam (Harar). July 4, 1974: declared loyalty to emperor. Then arrested government, then emperor (Sept 12). Executions began
- Dec 1974: socialist state declared. Selassie died (probably murdered) Aug 27, 1975
- 1975: nationalized all land + most property → opposition → Eritrean/Tigrayan independence movements, Somali invasion of Ogaden
- Mengistu: most ruthless, eliminated rivals by mid-1977. Saved by Soviet/Cuban weapons (Nov 1977)
- 1978: 4th anniversary — Mengistu in gilded armchair at Grand Palace, on Selassie's throne. Compared himself to Emperor Tewodros
- Minister Dawit Wolde Giorgis: "At the beginning... neckties were considered criminal... Then around 1978... Designer clothes from the best European tailors... We had the best of everything... It was a complete reversal of the ideals of the Revolution"
- On Mengistu: "vengeful, cruel and authoritarian... We were supposed to have a revolution of equality; now he had become the new Emperor"
- Robert Michels: "iron law of oligarchy" — even entirely new groups reproduce the same extractive system
- Laurent Kabila (Congo): overthrew Mobutu → set up equally corrupt regime, aided by Mobutu's own former minister. Mobutu's regime itself modeled on King Leopold's Congo Free State
- Mengistu used FAMINE as political weapon (contrast: Selassie had been merely indifferent to Wollo famine 1973)

### Why Some Revolutions Succeed (pp. 412-414)
- Three factors that made Glorious Revolution and French Revolution different:
  1. New merchants/businessmen wanted creative destruction, not another extractive system
  2. Broad coalition (not narrow coup): merchants, industrialists, gentry, diverse political groups
  3. Historical tradition of power-sharing (Magna Carta, Assembly of Notables) → harder for new rulers to establish unchecked control
- In Sierra Leone, Ethiopia, Congo: none present — no merchant class, no broad coalition, no power-sharing tradition, colonial period eliminated entrepreneurship

### Chapter 12 Summary: Three Forms of Vicious Circle (pp. 414-416)
1. **Same elite persists** (Guatemala, U.S. South): form of extraction changes but extractive nature and elite identity persist
2. **Iron law of oligarchy** (Ethiopia, Sierra Leone, Congo): new rulers reproduce same extractive system
3. **Extractive institutions breed infighting**: huge inequality + unchecked power → many willing to fight for control → civil wars → state failure
- Vicious circles NOT destiny (Ch. 14) but are resilient

## CHAPTER 13: WHY NATIONS FAIL TODAY

### How to Win the Lottery in Zimbabwe (pp. 418-420)
- Jan 2000: Zimbank national lottery — MC Fallot Chawawa drew winning ticket: President Robert Mugabe. Prize: Z$100,000 (~5x annual per capita income)
- By 2008: per capita income about HALF of 1980 level (independence). Health system collapsed → cholera: 98,741 cases, 4,293 deaths by Jan 10, 2010. Unemployment: 94% (UN estimate, early 2009)

### Zimbabwe's Colonial Origins (pp. 419-420)
- 1890: Cecil Rhodes's BSAC expedition into Ndebele kingdom → 1901: Southern Rhodesia colony
- Rich farmland attracted white settlers; by 1923 self-government → white-only apartheid modeled on South Africa
- 1960s: Ian Smith's white elite (~5% of population) declared independence 1965 → UN sanctions → black guerrilla war
- ZANU (Mugabe) + ZAPU (Joshua Nkomo) → negotiated end to white rule → Zimbabwe created 1980
- Mugabe eliminated opponents (up to 20,000 killed in Matabeleland), merged ZAPU into ZANU-PF (1987)
- Rewrote constitution: president (from PM), abolished Senate, introduced nominated positions → one-party state
- Took over colonial extractive institutions: price regulations, marketing boards, state industries, patronage jobs for ZANU-PF
- Tight regulation prevented independent African business class (like Ghana 1960s)
- 1991: IMF reforms after fiscal crisis → MDC opposition emerged
- 1995: ZANU-PF won 118/120 seats (55 unopposed). 1996: Mugabe won 93% after opponents withdrew
- After 2000: weakening — only 49% popular vote, 63 seats. MDC took all Harare seats. 2002: Mugabe won 56% via violence/fraud
- Mugabe's response: intensified repression + full-scale assault on white landowners (land occupations from 2000, by "war veterans")
- Much expropriated land went to ZANU-PF elites, not just war veterans
- Property rights insecurity → collapse of agricultural output and productivity
- Only option left: print money → hyperinflation. Jan 2009: Zimbabwean dollar abandoned, replaced by South African rand and other currencies
- Zimbabwe = iron law of oligarchy: Ian Smith's extractive regime replaced by Mugabe's equally extractive regime

## PAGES 421-434: CHAPTER 13 (cont.) — Why Nations Fail Today

### Chapter 13 Framework (pp. 422-423)
- Nations fail because extractive economic institutions don't create incentives to save, invest, innovate
- Extractive political institutions cement power of beneficiaries
- Two forms: (1) lack of economic activity because politicians extract/quash independent business; (2) extreme cases where extractive institutions cause complete state failure
- State failure examples: Angola, Cameroon, Chad, DRC, Haiti, Liberia, Nepal, Sierra Leone, Sudan, Zimbabwe — civil wars, famines, epidemics, many poorer today than in 1960s

### A Children's Crusade? — Sierra Leone Civil War (pp. 423-427)
- March 23, 1991: Foday Sankoh crossed from Liberia into Sierra Leone, attacked Kailahun
- Sankoh: former corporal, imprisoned after abortive 1971 coup against Stevens, ended up in Libya at Qaddafi's training camp for African revolutionaries
- Met Charles Taylor (plotting Liberian coup) in Libya; Taylor invaded Liberia Christmas Eve 1989
- Sankoh invaded Sierra Leone with Taylor's men (Liberians, Burkinabes) as the RUF (Revolutionary United Front)
- Stevens's quote: "The cow eats where it is tethered" — Momoh gorged even more
- Under Momoh: roads fell apart, schools disintegrated, national TV stopped 1987 (transmitter sold by minister of information), radio tower collapsed 1989
- 1995 Freetown newspaper: "by the end of Momoh's rule he had stopped paying civil servants, teachers and even Paramount Chiefs"
- "sobels" = soldiers turned rebels — impossible to tell soldier from rebel
- RUF manifesto "Footpaths to Democracy" — opened with Frantz Fanon quote: "Each generation must, out of relative obscurity, discover its mission, fulfill it or betray it"
- RUF quickly lost any intellectual roots; Sankoh executed critics of atrocities
- Forcible recruitment of children — all sides did this, including government army
- Massacres, mass rapes, amputation of hands and ears
- RUF in diamond areas: press-ganged people into diamond mining
- War ended 2001: ~80,000 dead, country devastated
- Koidu (diamond area): still rows of burned-out, bullet-scarred houses today

### State Failure as Consequence of Vicious Circle (pp. 426-428)
- By 1991 Sierra Leone was already a failed state — no capacity to oppose RUF invasion
- Stevens had emasculated the military (feared overthrow) → state couldn't defend itself
- Compare Bushong kingdom (King Shyaam): even extractive central authority was better than no law/order (Lele)
- African state failure: partly because political centralization was historically delayed, partly because vicious circle REVERSED any centralization that existed
- Failed states arise from legacy of extractive institutions that concentrate power/wealth → unrest, strife, civil war
- Extractive institutions directly cause state failure by neglecting investment in public services

### Who Is the State? Colombia (pp. 428-434)
- Colombia: seems democratic — regular elections since 1958, National Front pact (Conservatives/Liberals alternating)
- But history of civil liberties violations, extrajudicial executions, violence against civilians, civil war
- La Violencia (1950s civil war) → military rule until 1958 → guerrilla groups since then
- Rural Colombia: must pay "vacuna" ("vaccination") — monthly protection payment to armed groups
- FARC kidnapping: Jesus Castaño, dairy farmer in Amalfi, Antioquia — kidnapped 1981, $7,500 ransom, family mortgaged farm, found father's corpse chained to tree
- Castaño sons (Carlos, Fidel, Vicente) founded Los Tangueros paramilitary → grew into AUC (Autodefensas Unidas de Colombia) by 1997
- AUC: up to 30,000 armed men by 2001; Bloque Catatumbo in Córdoba led by Salvatore Mancuso
- Pact of Santa Fé de Ralito: "refounding of the country" signed by paramilitary leaders ("Jorge 40," "Don Berna," Diego Vecino) and senators (William Montes, Miguel de la Espriella)
- San Onofre (Sucre) 2002 election: paramilitary leader Cadena forced voters at gunpoint; threatened to kill council members if his candidate lost
- Each candidate got 40,000 votes; ~1/3 of congressmen owed 2002 election to paramilitaries
- Mancuso quote: "35 percent of the Congress was elected in areas where there were Self-Defense groups"
- IDMC: ~10% of Colombia's population (~4.5 million) internally displaced by early 2010
- Paramilitaries expropriated up to 10% of all rural land; Mancuso accumulated ~$25 million in property
- Casanare: highest per capita income (oil), paramilitaries demanded 50% of municipal budget, 10% of every contract
- 2002: Álvaro Uribe elected (father killed by FARC) — vote share 3% higher in paramilitary areas; 11% higher in 2006
- Uribe changed constitution for reelection (2006); in exchange delivered lenient demobilization law
- Demobilization ≠ end of paramilitarism — institutionalized paramilitary control in Colombian state
- KEY: Colombia lacks centralized authority; symbiotic relationship between national politicians and paramilitary groups

### El Corralito: Argentina (pp. 434)
- Late 2001: economic crisis — 3 years of falling income, rising unemployment, massive international debt
- Menem (1991): pegged peso to dollar 1:1; dollars used in shops and ATMs
- Stabilized economy but made exports expensive → trade deficit → borrowing
- Dec 1, 2001: government froze all bank accounts for 90 days; weekly withdrawal limit 250 pesos (then 300 from peso accounts only)
- "El Corralito" = "the Little Corral" — depositors hemmed in like cows
- January 2002: devaluation — 4 pesos per dollar. Government forcibly converted dollar accounts to pesos at old 1:1 rate
- Someone with $1,000 saved → suddenly had only $250 worth. Government expropriated 3/4 of people's savings
- Simon Kuznets famous remark: four types of countries — developed, undeveloped, Japan, and Argentina
- Argentina was one of richest countries pre-WWI; steady decline relative to rich world; absolute decline in 1970s-80s

### Argentina's Extractive Trajectory (pp. 435-437)
- Pre-1914: ~50 years of growth under extractive institutions — narrow elite exporting beef/hides/grain during commodity boom
- Growth without creative destruction, not sustainable
- WWI → political instability → 1930 first military coup → oscillated between dictatorship and democracy until 1983
- Military repression peaked 1970s: at least 9,000 illegally executed, hundreds of thousands imprisoned/tortured
- Perón (1940s onward): Partido Justicialista dominated democratic periods — political machine buying votes, patronage, corruption
- Power concentrated in Perónist Party with few constraints; if Supreme Court challenged → packed/replaced
- Perón cultivated labor in 1940s; by 1970s-80s switched to buying votes directly
- Menem rewrote constitution to remove term limits — more of same
- Buenos Aires vs. interior: Buenos Aires = elegant Belle Epoch architecture; but Menem from Anillaco, La Rioja province
- La Rioja: former Inca Empire territory, encomiendas, produced warlord Facundo Quiroga (19th century)
- Argentine institutional story = interior provinces (La Rioja etc.) reached agreements with Buenos Aires: warlords leave Buenos Aires alone to make money; Buenos Aires elites give up reforming interior
- Interior extractive politics embedded into national institutions → Argentina followed same path as other extractive Latin American countries

### Latin American Democracy Without Pluralism (pp. 437-438)
- Elections in Latin America have NOT brought inclusive institutions — typical pattern
- Venezuela under Chávez: attacks opponents, fires from public-sector jobs, closes newspapers, expropriates property
- Chávez less constrained than Walpole was in 1720s Britain
- Why voters support strongmen like Perón/Chávez: centuries of extractive elite rule left populations without basic services → vote for anyone promising redistribution, even if corrupt
- Perón, Chávez, and dozens of Latin American strongmen = iron law of oligarchy: extractive institutions produce strongmen who reproduce extraction

### The New Absolutism: North Korea (pp. 438-440)
- Nov 2009: North Korea currency reform — removed 2 zeros (100 old won = 1 new won)
- Catch: max conversion 100,000 won (later raised to 500,000) — 100,000 won ≈ $40 on black market
- Government wiped out huge fraction of citizens' private wealth — probably greater expropriation than Argentina 2002
- Purpose: punish people using black markets, prevent anyone getting wealthy/powerful enough to threaten regime
- Kim Jong-Il: seven-story pleasure palace with bar, karaoke, mini movie theater, swimming pool with wave machine and body board
- 2006 US sanctions: banned export of 60+ luxury items to North Korea (yachts, water scooters, racing cars, TVs >29 inches, silk scarves, designer pens, furs, leather luggage)
- Kim's annual cognac budget estimated at $800,000/year (Hennessy sales figures)

### Communism as New Absolutism (pp. 440-441)
- Marx's vision vs. reality: Bolshevik Revolution 1917 created new elite at head of Communist Party
- Lenin's entourage purged non-communists AND rival communists
- Stalin's collectivization + purges: up to 40 million killed
- Pattern repeated: Cambodia (Khmer Rouge 1970s), China (Mao), North Korea
- Communist economic institutions = extractive: designed to extract from people, abolish property rights → poverty not prosperity
- Communist economic institutions supported by extractive political institutions concentrating all power in party

### King Cotton: Uzbekistan (pp. 441-444)
- Cotton = 45% of Uzbekistan's exports; 2,048 state farms broken up after 1991 independence
- President Ismail Karimov: farmers forced to allocate 35% of land to cotton, paid fraction of world price
- At independence: 40% of harvest picked by combine harvesters; under Karimov, farmers wouldn't maintain machines
- Karimov's solution: schoolchildren. 2.7 million children (2006) emptied from schools each September
- Gulnaz (mother): "classes are suspended... children are sent to the cotton harvest. Nobody asks for the consent of parents"
- Children assigned 20-60 kg/day quota depending on age; sleep in sheds with animals; no toilets/kitchens; bring own food
- 2006: world cotton price ~$1.40/kg, children paid ~$0.03 per quota. ~75% of cotton harvest now picked by children
- Schools also closed in spring for hoeing, weeding, transplanting

### Karimov's Political Control (pp. 444-445)
- Former Communist Party first secretary; reinvented as nationalist in 1989 as Berlin Wall fell
- Won Dec 1991 presidential election with security forces' support; cracked down on all opposition
- No free media, no NGOs; 2005 Andijon massacre: ~750 demonstrators killed by police/army
- Extended term to 5 years by referendum, then won 7-year term in 2000 with 91.2% (only opponent declared he voted for Karimov!)
- 2007 reelection: 88% of vote, widely considered fraudulent
- Elections compared to Stalin's 1937 Soviet elections — NYT correspondent Harold Denny's *Pravda* account: "100 per cent! What election in what country for what candidate has given a 100 per cent response?"

### Uzbekistan's Extractive Economy (pp. 445-446)
- 1/3 of population in poverty; average annual income ~$1,000
- School enrollment 100% — except during cotton picking season
- Karimov family and former communist cadres = new economic/political elite
- Karimov's daughter Gulnora expected to succeed him; family controls unknown extent of economy
- U.S. company Interspan case: invested in Uzbek tea industry, took 30%+ of local market by 2005
- Gulnora decided tea industry was promising → Interspan personnel arrested, beaten, tortured; Aug 2006 company pulled out
- Interspan's assets taken over by Karimov family tea interests (from 2% to 67% of market)
- Uzbekistan shares pattern with Armenia, Azerbaijan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan — former Soviet states with extractive institutions

### Keeping the Playing Field at an Angle: Egypt (pp. 447-449)
- 1990s reforms: rhetoric of socialism lapsed, markets opened — but not inclusive markets
- Markets controlled by handful of businessmen allied with NDP (National Democratic Party, founded by Sadat 1978)
- Under Mubarak: businessmen → party → government posts
  - Rasheed Mohamed Rasheed (former Unilever AMET president) → minister of foreign trade
  - Mohamed Zoheir Wahid Garana (Garana Travel Company) → minister of tourism
  - Amin Ahmed Mohamed Osman Abaza (Nile Cotton Trade Company) → minister of agriculture
- Entry barriers in media, iron/steel, automotive, alcoholic beverages, cement — protecting connected businessmen
- Ahmed Ezz: chairman of Ezz Steel (70% of Egypt's steel), high-ranking NDP member, chairman of People's Assembly Budget Committee, close to Gamal Mubarak
- Privatization (1990s): like Mexico's — state monopolies became private monopolies enriching connected "whales" (32 families dominated economy)
- Ahmed Zayat / Luxor Group example: privatization of Al Ahram Beverages (ABC, monopoly beer maker)
  - Competing bid of 400 million Egyptian pounds rejected as "too low" — but bidders weren't connected enough
  - Zayat floated ABC shares on London Stock Exchange, bought 74.9% at 68.5 pounds/share, split shares, sold at 52.5 each → 36% profit → funded 231 million pound purchase of ABC
  - ABC had 41.3 million annual profit and 93 million cash reserves — a bargain
  - 1999: bought Gianaclis wine monopoly (3,000% import tariff, 70% profit margin)
  - 2002: sold ABC to Heineken for 1.3 billion Egyptian pounds — 563% profit in 5 years
- Mohamed Nosseir: bought El Nasr Bottling (Coca-Cola monopoly in Egypt) in 1993 with little competition due to connections to minister Atef Ebeid; sold 2 years later for 3x price
- State cinema privatization: only 2 families (including Sawiris) allowed to bid
- Mubarak planned dynastic succession (son Gamal); cut short by Arab Spring 2011
- Under Nasser: some inclusive economic aspects (education, opportunities) but unstable combo with extractive politics
- Under Mubarak: economic institutions became MORE extractive → Arab Spring reaction
- Tunisia similar: 3 decades of growth under Ben Ali, then family preyed more on economy

### Why Nations Fail — Chapter Summary (pp. 449)
- Nations fail because of extractive institutions across diverse settings:
  - Africa: Zimbabwe, Sierra Leone
  - South America: Colombia, Argentina
  - Asia: North Korea, Uzbekistan
  - Middle East: Egypt
- Common thread: elite designs economic institutions to enrich themselves and perpetuate power at expense of population

### Comparative Extractive Institutions (pp. 450-452)
- Different histories → different elites → different forms of extraction, but always vicious circle
  - Zimbabwe: ZANU-PF from anticolonial fight → elections as cloak for one-party state
  - North Korea: Kim dynasty + Communist Party → abolished private property
  - Uzbekistan: Karimov hijacked Soviet state apparatus → crushed opposition
  - Colombia: fragmented elites + lack of state authority → paramilitaries + national politicians in symbiosis
- North Korea: communist toolkit (abolition of property, state farms); Egypt under Nasser similar (nationalized Suez Canal, Soviet-aligned)
- Egypt's crony capitalism still generated more growth than North Korea's total extraction — less extreme extraction = somewhat better outcomes
- Argentina's income per capita is double Colombia's — political institutions do a better job restraining elites
- Intensity of extraction correlates with depth of poverty
- Even when extractive institutions lead to state collapse (Sierra Leone, Zimbabwe), this doesn't end extractive institutions
  - Sierra Leone 2007: APC (Stevens's old party) returned to power; Ernest Bai Koroma won presidency, but many cabinet members from old APC era; Stevens's sons Bockarie and Jengo made ambassadors

### Vicious Circles and Their Roots (pp. 452-454)
- All cases share long history of extractive institutions since at least 19th century
- Colombia/Argentina: rooted in Spanish colonial institutions
- Zimbabwe/Sierra Leone: British colonial regimes built on precolonial extractive structures intensified by slave trade
- Uzbekistan: Soviet extractive institutions were continuation of tsarist regime — iron law of oligarchy
- Solution: transform extractive → inclusive institutions. Not easy, but not impossible
- What can break vicious circle: preexisting inclusive elements, broad coalitions, contingent nature of history, luck
- Glorious Revolution 1688: Parliament was already powerful, broad coalition (merchants, industrialists, gentry), different from Sierra Leone civil war — iron law of oligarchy less likely when many groups share power

---

## CHAPTER 14: BREAKING THE MOLD

### Three African Chiefs — Botswana's Origins (pp. 455-460)
- September 6, 1895: ocean liner *Tantallon Castle* docked at Plymouth; three Tswana chiefs — Khama (Ngwato), Bathoen (Ngwaketse), Sebele (Kwena) — arrived in Britain
- Mission: save their states from Cecil Rhodes's British South Africa Company (BSAC)
- Ngwato, Ngwaketse, Kwena = 3 of 8 Tswana states forming Bechuanaland (later Botswana, independent 1966)
- Tswana traded with Europeans since 19th century; David Livingstone traveled Bechuanaland in 1840s, converted King Sechele of Kwena to Christianity
- First Bible translation into African language was in Setswana
- 1885: Britain declared Bechuanaland a protectorate — Tswana content (protection from Boers, who'd been clashing since Great Trek 1835)
- High Commissioner Rey (1885): "We have no interest in the country... except as a road to the interior"
- 1889: Rhodes's BSAC started expanding north → created Northern/Southern Rhodesia (Zambia/Zimbabwe)
- By 1895: Rhodes had eye on Bechuanaland. Chiefs knew only disaster awaited under Rhodes
- Chiefs traveled to London via London Missionary Society to persuade Queen Victoria and Colonial Secretary Joseph Chamberlain
- Sept 11, 1895: first meeting with Chamberlain; then nationwide speaking tour (Windsor, Reading, Southampton, Leicester, Birmingham, Sheffield, Leeds, Halifax, Bradford, Bristol, Manchester, Liverpool)
- Meanwhile: Rhodes preparing disastrous Jameson Raid on Boer Transvaal → Chamberlain became more sympathetic to chiefs
- Nov 6, 1895: final meeting. Chamberlain-Khama dialogue about land, railway, law
- Chamberlain: "I will guard your interests"
- Edward Fairfield (Colonial Office): "Each of the three chiefs... shall have a country within which they shall live as hitherto under the protection of the Queen"
- Rhodes cabled: "I do object to being beaten by three canting natives"

### Tswana Political Institutions (pp. 458-460)
- By 19th century: unusual degree of political centralization AND pluralism for sub-Saharan Africa
- *Kgotla*: general assembly of adult males at chief's council place — frequent meetings, anyone could speak, assembly could overrule chief
- Isaac Schapera (anthropologist): "it is not unknown for the tribal assembly to overrule the wishes of the chief... the people are seldom afraid to speak openly and frankly"
- Chieftaincy: hereditary in appearance but open to talented candidates in practice — bad rulers removed
- Proverb: *kgosi ke kgosi ka morafe* — "The king is king by the grace of the people"
- John Comaroff (anthropologist): studied Rolong Tswana state — chieftaincy was "a matter of achievement" rationalized as inheritance after the fact

### Botswana Under British Rule (pp. 459-461)
- Tswana chiefs conceded railway construction but limited British intervention in governance
- Not opposed to railways (unlike Austria-Hungary/Russia) — understood economic value
- But realized British development wouldn't benefit Bechuanaland under colonial control
- Quett Masire (future president): enterprising farmer in 1950s, developed sorghum cultivation, found buyer in South Africa (Vryburg Milling)
- Masire tried to rent rail trucks at Lobatse station — refused; got white friend to intervene; station master quoted 4x the white rate
- Masire: "It was the practice of the whites, not just the laws prohibiting Africans from owning freehold land or holding trading licenses that kept blacks from developing enterprises"
- Bechuanaland marginal to British → no intense indirect rule (unlike Sierra Leone) → no vicious circle of colonial extraction
- Avoided South African-style colonial expansion into interior (no labor reservoirs, no mining)

### Botswana's Path to Independence (pp. 461-464)
- At independence (1966): one of poorest countries in world — 12 km of paved roads, 22 university graduates, 100 secondary school graduates
- Surrounded by hostile white regimes (South Africa, Namibia, Rhodesia)
- Yet became one of fastest-growing countries over next 45 years
- Now: highest per capita income in sub-Saharan Africa, comparable to Estonia, Hungary, Costa Rica
- How? Quickly developed inclusive economic AND political institutions after independence
- Democratic since independence, regular competitive elections, no civil war or military intervention
- Government enforced property rights, macroeconomic stability, inclusive market economy
- KEY PARALLELS WITH ENGLAND before Glorious Revolution:
  1. Political centralization (Tswana states had unusual degree of central authority)
  2. Pluralism (kgotla tradition, constrained chiefs, accountable leadership)
  3. Coalition favoring property rights (chiefs and elites owned cattle — private property even though land was communal)
- Independence led by Botswana Democratic Party (BDP), founded 1960 by Quett Masire and Seretse Khama
- Seretse Khama: grandson of King Khama III; name means "the clay that binds together"
- Most Tswana chiefs/elites joined BDP; no marketing board existed (British hadn't bothered)
- BDP quickly set up Botswana Meat Commission (1967) — unlike African marketing boards, this one DEVELOPED cattle economy: fences for foot-and-mouth, promoted exports
- Diamonds discovered under Ngwato land (Khama's homeland); before announcement, Khama changed law: all subsoil mineral rights vested in NATION, not tribe
- Diamond revenues → state building, bureaucracy, infrastructure, education
- In Sierra Leone: diamonds = "Blood Diamonds" fueling civil war. In Botswana: diamonds managed for national good
- Chieftaincy Act (1965) + Chieftaincy Amendment Act (1970): continued political centralization, gave state/president power over chiefs (land allocation, removal from office)
- Language policy: only Setswana + English in schools → ethnic homogeneity (1946 census showed Ngwato reserve only 20% pure Ngwato, many non-Tswana groups)
- Census stopped asking about ethnicity → "In Botswana everyone is Tswana"
- Leaders (Khama, Masire) chose to contest power via elections rather than subvert electoral system — critical difference from most sub-Saharan African independence leaders
- Contingent path of history worked in Botswana's favor — lucky that leaders were not Siaka Stevens or Mugabe types
- KEY: Botswana succeeded because of interplay between existing institutions (centralization + pluralism + property rights via cattle) and critical juncture (independence)

## PAGES 465-479: CHAPTER 14 (cont.) — Breaking the Mold

### The End of the Southern Extraction — Civil Rights (pp. 465-471)
- December 1, 1955: Rosa Parks arrested in Montgomery, Alabama for sitting in white section of Cleveland Avenue bus
- Fined $10 + $4 court fees. Parks was secretary of Montgomery NAACP chapter — not random
- Montgomery Bus Boycott: organized by Martin Luther King Jr., lasted until Dec 20, 1956
- Culminated in Supreme Court ruling: segregated buses unconstitutional
- By 1950s, economic logic of southern extraction was weakening:
  - Mass outmigration of blacks: 100,000/year in 1940s-50s (legacy of Great Depression + WWII)
  - Mechanization of cotton: 1950 almost all picked by hand; by 1960 nearly half mechanized in AL, LA, MS
  - Blacks became less indispensable to plantation owners → less reason for elites to fight for old extractive institutions
- Two forces combined: (1) blacks organizing against discrimination; (2) federal government (Supreme Court, Congress, executive) intervening
- Being part of United States was KEY — South subject to U.S. Constitution/federal law, unlike Guatemala where elites had free rein

### Federal Intervention (pp. 468-471)
- 1944: Supreme Court ruled white-only primary elections unconstitutional — opening salvo
- Literacy tests routinely manipulated — in Louisiana, white applicant judged literate after writing "FRDUM FOOF SPETGH" as answer about state constitution
- *Brown v. Board of Education* (1954): school segregation unconstitutional
- *Baker v. Carr* (1962): "one-person, one-vote" — ended malapportionment overrepresenting rural planter areas
- 1962 Ole Miss crisis: James Meredith (black air force veteran) admitted to University of Mississippi
  - Governor Ross Barnett publicly rejected court order on TV (Sept 13)
  - Citizens' Councils (formed Indianola, MS, 1954) organized opposition
  - Sept 30: 2,500 rioters vs. U.S. marshals; marshals came under fire; by 10 PM federal troops moved in
  - 20,000 troops + 11,000 National Guardsmen; 300 arrested
  - Meredith stayed protected by marshals + 300 soldiers; graduated
- Strom Thurmond: 1948 States' Rights Democratic candidate, carried 4 states (39 electoral votes)
  - Quote: "there's not enough troops in the army to force the Southern people to break down segregation and admit the nigra race into our theaters, into our swimming pools, into our homes, and into our churches"
- Civil Rights Act of 1957 → Civil Rights Act of 1964 (outlawed segregationist legislation)
  - Thurmond filibustered 1957 act for 24 hours 18 minutes (read Declaration of Independence, phone books)
- Voting Rights Act of 1965: literacy tests, poll taxes declared illegal; extended federal oversight into state elections
- Mississippi black voter registration: ~5% (1960) → 50% (1970); Alabama/South Carolina: ~10% → 50%

### Economic Transformation of the South (pp. 471-472)
- Before 1960s: blacks almost excluded from southern textile mills — ~5% of employees in 1960
- By 1970: 15%; by 1990: 25%
- Southern per capita income: ~50% of U.S. average in 1940 → gap basically vanished by 1990
- KEY: Critical juncture (civil rights + federal intervention) interacted with existing inclusive federal institutions to break vicious circle

### Rebirth in China (pp. 472-479)
- Mao overthrew Nationalists 1949; People's Republic Oct 1
- Highly extractive: one-party dictatorship, nationalized land, abolished property rights, executed landlords
- Communal farms; "work points" replaced wages; internal passports (1956)
- Five-year plans; Communist Party monopoly over agricultural sales → heavily taxed farmers
- Great Leap Forward (1958): "backyard" blast furnaces, people melted pots/pans/plows for scrap metal
  - Workers tending fields were making steel → famine; 20-40 million deaths; per capita income fell ~25%
- Deng Xiaoping: senior Communist, successful general
  - 1961: "No matter whether the cat is black or white, if it catches mice, it's a good cat"
  - May 16, 1966: Mao launched Cultural Revolution → Red Guards purged opponents
  - Mao: "This man Hitler was even more ferocious. The more ferocious, the better"
  - Deng labeled "number-two capitalist roader" — jailed 1967, exiled to Jiangxi 1969 (tractor factory)
  - Rehabilitated 1974; first vice-premier under Zhou Enlai
  - 1975: supervised 3 reform documents (material incentives, higher education, remove leftists)
  - April 5, 1976: Tiananmen protest (mourning Zhou Enlai) → Gang of Four blamed Deng → stripped again
- Gang of Four: Mao's wife Jiang Qing + 3 associates — wanted to continue Cultural Revolution
- Mao died September 1976 → critical juncture / power vacuum
- Three factions: Gang of Four; Hua Guofeng ("Two Whatevers"); Deng (reform economy, keep party)
- Hua Guofeng: "We will resolutely uphold whatever policy decisions Chairman Mao made"
- Within month of Mao's death: Hua arrested Gang of Four; reinstated Deng (March 1977)
- Deng outmaneuvered Hua: encouraged public criticism of Cultural Revolution, filled party with reformers
- September 1978: attacked "Two Whatevers" — correct approach = "seek truth from facts"
- Democracy Wall movement (1978): public complaints posted on wall in Beijing
- Hu Qiaomu (July 1978): firms need initiative, prices set by supply/demand, reduce state regulation
- Nov-Dec 1978: Third Plenum of 11th Central Committee — breakthrough
  - Focus: class struggle → economic modernization
  - "Household responsibility system" experiments (rolling back collective agriculture)
  - Cultural Revolution declared "great calamity"
- 1980: Hua stepped down (replaced by Zhao Ziyang); 1982: removed from Central Committee
- Sept 1985: almost complete reshuffle — 21/26 Politburo, 8/11 secretariat, 10/18 vice-premiers changed
- KEY ECONOMIC REFORMS:
  - 1983: household responsibility system universal → 1984 grain output 1/3 higher than 1978
  - 1985: mandatory state grain purchasing ended; agricultural price controls relaxed
  - Urban: state enterprises got autonomy; 14 "open cities" for foreign investment
  - Township Village Enterprises (TVEs): rural industries competing with state firms from 1979
  - Privatization waited until mid-1990s
- China broke the mold economically BUT political institutions remained extractive (Communist Party dictatorship)
- Highly contingent: Gang of Four losing was not inevitable; if they'd won, no sustained growth

### Chapter 14 Summary (pp. 479)
- Botswana, U.S. South, China = history is not destiny
- Despite vicious circle, extractive CAN be replaced by inclusive
- Requires: critical juncture + broad coalition + propitious existing institutions + luck

---

## CHAPTER 15: UNDERSTANDING PROSPERITY AND POVERTY

### Historical Origins (pp. 480-484)
- Huge differences in living standards are relatively recent — emerged over last 200 years
- 500 years ago: Mexico (Aztec Empire) was richer than polities to the north; US didn't pull ahead until 19th century
- South/North Korea: economically/culturally indistinguishable before division at 38th parallel after WWII
- Was it predetermined? No — theory needed to explain, not assume
- Book's theory operates on two levels:
  1. **Institutional interpretation of history**: distinction between extractive and inclusive economic/political institutions
  2. **How history shaped institutional trajectories**: institutional drift + critical junctures
- Inclusive economic institutions: enforce property rights, create level playing field, encourage investment in technology/skills
- Supported by inclusive political institutions: distribute power pluralistically, achieve centralization for law/order
- Extractive economic institutions: extract from many for benefit of few, fail to protect property rights
- Supported by extractive political institutions: concentrate power in few hands

### Growth Under Extractive Institutions (pp. 482-483)
- Extractive institutions NOT inconsistent with ALL growth — elites want growth too (more to extract)
- Extractive institutions with minimal political centralization CAN generate some growth
- BUT growth under extractive institutions will NOT be sustained, for two reasons:
  1. **Creative destruction**: sustained growth requires innovation, which replaces old with new — destabilizes power relations. Elites fear it, resist it → growth under extraction is ultimately short-lived
  2. **High stakes**: ability to benefit greatly at others' expense → many groups fight for control → political instability
- Vicious circle: extractive institutions persist and reproduce. Virtuous circle: inclusive institutions persist and strengthen
- Neither is absolute — some nations have broken the mold (Botswana, China, U.S. South)

### Institutional Drift and Critical Junctures (pp. 483-484)
- Institutional drift: like genetic drift — two similar societies slowly diverge through small, contingent differences in conflict outcomes
- Not necessarily cumulative (differences can appear and disappear, as in Roman Britain)
- But at critical junctures, small differences from institutional drift can lead to radical divergence
- Three major critical junctures: Black Death (14th century), Atlantic trade routes (post-1500), Industrial Revolution (18th-19th century)
- England's small differences (Crown couldn't monopolize trade; opposition groups existed) became decisive when Atlantic trade created enormous profit opportunities

### Why Peru Is Not Destined to Be Poor (pp. 485-486)
- At least three factors could have changed Peru's trajectory:
  1. North America was sparsely settled → attracted settlers who rebelled against elite (Virginia Company etc.); Peru had dense indigenous population → conquistadors exploited them. These populations could have been REVERSED — Inca civilization could have developed in Mississippi Valley instead
  2. Inca Empire might have resisted European colonization (as Japan responded to Commodore Perry) — no historical necessity for total conquest
  3. Most radically: not predetermined that Europeans would colonize at all — could have been Chinese or even Incas. Western Europe's advantage was itself contingent on feudalism's specific path, independent commercial cities, Black Death, etc.

### Theory's Predictive Limits (pp. 487-489)
- Theory where small differences + contingency are key → limited predictive power
- Few in 15th-16th century would have predicted England's breakthrough
- Few during Cultural Revolution would have predicted China's boom
- These are NOT shortcomings — they show that historical/geographic/cultural determinism is inadequate
- Theory still useful: explains broad differences, provides guidelines for which societies more likely to grow

### Broad Predictions (pp. 488-489)
- Vicious and virtuous circles → persistence: US/Western Europe will likely remain richer than sub-Saharan Africa, Middle East, Central America, SE Asia for 50-100+ years
- Within these broad patterns, some countries will break the mold
- Countries with NO political centralization (Somalia, Afghanistan) or collapsed states (Haiti) → unlikely to achieve growth or transition to inclusive institutions
- Countries likely to grow (under extractive institutions): those with some centralization — in Africa: Burundi, Ethiopia, Rwanda, Tanzania; in Latin America: Brazil, Chile, Mexico (centralization + nascent pluralism)
- Sustained growth unlikely in Colombia (insufficient centralization)
- Growth under extractive political institutions (like China) will NOT be sustained — will run out of steam

### Policy Recommendations: Caution (pp. 489-490)
- No easy recipes for transitioning from extractive to inclusive
- Iron law of oligarchy: extractive institutions re-create themselves under different guises (Egypt's Arab Spring doesn't guarantee inclusive outcome)
- Contingent path of history → hard to predict whether particular interplay of critical juncture + institutions will lead to inclusion
- Theory IS useful for identifying BAD policy advice based on wrong hypotheses
- Biggest current mistake: recommending "authoritarian growth" based on China

### The Irresistible Charm of Authoritarian Growth (pp. 490-494)
- Dai Guofang case: recognized China's urban boom in 1990s, started Jingsu Tieben Iron and Steel company in Changzhou (2003)
- March 2004: project stopped by Beijing; Dai arrested (never clearly explained why)
- Spent 5 years in jail/home detention; found guilty on minor charge 2009
- Real crime: starting large project competing with state-sponsored companies without approval of Communist Party higher-ups
- Chen Yun (Deng's close associate, architect of early reforms): "bird in a cage" analogy — economy is the bird, party's control is the cage; enlarge cage but never unlock it
- Jiang Zemin (1989, CCP general secretary): entrepreneurs are "self-employed traders and peddlers [who] cheat, embezzle, bribe and evade taxation"
- Throughout 1990s: private entrepreneurship greeted with suspicion, many entrepreneurs expropriated or jailed
- Chinese economist quote: "Big state companies can get involved in huge projects. But when private companies do so, especially in competition with the state, then trouble comes from every corners"
- Richard McGregor (journalist): red phone on desk of every major state company CEO — party calls with orders on investment, targets, personnel
- Party can shuffle/fire/promote chief executives of giant companies with little explanation

### China vs. Soviet Growth (pp. 493-494)
- Chinese growth resembles Soviet growth (1950s-60s): growth under extractive political institutions, facilitated by catching up
- Key differences: China's economic institutions more inclusive than Soviet Union's were; growth more diversified (not just armaments/heavy industry); Chinese entrepreneurs showing ingenuity
- But ALL growth under extractive political institutions will ultimately be limited
- Property rights not entirely secure; entrepreneurs regularly expropriated; labor mobility tightly regulated
- Only businesses with party cadre support dare venture into significant activity
- Business-party connection: lucrative for both sides — party-supported businesses get contracts, can expropriate land, violate regulations with impunity
- Those in the way can be jailed or murdered

### Will Growth Bring Democracy to China? (pp. 494)
- 1989 Tiananmen Square: hope that growth → democracy. Instead: tanks, massacre
- Political institutions became MORE extractive after Tiananmen; Zhao Ziyang (reformist CCP general secretary) purged, placed under house arrest 15+ years, public record gradually erased
- Party controls media including Internet: self-censorship + Orwellian monitoring apparatus
- Liu Xiaobo: government critic demanding democratization, imprisoned, awarded Nobel Peace Prize while still in prison
- Corruption story: son of CCP general secretary Hu Jintao accused (2009) → party blocked Chinese media AND selectively blocked NYT/Financial Times websites
- Creative destruction curtailed → will remain so until radical political reform
- Chinese growth per capita still fraction of US/Western Europe — catch-up growth feasible for a while
- Most likely scenario: CCP maintains tight grip for decades; growth with creative destruction never arrives; spectacular growth rates slowly evaporate
- NOT preordained: could be avoided if China transitions to inclusive political institutions before growth under extraction hits its limit
- Premier Wen Jiabao: warned economic growth will be "hampered" without political reform — authors consider this prescient
- "Authoritarian growth" appeals to rulers of extractive institutions: gives free rein to maintain/strengthen power while legitimizing extraction
- Growth under extractive institutions possible in many nations (Cambodia, Vietnam, Burundi, Ethiopia, Rwanda) but will not be sustained

## PAGES 495-509: CHAPTER 15 (cont.) — Understanding Prosperity and Poverty

### Critique of Modernization Theory (pp. 495-498)
- Seymour Martin Lipset's modernization theory: all societies, as they grow, headed toward modernity, democracy, inclusive institutions
- Thomas Friedman (postmodern version): once a country has enough McDonald's, democracy follows
- George H.W. Bush: "Trade freely with China and time is on our side" — but rapid US-China trade since mid-1980s has done little for Chinese democracy
- Iraq example: U.S. invasion optimism based on modernization theory (educated population, not too poor) → hopes dashed as chaos and civil war ensued
- Modernization theory is WRONG because:
  1. Rich nations with inclusive institutions grew BECAUSE of those institutions — causation runs from institutions to growth, not the reverse
  2. Authoritarian regimes that have grown rapidly over past 60-100 years have NOT become more democratic (contrary to Lipset's prediction)
  3. Growth under extractive institutions doesn't automatically undermine those institutions — elites often VIEW growth as SUPPORTING their regime
  4. Resource-driven growth (Gabon, Russia, Saudi Arabia, Venezuela) is unlikely to transform authoritarian regimes
- Historical counterexamples: Germany and Japan were among richest/most industrialized nations in early 20th century with well-educated populations → still succumbed to Nazism and militaristic expansionism
- Argentina: one of richest countries in 19th century, most educated in Latin America → democracy and pluralism were no more successful than elsewhere in Latin America
- THREE key takeaways on authoritarian growth:
  1. Growth under extractive political institutions (like China) will NOT translate into sustained growth
  2. Should NOT count on authoritarian growth leading to democracy (contra modernization theory)
  3. Authoritarian growth is neither desirable nor viable long-term → should NOT be endorsed by international community as template

### You Can't Engineer Prosperity (pp. 499-503)
- Ignorance hypothesis leads to "engineering" approach: teach rulers good economics → prosperity
- Ghana's Kofi Busia (1970s): obstacle was NOT ignorance but political incentives/constraints
- TWO flavors of engineering prosperity:
  1. **Washington Consensus** (IMF/World Bank): macro reforms (central bank independence, privatization, flexible exchange rates, capital account liberalization, anticorruption)
    - Problem: foisted on countries where politics continues as usual → reforms adopted but subverted/blunted
    - Zimbabwe example: declared central bank independent in 1995. Before: inflation ~20%. By 2002: 140%. By 2003: 600%. By 2007: 66,000%. By 2008: 230 MILLION percent
    - Central bank governor knew what happened to Sierra Leone's Sam Bangura — compliance was "the prudent choice for his personal health"
    - Argentina/Colombia: central bank independence coincided with EXPANSION of government spending (financed by borrowing)
  2. **Micro-market failure fixes** (fashionable now): address small market failures (education, health, etc.)
    - Seva Mandir NGO + economists: incentive scheme for nurse attendance in Udaipur, Rajasthan, India (2006)
    - Introduced time clocks — nurses stamp 3x/day. Initial sharp attendance increase
    - Within a year: local health administration deliberately undermined scheme — created "exempt days," broke time clocks, wouldn't cooperate with repairs
    - Health administrators were in cahoots with nurses — didn't want accountability
    - KEY: micro-market failures that are "easy to fix" may be illusory — the institutional structure creating them also prevents fixing them

### The Failure of Foreign Aid (pp. 503-507)
- Post-9/11 Afghanistan: Bonn Agreement (Dec 2001), Loya Jirga elected Karzai, billions poured in
- First tranche: commissioned airline for UN/international officials. Then hired few English-speaking bureaucrats and teachers as drivers/interpreters — paying multiples of Afghan salaries, draining state capacity
- Village shelter program example: multimillion-dollar program → 20% taken as UN head office costs in Geneva → subcontracted to NGO (another 20% for Brussels head office) → 3 more layers each taking ~20% → remaining money bought wood from western Iran → transported by Ismail Khan's trucking cartel at inflated prices → only oversize wooden beams arrived (too big, used as firewood)
- Studies estimate only 10-20% of aid reaches its target
- Decades of development aid: hundreds of billions paid to governments, much wasted in overhead/corruption → often propped up extractive regimes (e.g., Mobutu depended on Western aid to buy support)
- Foreign aid is NOT effective means of dealing with failure of nations — countries need inclusive institutions, not aid to extractive regimes
- Conditional aid (Millennium Challenge Accounts, George W. Bush): made aid dependent on quantitative improvements → countries failing conditions received as much aid as those meeting them; dictators won't dismantle extractive institutions for marginal additional aid
- Aid shouldn't cease entirely — humanitarian aid has value; some specific programs (building schools for girls in Afghanistan) have been genuine successes
- Even if only 10 cents of every dollar reaches the poor, "that is ten cents more than they had before"
- Better approach: structure aid to bring excluded groups into decision-making, empower broader population

### Empowerment: Brazil's Workers' Party (pp. 508-509)
- May 12, 1978: Scânia truck factory, São Bernardo, São Paulo state — workers put down tools at 7 AM
- Strikes banned since 1964 military coup (overthrew President João Goulart)
- Trigger: government caught fixing inflation figures (cost of living increase underestimated)
- Gilson Menezes (union organizer) called union; president was Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva ("Lula"), age 33
- Lula: "I think we can't separate economic and political factors... in struggling for wages, the working class won a political victory"
- Part of broader social reaction to decade and a half of military rule
- Fernando Henrique Cardoso (left-wing intellectual, future president, 1973): democracy requires "reactivation of civil society... professional associations, trade unions, churches, student organizations, study groups and debating circles, social movements" — broad coalition
- Late 1978: Lula began creating Workers' Party (Partido dos Trabalhadores)
- Aug 18, 1979: meeting in São Paulo — former opposition politicians, union leaders, students, intellectuals, 100+ diverse social movements
- Workers' Party launched at São Judas Tadeo restaurant, São Bernardo, October 1979
- Party not just for trade unionists — for ALL wage earners and the poor
- 1982: ran candidates in local elections, won 2 mayoral races
- Throughout 1980s: took over more local governments; by 1988 controlled 36 municipalities (São Paulo, Porto Alegre)
- 1989 (first free presidential election since coup): Lula got 16% first round, 44% in runoff against Fernando Collor
- Porto Alegre: Workers' Party introduced "participatory budgeting" after 1988 — ordinary citizens involved in spending priorities; became world model for local government accountability
- Massive improvements in public services and quality of life

### Brazil's Transformation (pp. 510-511)
- Lula defeated by Cardoso in 1994 and 1998; elected president 2002; Workers' Party in power since
- Since 1990: poverty fell from 45% to 30% (2006); inequality (which rose under military) fell sharply under Workers' Party
- Average years of schooling: 6 (1995) → 8 (2006)
- Brazil now part of BRIC nations — first Latin American country with real weight in international diplomacy
- KEY: Brazil's rise was NOT engineered by economists, international institutions, or foreign aid — it was the consequence of diverse groups courageously building inclusive political institutions from below

### Why Political Revolutions Fail or Succeed (pp. 511-512)
- History littered with reform movements that succumbed to iron law of oligarchy
- Bolshevik Revolution: promised replacing exploitation with justice → created even more repressive extractive institutions
- Similar: China, Cuba, Vietnam (communist); Egypt under Nasser → Mubarak's corruption; Zimbabwe → Mugabe
- What distinguishes SUCCESSFUL political revolutions (England 1688, France 1789, North American colonies, Botswana, Brazil)?
  - They EMPOWERED a broad cross-section of society
  - Pluralism = political power widely held, not seized by narrow group
  - This requires a PROCESS of empowerment — broad coalition mobilization
- Glorious Revolution: broad coalition (merchants, industrialists, gentry, dissident aristocracy)
- French Revolution: broad segment rose against ancien regime; Terror was a pitfall but ultimately overcome
- Brazil: Workers' Party fused trade unions + intellectuals + local social movements + opposition politicians → participatory governance → empowerment from below, not revolution from above

### Brazil vs. Venezuela (pp. 513)
- Venezuela: transitioned to democracy in 1958 BUT without grassroots empowerment
- No pluralistic distribution of power — corrupt politics, patronage networks persisted
- Voters supported Hugo Chávez because he alone seemed able to stand up to established elites
- Result: Venezuela still languishes under extractive institutions; Brazil broke the mold

### What Facilitates Empowerment? (pp. 513-514)
- No recipe, but some obvious factors:
  1. **Centralized order**: so challenging regimes doesn't cause immediate descent into lawlessness
  2. **Preexisting pluralistic institutions**: even rudimentary (like Tswana kgotla) → broad coalitions can form and endure
  3. **Civil society institutions**: coordinate demands of population, prevent movements from being crushed or captured
- Many of these factors are historically predetermined and change slowly
- Brazilian case shows civil society can be built from ground up, but slowly and with uncertain success

### The Role of Media (pp. 514-515)
- Media: transformative role in empowerment — information needed to coordinate opposition and expose abuses
- Pamphlets/books in Glorious Revolution, French Revolution, 19th-century British democratization
- Modern: blogs, Facebook, Twitter → Iranian opposition (2009 election), Arab Spring protests
- Authoritarian regimes understand this:
  - Alberto Fujimori (Peru): Valdimiro Montesinos (intelligence chief) videotaped bribes as blackmail
  - Montesinos's records: Supreme Court judge = $5,000-$10,000/month; politicians = similar; BUT newspapers/TV stations = MILLIONS ($9 million on one occasion, $10 million on another, $1 million to mainstream newspaper, $3,000-$8,000 per headline in others)
  - General Bello (Montesinos's henchman): "If we do not control the television we do not do anything"
- China's extractive institutions also depend crucially on media control
- Chinese commentator: "To uphold the leadership of the Party in political reform, three principles must be followed: that the Party controls the armed forces; the Party controls cadres; and the Party controls the news"

### Final Chapter Conclusion (pp. 515-516)
- Free media and new communication technology help only at the margins
- Meaningful change: broad segment of society must mobilize, organize for political change — NOT for sectarian reasons or to seize extractive institutions, but to TRANSFORM them into inclusive ones
- Whether this succeeds depends on history of economic/political institutions, small differences, and the contingent path of history

