## PAGES 101-120: CHAPTERS 3 (cont.) and 4

### Losers from Creative Destruction (pp. 101-103)
- Luddites: John Kay (flying shuttle, 1733) house burned 1753; James Hargreaves (spinning jenny) similar treatment — but Luddites lacked political power to block industrialization
- In England: aristocratic opposition muted; in Austro-Hungarian and Russian empires absolutist monarchs/aristocrats blocked industrialization → economies stalled
- Elites under absolutism won't voluntarily create pluralism — only way to change is to FORCE the elite

### The Long Agony of the Congo (pp. 103-108)
- Kingdom of Kongo: elite wealth from slave plantations around São Salvador + arbitrary taxation
- One tax collected every time the king's beret fell off
- Kongolese MOVED VILLAGES AWAY from roads to escape plunder/slave traders — engines of prosperity working in reverse
- Government = biggest threat to property and human rights; labor market did not exist due to slavery
- Long-distance trade controlled by king; writing introduced but not spread to population
- Absolutist political institutions: standing army of 5,000 with core of 500 musketeers
- Why elite wouldn't reform: (1) undermine slave trade/plantation wealth; (2) who would believe king abolishing slavery while commanding 500 musketeers?
- European "scramble for Africa" brought even worse extractive institutions (Belgian King Leopold II)
- After independence 1960: same pattern. Mobutu's Zairianization program 1973 (mass expropriation)
- Mobutu presided over noncentralized state — needed foreign help to stop Katanga/Kasai seceding
- In sub-Saharan Africa: infighting to control extractive institutions destroyed state centralization

### Growth Under Extractive Political Institutions (pp. 108-112)
#### Type 1: Elite directly allocates resources to high-productivity activities
- Caribbean Islands (16th-18th c.): slaves on plantations, yet islands among richest (sugar). Stagnated when needed to shift
- Soviet Union: First Five-Year Plan (1928) through 1970s — state moved resources from agriculture to industry

#### Type 2: Extractive political institutions permit somewhat inclusive economic institutions
- South Korea under Park: military coup 1961 but US-supported inclusive economy. Regime felt secure enough to promote growth
- South Korea transitioned to inclusive political institutions in 1980s:
  - Economic elite had little to gain from military dominance; relative income equality → less fear from pluralism
  - Park assassinated 1979 → Chun Doo-hwan → Roh Tae-woo → democracy after 1992
- No such transition in Soviet Union → collapse
- China today: growth under extractive institutions under state/party control; transition less likely

#### Political Centralization Is Key:
- Without centralization, growth under extractive institutions impossible
- Major dividing line = degree of centralization. Sub-Saharan Africa without it can't achieve even limited growth

#### Limits: growth under extractive institutions usually NOT sustained, NOT with creative destruction
- State resource reallocation by fiat = intrinsically limited (USSR 1970s)
- Extractive institutions create infighting over concentrated wealth/power → civil wars → state collapse
- When growth under extractive political + inclusive economic: danger economic institutions become extractive → growth stops

## CHAPTER 4: SMALL DIFFERENCES AND CRITICAL JUNCTURES (pp. 114-)

### The World the Plague Created (pp. 114-120)
- 1346: Black Death reached Tana (mouth of River Don, Black Sea). From China via Silk Road traders (fleas on rats)
- Spread by Genoese traders across Mediterranean. 1347: Constantinople. Spring 1348: France, N. Africa, Italy
- Wiped out ~HALF the population. Boccaccio (Florence): "death occurred within three days"
- England: Edward III asked Archbishop of Canterbury to organize prayers (Aug 1348)
- Also had socially, economically, politically transformative impact

#### Feudal Order:
- 14th century: king → lords (land for military service) → serfs (tied to land, unpaid labor, fines/taxes, couldn't move)
- Lord was judge, jury, police. Highly extractive: wealth from many peasants to few lords

#### Western Europe (England) — Feudalism Weakened:
- Labor scarcity → peasants demanded change. Eynsham Abbey: "scarcely two tenants remained" after 1349 → abbot negotiated
- Wages rose. Statute of Laborers (1351): tried to fix wages at 1347 levels, imprison workers who left
- DIDN'T WORK: 1381 Peasants' Revolt (Wat Tyler) captured most of London. Tyler executed but Statute abandoned
- Feudal labor dwindled; inclusive labor market emerged; wages rose

#### Eastern Europe — Second Serfdom (OPPOSITE outcome):
- Same plague, labor scarcity, demands — but lords had GREATER incentive to keep labor extractive
- Workers in England had sufficient power; in East, lords prevailed. Towns weaker, peasants less organized
- Second Serfdom = more intense than early Middle Ages:
  - Korczyn, Poland: all work paid (1533) → nearly half unpaid (1600)
  - Mecklenberg: few days/year (1500) → 1 day/week (1550) → 3 days/week (1600)
  - Hungary: landlord control of land (1514) → 1→2→3 days/week by end of century; serfs = 90% of rural population
- By 1600: West free of feudal dues in market economy; East = coerced serfs growing food for Western demand

#### CRITICAL JUNCTURE: major event disrupting existing balance. Double-edged: can break extractive cycle (England) OR intensify it (Eastern Second Serfdom). Small initial differences amplified enormously.

### The Making of Inclusive Institutions (pp. 119-120)
- England unique: sustained growth preceded by political revolution. NOT consensus — intense conflict
- English Civil War (1642-1651) and Glorious Revolution (1688)
- Glorious Revolution: limited king's power → Parliament; opened political system to broad cross section
- Created world's first inclusive political institutions; accelerated centralization
- After Glorious Revolution:
  - Enforced property rights including patents; law for ALL citizens; arbitrary taxation ceased; monopolies abolished
  - State promoted mercantile activities; used navy to defend trade; rationalized property rights → infrastructure
- These foundations → Industrial Revolution:
  - Market created profitable opportunities for technologies; inclusive markets allocated talent; relied on education
  - NOT coincidence IR started few decades after Glorious Revolution
  - Inventors: James Watt (steam engine), Richard Trevithick (steam locomotive), Richard Arkwright (spinning frame), Isambard Kingdom Brunel (steamships)

### Watt and Parliament (p. 121)
- 1775: Watt renewed patent via Act of Parliament. Letter to father revealed: motivated by market demand + Parliament responsive to innovators

### Small Differences That Matter (pp. 122-126)
- 1588: England/France/Spain all absolutist, all battling assemblies. KEY: English Parliament had taxation power; Estates-General didn't
- Spain: American gold funded Crown; trade monopolized. England: Elizabeth less independent → Parliament demanded concessions → won
- After 1600: Elizabeth couldn't monopolize Atlantic trade → wealthy merchants with few Crown links → demanded institutional changes → critical role in Civil War and Glorious Revolution
- France: Fronde Rebellion (1648-52) but opponents less wealthy/numerous than in England

### Critical Junctures and Institutional Drift (pp. 124-128)
- Poland-Lithuania: Szlachta elite introduced elections for kings — "absolutism of an elite." Russia: Peter the Great's absolutism more intense than Louis XIV
- Map 8: serfdom in 1800 — Eastern dark, Western light. Divergence began at Black Death 1346
- INSTITUTIONAL DRIFT: like genetic drift — similar societies drift apart through cumulative small differences. Consequential during critical junctures

### Contingent Path of History (pp. 128-132)
- English navy relied on privateers, much weaker than Spanish. 1588 Armada: bad weather + Sidonia's mistakes → English won against all odds → Atlantic opened
- WITHOUT this unlikely victory: Glorious Revolution "would never have got moving"
- Michels: "iron law of oligarchy" — revolutions often replace one tyranny with another
- Post-WWII decolonization: most govts intensified extraction. Botswana = rare exception
- Venice: inclusive medieval institutions → ultimately transformed into extractive under narrow elite

### Understanding the Lay of the Land (pp. 133-140)
- Settler colonies (US/Canada/Australia): IR spread rapidly
- Western Europe: French Revolution → converged with England; Eastern Europe diverged
- Latin America: Spanish extractive institutions endured. Argentina/Chile fared better (neglected by Spain). Poorest Argentina = northwest (Spanish colonial economy area)
- Africa: least able for IR. Centralized states late/tenuous. Shares trajectory with Afghanistan/Haiti/Nepal. Slave trade made institutions MORE extractive. European colonialism reversed modernization. Colonial legacy worse in 1960s than at start
- Botswana: King Khama modernized; Seretse Khama (studied England 1940s, married Ruth Williams → banned by South Africa → resigned kingship) adapted institutions. "Extraordinary man, uninterested in personal wealth"
- China: Ming emperors turned from oceans fearing creative destruction. India: rigid caste + Mughal absolutism → English colony
- Japan vs China: Tokugawa's tenuous hold on feudal domains (vs China's stronger absolutism) → 1853 Perry → Japan: Meiji Restoration → growth; China: absolutism continued
- Middle East: 500 years Ottoman. Absolutist, no private property in land, "farmed" taxes (collectors took 1/2 to 2/3). Palestine peasants fled to mountains. Urban guilds/monopolies. Reform thwarted by fear of creative destruction. Ottoman → European colonization after 1918 → extractive institutions taken over by elites. Non-oil ME = income similar to poor Latin America
